OR]\n* Shortridge, James R. ''The Middle West: Its Meaning in American Culture'' (1989)\n* Sisson, Richard, Christian Zacher, and Andrew Cayton, eds. ''The American Midwest: An Interpretive Encyclopedia'' (Indiana University Press, 2006), 1916 pp of articles by scholars on all topics covering the 12 states\n* Slade, Joseph W. and Judith Lee. ''The Midwest: The Greenwood Encyclopedia of American Regional Cultures'' (2004)\n* Sleeper-Smith, Susan. ''Indigenous Prosperity and American Conquest: Indian Women of the Ohio River Valley, 1690-1792'' (The Omohundro Institute of Early American History and Culture; 2018)\n* [[Jon C. Teaford|Teaford, Jon C.]] ''Cities of the Heartland: The Rise and Fall of the Industrial Midwest'' (1993)\n* Tucker, Spencer, ed. ''American Civil War: A State-by-State Encyclopedia'' (2 vol., 2015) 1019pp [https://www.amazon.com/dp/1598845284/ excerpt]\n*White, Richard. ''The Middle Ground: Indians, Empires, and Republics in the Great Lakes Region, 1650-1815'' (Cambridge University Press; 1991)\n* Wuthnow, Robert. ''Remaking the Heartland: Middle America Since the 1950s'' (Princeton University Press; 2011) 358 pages\n\n=== Historiography ===\n* Brown, David S. ''Beyond the Frontier: The Midwestern Voice in American Historical Writing'' (2009)\n* Good, David F. \"American History through a Midwestern Lens\". ''Wirtschaft und Gesellschaft'' 38.2 (2012): 435+ [http://wug.akwien.at/WUG_Archiv/2012_38_2/2012_38_2_0435.pdf online]\n* Lauck, Jon K. ''The Lost Region: Toward a Revival of Midwestern History'' (University of Iowa Press; 2013) 166 pages; criticizes the neglect of the Midwest in contemporary historiography and argues for a revival of attention\n* Lauck, Jon K. \"Trump and The Midwest: The 2016 Presidential Election and The Avenues of Midwestern Historiography.\" ''Studies in Midwestern History'' 3.1 (2017): 1-24.  [https://scholarworks.gvsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1021&context=midwesternhistory  online]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://unp-bookworm.unl.edu/product/Midwest-History-Association,678087.aspx issues of ''Middle West Review'']\n* [https://scholarworks.gvsu.edu/midwesternhistory/ The Midwest History Association, scholarly association that published ''Middle West Review'']\n{{Wikivoyage|Midwest (United States of America)}}\n* [http://www.umvphotoarchive.org/ Archives of photo images, upper Midwest]\n\n{{Regions of the world}}\n{{Regions of the United States}}\n{{United States topics}}\n\n[[Category:Midwestern United States| ]]\n[[Category:Census regions of the United States]]\n[[Category:Regions of the United States]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1880s]]\n", "name_user": "2601:441:8580:3db0:c1bf:d5fb:efd6:5639", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midwestern_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Punjab Irrigation Department", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani irrigation department}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{primary sources|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Punjab Irrigation Department\n| logo = Pk)punjab.gif\n| type = Government organization\n| industry = Water Resource Management\n| hq_location_city = Lahore\n| area_served = 21 Million Acres\n| services = Water Resource Management\n| num_employees = 35,000\n| divisions = 6 Operational Zones - Lahore, Faisalabad, Multan, Sargodha, Bahawalpur and DG Khan\n| homepage = https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/\n}}\n\n'''Punjab Irrigation Department ('''{{Lang-ur|\u067e\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u062d\u06a9\u0645\u06c1 \u0622\u0628 \u067e\u0627\u0634\u06cc}}), Pakistan, is a provincial irrigation department in the Punjab province of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.punjab.gov.pk/provincial_departments|title=Punjab Portal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Punjab Irrigation Department irrigates 21 million acres of agricultural land in Punjab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/02/15/punjab-irrigation-mr-backlog-reaches-rs600-billion/|title=Punjab irrigation M&R backlog reaches Rs600 billion|last=Farooqi|first=Monem|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari|Muhammad Mohsin Leghari]], an MPA from Rajanpur, is the Minister for Irrigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pap.gov.pk/members/profile/en/21/1534|title=Muhammad Mohsin Leghari|last=|first=|date=|website=Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Secretary Irrigation to the government of the Punjab is the administrative head of the department.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Balloki Sulemanki Link Canal.jpg|thumb|Balloki Sulemanki Link Canal Head Regulator]]\nThe Indus Basin has a long history of irrigation dating back to 4000 year old Indus valley civilization in Harrapa and Mohenjodaro settlements.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alam|first=U|date=|title=Irrigation in the Indus basin: A history of unsustainability?|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/250142704|journal=Water Science and Technology Water Supply|volume=7|pages=|via=Researchgate}}</ref> At the time irrigation in the region was done mainly through inundation canals.  The history of modern Punjab Irrigation Department can be traced back to the establishment of 5 major canals in the region in early 20th century when the British built Lower Chenab Canal, Lower Jhelum Canal, Upper Jhelum Canal, Upper Chenab Canal and Lower [[Bari Doab]] Canal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Douie|first=James|title=The Punjab Canal Colonies|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Arts|volume=62|issue=3210|pages=611\u2013623|jstor=41341616|year=1914}}</ref>\n\nThe Indus Waters Treaty which was signed between India and Pakistan in 1960 was a major watershed in the history of development of irrigation infrastructure in the province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/region/sar/brief/fact-sheet-the-indus-waters-treaty-1960-and-the-world-bank|title=Fact Sheet: The Indus Waters Treaty 1960 and the Role of the World Bank|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2018|website=The World Bank|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> The treaty gave the rights of the three eastern rivers of the Indus basin namely Ravi, Sutlej and Beas to India and thus necessitated the construction of inter river link canals to haul water from Indus, Jhelum and Chenab to the eastern parts of the province. It was after this treaty that Pakistan built Tarbela and Mangla reservoirs to store monsoon water for winter months to continue to irrigate the fields year round.   \n\nThe second major development post independence in the history of irrigation in Punjab was 1991 Water Accord between all the four provinces of Pakistan. This accord gave Punjab province 55.94 million acre feet of water share annually for its irrigation and drinking usages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pakirsa.gov.pk/WAA.aspx|title=Indus River System Authority|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> It is with this share that the Punjab Irrigation Department caters to its 21 million acres of command area in the province.\n\n<br />\n\n== Services ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department is responsible for delivering the following services in the province:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1015|title=List of Services|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Provision of irrigation supplies to farmers\n*Construction, maintenance and operation of irrigation infrastructure\n* Flood planning and management\n* Basic and applied research in hydraulics, groundwater and land reclamation\n* Construction of reservoirs\n* Vertical and surface drainage\n*Management of workshop and machinery pool\n\n== Barrages ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department Manages the following barrages:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/819561468078530414/pdf/Punjab0Barrage1ect00PID010PAD0Stage.pdf|title=PUNJAB BARRAGE REHABILITATION & MODERNIZATION PROJECT|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n#[[Jinnah Barrage|Jinnah Barrage on River Indus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jinnah_Barrage|title=Jinnah Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Taunsa Barrage]] on River Indus <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taunsa_Barrage|title=Taunsa Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Rasul Barrage]] on River Jhelum <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rasul_Barrage|title=Rasul Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#Marala Headworks on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marala_Headworks|title=Marala Headworks|last=|first=|date=March 15, 2020|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Qadirabad Barrage on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/project-documents/49038/49038-001-iee-01.pdf|title=Remodeling of LMB of Qadirabad Barrage in Critical Reaches|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Khanki Headworks|New Khanki Barrage]] River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khanki_Headworks|title=Khanki Headworks|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Balloki Barrage on River Ravi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lbdcip.irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Lower Bari Doab Canal Improvement Project (LBDCIP)|last=|first=|date=|website=Lower Bari Doab Canal Improvement Project (LBDCIP)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Trimmu Barrage]] on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trimmu_Barrage|title=Trimmu Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Sidhnai Barrage on River Ravi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unesco.org.pk/ns/documents/Workshop_Workbook/Session_5/9_Barrage-(Sidhnai).pdf|title=Flood Fighting Plan 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=UNESCO Office in Islamabad|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Islam Barrage]] on River Sutlej <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam_Barrage|title=Islam Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Sulemanki Headworks|Suleimanki Barrage]] on River Sutlej<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulemanki_Headworks|title=Sulemanki Headworks|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Panjnad Barrage on River Indus<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1444136|title=Panjnad headworks rehabilitation project begins|last=Gill|first=Majeed|date=7 November 2018|work=Dawn|access-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Irrigation network.jpg|thumb|Main Canals and barrages in Punjab]]\n<br />\n== Zones ==\nFor the purpose of administration and management the Punjab irrigation system is divided into the following 6 operational zones:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/#|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Lahore Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Lahore Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1029|title=Introduction Of Lahore Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Irrigation Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Chenab Canal Circle\n* Depalpur Canal Circle\n* Link Canal Circle\n* Lahore Drainage Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n[[File:Lower Bari Doab canal.jpg|thumb|Lower Bari Doab Canal]]\n\n==== Faisalabad Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Faisalabad Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1034|title=Introduction Of Faisalabad Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Lower Chenab Canal East Circle\n* Lower Chenab Canal West Circle\n* Drainage Circle\n* Qadirabad Balloki Link Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n==== Sargodha Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Sargodha Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1024|title=Introduction of Sargodha Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Irrigation Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Jhelum Canal Circle\n* Lower Jhelum Canal Circle\n* Thal Canal Circle\n* Drainage Circle\n\n==== Multan Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Multan Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1039|title=Introduction Of Multan Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Nilibar Circle\n* Haveli Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n* Mailsi Canal Circle\n\n==== Bahawalpur Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Bahawalpur Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1|title=Introduction of Bahawalpur Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bahawalpur Canal Circle\n* Bahawalnagar Canal Circle\n* Rahimyarkhan Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n==== DG Khan Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Dera Ghazi Khan Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1044|title=Introduction Of D G Khan Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Derajat Circle\n* Muzaffargarh Canal Circle\n* Project Circle \n\nEach operational zone is headed by a chief engineer and each circle is headed by a superintending engineer and they are supported by an extended team of executive engineers, sub-divisional officers, sub-engineers, mates and baildars. In addition to operational zones, the department has following zones for overall planning and management of irrigation operations:\n\n* Planning and Review Zone  \n* Drainage and Flood zone \n* Research zone \n* Development zone  \n\nPunjab Irrigation Department also manages Government Engineering Academy Punjab which provides pre-service and in-service training to irrigation engineers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://geap.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Government Engineering Academy Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Service Delivery ===\nPunjab Irrigation Department delivers irrigation supplies to farmers through 51,990 outlets in its system of 24 main canals and distribution canals spanning 22,700 kilometers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pide.org.pk/pdf/Rural/water_and_irrigation(Khalid_Riaz).pdf|title=Water and Irrigation in Punjab|last=Riaz|first=Khalid|date=|website=Pakistan Institute of Development Economics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Head Office Building.jpg|alt=The main secretariat of Punjab Irrigation Department in Old Anarkali, Lahore|thumb|Secretariat of Irrigation Department]]\nThe Punjab Irrigation Department has its head office in [[Old Anarkali]], Lahore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Punjab Irrigation Department has complaint hotline 0800 11 333 for registration of complaints regarding irrigation supply issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://imis.irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Program Monitoring and Implementation Unit|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Daily canal discharges at all the canals in the entire system can be checked at the official website of the department.<ref>https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/</ref>   \n\n==Units==\nFor the purpose of management of various projects and institutional reforms the Punjab Irrigation Department has established the following Units:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Program Monitoring and Implementation Unit\n* Strategic Planning and Reforms Unit\n* Project Management Office (Canals)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1073|title=Project Management Office Canals|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Projects Management Office (Barrages)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmo-pb.gop.pk/pages/index.php|title=PMO Punjab Barrages|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Flood Risk Assessment Unit\n* Hydraulic Safety Structure Evaluation Unit\n* Program Implementation Unit\n\n== Laws and policies ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department functions under [https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/xbdYzzLgub7806TxhY3IPm5QZmfhOBdiHchhQx4biiL4BYvuaP8qm3aBqMgNF2W3rv2F7jzc9qtf9OTtahmJlw-- Canal and Drainage Act 1873] which was introduced to regulate irrigation, navigation and drainage of provincial territories. The purpose of this act is that the Provincial Government is entitled to use and control for public purposes, the water of all rivers and streams flowing in natural channels, and of all lake and other natural collections of still water in said territories<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecolex.org/details/legislation/canal-and-drainage-act-1873-act-viii-of-1873-lex-faoc064507/|title=Canal and Drainage Act, 1873 (Act VIII of 1873)|last=|first=|date=|website=ECOLEX|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. An amendment was made in Canal and Drainage Act in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/nZOfE1HY0TfvbiWVPJ0LK7orZSrwQj60DkViPE4WbrYUQQYyFP~YnbyRc6CKcbFOzUBpFDaYycYs3xwRMefxiw--|title=CANAL AND DRAINAGE (AMENDMENT) ACT 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Code|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. In 2019, the Government introduced Punjab Water Act 2019 to regulate the usage of surface and groundwater in the province<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/nIKGkzRRTKQ2T2fiRi5.at0Lxzstpqigttf4DpBFajVEC2AyJADmKH5.TsrG27KP7jXjXGobpfikCY654X5Ozw--|title=Punjab Water Act 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Codes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== Major developments ==\n[[File:Khanki Barrage, Punjab.jpg|thumb|New Khanki Barrage in Punjab, Pakistan]]\nIn 2010-11 completed the Taunsa Barrage rehabilitation and modernization project with cost of Rs. 11 billion rupees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.std.com.pk/fulltext/?doi=std.2014.127.131|title=Rehabilitated Taunsa Barrage: Prospects and Concerns|last=Chaudary|first=Zulfiqar|date=|website=Science and Technology Development|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Punjab Irrigation Department Completed the  Punjab Irrigation completed the construction of New Khanki Barrage in August 2017 which replaced the old [[Khanki Headworks]] which irrigated 3.03 million acres of fertile land in 8 districts of central Punjab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/12-May-2019/descon-to-hand-over-new-khanki-barrage-to-irrigation-dept-in-june|title=Descon to hand over New Khanki Barrage to Irrigation Dept in June|last=Gilani|first=Iqtidar|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPunjab Irrigation Department has, in December 2019, inaugurated the construction of Jalalpur Irrigation Canal System.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/589820-jalalpur-canal-to-benefit-people-cm-usman-buzdar|title=Jalalpur Canal to benefit people: CM Usman Buzdar|last=|first=|date=28 December 2019|work=The News|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The 117 kilometer long canal will originate from River Jhelum at Rasul Barrage and, along with its branches, will irrigate 1,70,000 acres of arid land in Districts of Jhelum and Khushab. The Department has also initiated works on Dadocha Dam which will supply 35 million gallons of drinking per day to the people of Rawalpindi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1525513|title=Irrigation dept claims credit for executing key projects in 2019|last=Mehmood|first=Amjad|date=1 January 2020|work=Dawn|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to this civil works on projects like Rehabilitation of Trimmu and Panjnad Barrages, rehabilitation of Trimmu-Sidhnai Canal, SMB Link Canal, Ahmadpur Branch and Eastern Sadiqia Canal are also underway and expected to be completed by 2022.   \n\nOn 22 May 2019, [[Punjab Khal Panchayat Authority]] was established under the Punjab Khal Panchayat Ordinance 2019 to ensure implementation of [[Warabandi system|warabandi]] minimizing the water disputes and distribution.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1484382|title=PIDA abolished: Irrigation dept takes control of canals, watercourses|date=May 25, 2019|work=Dawn|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/11/21/546246/pa-passes-punjab-water-bill-2019-amid-oppositions-boycott/|title=PA passes Punjab Water Bill 2019 amid opposition\u2019s boycott|date=November 21, 2019|work=Business Recorder|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This authority replaced the erstwhile Punjab Irrigation and Drainage Authority (PIDA).     \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}{{Pakistani water locks}}{{Waters of Pakistan}}{{Irrigation by country}}\n[[Category:Government of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Irrigation in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Departments of Government of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani irrigation department}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{primary sources|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Punjab Irrigation Department\n| logo = Pk)punjab.gif\n| type = Government organization\n| industry = Water Resource Management\n| hq_location_city = Lahore\n| area_served = 21 Million Acres\n| services = Water Resource Management\n| num_employees = 35,000\n| divisions = 6 Operational Zones - Lahore, Faisalabad, Multan, Sargodha, Bahawalpur and DG Khan\n| homepage = https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/\n}}\n\n'''Punjab Irrigation Department ('''{{Lang-ur|\u067e\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0628 \u0645\u062d\u06a9\u0645\u06c1 \u0622\u0628 \u067e\u0627\u0634\u06cc}}), Pakistan, is a provincial irrigation department in the Punjab province of Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.punjab.gov.pk/provincial_departments|title=Punjab Portal|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Punjab Irrigation Department irrigates 21 million acres of agricultural land in Punjab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/02/15/punjab-irrigation-mr-backlog-reaches-rs600-billion/|title=Punjab irrigation M&R backlog reaches Rs600 billion|last=Farooqi|first=Monem|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Mr. [[Muhammad Mohsin Khan Leghari|Muhammad Mohsin Leghari]], an MPA from Rajanpur, is the Minister for Irrigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pap.gov.pk/members/profile/en/21/1534|title=Muhammad Mohsin Leghari|last=|first=|date=|website=Provincial Assembly of the Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Secretary Irrigation to the government of the Punjab is the administrative head of the department.    \n\n== History ==\n[[File:Balloki Sulemanki Link Canal.jpg|thumb|Balloki Sulemanki Link Canal Head Regulator]]\nThe Indus Basin has a long history of irrigation dating back to 4000 year old Indus valley civilization in Harrapa and Mohenjodaro settlements.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alam|first=U|date=|title=Irrigation in the Indus basin: A history of unsustainability?|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/250142704|journal=Water Science and Technology Water Supply|volume=7|pages=|via=Researchgate}}</ref> At the time irrigation in the region was done mainly through inundation canals.  The history of modern Punjab Irrigation Department can be traced back to the establishment of 5 major canals in the region in early 20th century when the British built Lower Chenab Canal, Lower Jhelum Canal, Upper Jhelum Canal, Upper Chenab Canal and Lower [[Bari Doab]] Canal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Douie|first=James|title=The Punjab Canal Colonies|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Arts|volume=62|issue=3210|pages=611\u2013623|jstor=41341616|year=1914}}</ref>\n\nThe Indus Waters Treaty which was signed between India and Pakistan in 1960 was a major watershed in the history of development of irrigation infrastructure in the province.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/region/sar/brief/fact-sheet-the-indus-waters-treaty-1960-and-the-world-bank|title=Fact Sheet: The Indus Waters Treaty 1960 and the Role of the World Bank|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2018|website=The World Bank|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> The treaty gave the rights of the three eastern rivers of the Indus basin namely Ravi, Sutlej and Beas to India and thus necessitated the construction of inter river link canals to haul water from Indus, Jhelum and Chenab to the eastern parts of the province. It was after this treaty that Pakistan built Tarbela and Mangla reservoirs to store monsoon water for winter months to continue to irrigate the fields year round.   \n\nThe second major development post independence in the history of irrigation in Punjab was 1991 Water Accord between all the four provinces of Pakistan. This accord gave Punjab province 55.94 million acre feet of water share annually for its irrigation and drinking usages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pakirsa.gov.pk/WAA.aspx|title=Indus River System Authority|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 4, 2020}}</ref> It is with this share that the Punjab Irrigation Department caters to its 21 million acres of command area in the province.\n\n<br />\n\n== Services ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department is responsible for delivering the following services in the province:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1015|title=List of Services|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Provision of irrigation supplies to farmers\n*Construction, maintenance and operation of irrigation infrastructure\n* Flood planning and management\n* Basic and applied research in hydraulics, groundwater and land reclamation\n* Construction of reservoirs\n* Vertical and surface drainage\n*Management of workshop and machinery pool\n\n== Barrages ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department Manages the following barrages:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/819561468078530414/pdf/Punjab0Barrage1ect00PID010PAD0Stage.pdf|title=PUNJAB BARRAGE REHABILITATION & MODERNIZATION PROJECT|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n#[[Jinnah Barrage|Jinnah Barrage on River Indus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jinnah_Barrage|title=Jinnah Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Taunsa Barrage]] on River Indus <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taunsa_Barrage|title=Taunsa Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Rasul Barrage]] on River Jhelum <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rasul_Barrage|title=Rasul Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#Marala Headworks on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marala_Headworks|title=Marala Headworks|last=|first=|date=March 15, 2020|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Qadirabad Barrage on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/project-documents/49038/49038-001-iee-01.pdf|title=Remodeling of LMB of Qadirabad Barrage in Critical Reaches|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Khanki Headworks|New Khanki Barrage]] River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khanki_Headworks|title=Khanki Headworks|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Balloki Barrage on River Ravi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lbdcip.irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Lower Bari Doab Canal Improvement Project (LBDCIP)|last=|first=|date=|website=Lower Bari Doab Canal Improvement Project (LBDCIP)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Trimmu Barrage]] on River Chenab<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trimmu_Barrage|title=Trimmu Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Sidhnai Barrage on River Ravi<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unesco.org.pk/ns/documents/Workshop_Workbook/Session_5/9_Barrage-(Sidhnai).pdf|title=Flood Fighting Plan 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=UNESCO Office in Islamabad|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Islam Barrage]] on River Sutlej <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam_Barrage|title=Islam Barrage|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n#[[Sulemanki Headworks|Suleimanki Barrage]] on River Sutlej<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sulemanki_Headworks|title=Sulemanki Headworks|last=|first=|date=|website=Wikipedia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n# Panjnad Barrage on River Indus<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1444136|title=Panjnad headworks rehabilitation project begins|last=Gill|first=Majeed|date=7 November 2018|work=Dawn|access-date=13 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Irrigation network.jpg|thumb|Main Canals and barrages in Punjab]]\n<br />\n== Zones ==\nFor the purpose of administration and management the Punjab irrigation system is divided into the following 6 operational zones:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/#|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Lahore Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Lahore Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1029|title=Introduction Of Lahore Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Irrigation Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Chenab Canal Circle\n* Depalpur Canal Circle\n* Link Canal Circle\n* Lahore Drainage Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n[[File:Lower Bari Doab canal.jpg|thumb|Lower Bari Doab Canal]]\n\n==== Faisalabad Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Faisalabad Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1034|title=Introduction Of Faisalabad Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Lower Chenab Canal East Circle\n* Lower Chenab Canal West Circle\n* Drainage Circle\n* Qadirabad Balloki Link Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n==== Sargodha Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Sargodha Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1024|title=Introduction of Sargodha Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Irrigation Department|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Upper Jhelum Canal Circle\n* Lower Jhelum Canal Circle\n* Thal Canal Circle\n* Drainage Circle\n\n==== Multan Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Multan Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1039|title=Introduction Of Multan Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Nilibar Circle\n* Haveli Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n* Mailsi Canal Circle\n\n==== Bahawalpur Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Bahawalpur Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1|title=Introduction of Bahawalpur Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Bahawalpur Canal Circle\n* Bahawalnagar Canal Circle\n* Rahimyarkhan Canal Circle\n* Development Circle\n\n==== DG Khan Zone ====\nThere are following operational circles in Dera Ghazi Khan Zone:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1044|title=Introduction Of D G Khan Irrigation Zone|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Derajat Circle\n* Muzaffargarh Canal Circle\n* Project Circle \n\nEach operational zone is headed by a chief engineer and each circle is headed by a superintending engineer and they are supported by an extended team of executive engineers, sub-divisional officers, sub-engineers, mates and baildars. In addition to operational zones, the department has following zones for overall planning and management of irrigation operations:\n\n* Planning and Review Zone  \n* Drainage and Flood zone \n* Research zone \n* Development zone  \n\nPunjab Irrigation Department also manages Government Engineering Academy Punjab which provides pre-service and in-service training to irrigation engineers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://geap.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Government Engineering Academy Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Service Delivery ===\nPunjab Irrigation Department delivers irrigation supplies to farmers through 51,990 outlets in its system of 24 main canals and distribution canals spanning 22,700 kilometers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pide.org.pk/pdf/Rural/water_and_irrigation(Khalid_Riaz).pdf|title=Water and Irrigation in Punjab|last=Riaz|first=Khalid|date=|website=Pakistan Institute of Development Economics|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:Head Office Building.jpg|alt=The main secretariat of Punjab Irrigation Department in Old Anarkali, Lahore|thumb|Secretariat of Irrigation Department]]\nThe Punjab Irrigation Department has its head office in [[Old Anarkali]], Lahore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Punjab Irrigation Department has complaint hotline 0800 11 333 for registration of complaints regarding irrigation supply issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://imis.irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Program Monitoring and Implementation Unit|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Daily canal discharges at all the canals in the entire system can be checked at the official website of the department.<ref>https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/</ref>   \n\n==Units==\nFor the purpose of management of various projects and institutional reforms the Punjab Irrigation Department has established the following Units:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/|title=Irrigation Department Punjab|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* Program Monitoring and Implementation Unit\n* Strategic Planning and Reforms Unit\n* Project Management Office (Canals)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irrigation.punjab.gov.pk/page/1073|title=Project Management Office Canals|last=|first=|date=|website=Irrigation Department Punjab|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Projects Management Office (Barrages)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmo-pb.gop.pk/pages/index.php|title=PMO Punjab Barrages|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Flood Risk Assessment Unit\n* Hydraulic Safety Structure Evaluation Unit\n* Program Implementation Unit\n\n== Laws and policies ==\nPunjab Irrigation Department functions under [https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/xbdYzzLgub7806TxhY3IPm5QZmfhOBdiHchhQx4biiL4BYvuaP8qm3aBqMgNF2W3rv2F7jzc9qtf9OTtahmJlw-- Canal and Drainage Act 1873] which was introduced to regulate irrigation, navigation and drainage of provincial territories. The purpose of this act is that the Provincial Government is entitled to use and control for public purposes, the water of all rivers and streams flowing in natural channels, and of all lake and other natural collections of still water in said territories<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecolex.org/details/legislation/canal-and-drainage-act-1873-act-viii-of-1873-lex-faoc064507/|title=Canal and Drainage Act, 1873 (Act VIII of 1873)|last=|first=|date=|website=ECOLEX|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. An amendment was made in Canal and Drainage Act in 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/nZOfE1HY0TfvbiWVPJ0LK7orZSrwQj60DkViPE4WbrYUQQYyFP~YnbyRc6CKcbFOzUBpFDaYycYs3xwRMefxiw--|title=CANAL AND DRAINAGE (AMENDMENT) ACT 2016|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Code|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. In 2019, the Government introduced Punjab Water Act 2019 to regulate the usage of surface and groundwater in the province<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://punjabcode.punjab.gov.pk/en/show_article/nIKGkzRRTKQ2T2fiRi5.at0Lxzstpqigttf4DpBFajVEC2AyJADmKH5.TsrG27KP7jXjXGobpfikCY654X5Ozw--|title=Punjab Water Act 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Punjab Codes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== Major developments ==\n[[File:Khanki Barrage, Punjab.jpg|thumb|New Khanki Barrage in Punjab, Pakistan]]\nIn 2010-11 completed the Taunsa Barrage rehabilitation and modernization project with cost of Rs. 11 billion rupees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.std.com.pk/fulltext/?doi=std.2014.127.131|title=Rehabilitated Taunsa Barrage: Prospects and Concerns|last=Chaudary|first=Zulfiqar|date=|website=Science and Technology Development|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  Punjab Irrigation Department Completed the  Punjab Irrigation completed the construction of New Khanki Barrage in August 2017 which replaced the old [[Khanki Headworks]] which irrigated 3.03 million acres of fertile land in 8 districts of central Punjab.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/12-May-2019/descon-to-hand-over-new-khanki-barrage-to-irrigation-dept-in-june|title=Descon to hand over New Khanki Barrage to Irrigation Dept in June|last=Gilani|first=Iqtidar|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPunjab Irrigation Department has, in December 2019, inaugurated the construction of Jalalpur Irrigation Canal System.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/589820-jalalpur-canal-to-benefit-people-cm-usman-buzdar|title=Jalalpur Canal to benefit people: CM Usman Buzdar|last=|first=|date=28 December 2019|work=The News|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The 117 kilometer long canal will originate from River Jhelum at Rasul Barrage and, along with its branches, will irrigate 1,70,000 acres of arid land in Districts of Jhelum and Khushab. The Department has also initiated works on Dadocha Dam which will supply 35 million gallons of drinking per day to the people of Rawalpindi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1525513|title=Irrigation dept claims credit for executing key projects in 2019|last=Mehmood|first=Amjad|date=1 January 2020|work=Dawn|access-date=23 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to this civil works on projects like Rehabilitation of Trimmu and Panjnad Barrages, rehabilitation of Trimmu-Sidhnai Canal, SMB Link Canal, Ahmadpur Branch and Eastern Sadiqia Canal are also underway and expected to be completed by 2022.   \n\nOn 22 May 2019, [[Punjab Khal Panchayat Authority]] was established under the Punjab Khal Panchayat Ordinance 2019 to ensure implementation of [[Warabandi system|warabandi]] minimizing the water disputes and distribution.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1484382|title=PIDA abolished: Irrigation dept takes control of canals, watercourses|date=May 25, 2019|work=Dawn|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/11/21/546246/pa-passes-punjab-water-bill-2019-amid-oppositions-boycott/|title=PA passes Punjab Water Bill 2019 amid opposition\u2019s boycott|date=November 21, 2019|work=Business Recorder|access-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This authority replaced the erstwhile Punjab Irrigation and Drainage Authority (PIDA).     \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}{{Pakistani water locks}}{{Waters of Pakistan}}{{Irrigation by country}}\n[[Category:Government of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Irrigation in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Departments of Government of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Shantavira", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:MOS:HON", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Punjab_Irrigation_Department"}
{"title_page": "Partimento", "text_new": "[[File:Fenaroli Partimento No 1 Book 1 Gj1301.jpg|thumb|right|500px|A simple partimenti with figures to teach beginners. (Fenaroli Partimento No. 1, Book 1, Gj1301)]]\n[[File:Fenaroli Partimento Fugue 8, Book 5, Gj1418.jpg|thumb|right|500px| A partimenti fugue for more advanced students. As students progressed, partimenti became unfigured. (Fenaroli Partimento Fugue 8, Book 5, Gj1418)]]\n\nA '''Partimento'''  (from the [[Italian language|Italian]]: partimento, plural ''partimenti'') is a sketch (often a bass line), written out on a single staff, whose main purpose is to be a guide for the improvisation (\"realization\") of a composition at the keyboard.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=14}} Partimento differs from simple basso continuo [[accompaniment]] in that the result is a complete, fully-realized composition.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=167}} Partimenti were central to the training of European court musicians from the late 1600s until the early 1800s. They had their greatest influence first in Italian conservatories, especially at the [[music conservatories of Naples]], and then later at the [[Paris Conservatory]], which emulated the Neapolitan conservatories.\"<ref name=partimentoinfluence>[http://partimenti.org/partimenti/about_parti/hist_overview.html The History of Partimenti]Monuments of Partimenti</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Durante.jpg|thumb|Francesco Durante, hailed by [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau|Jean-Jacques Rousseau]] as,\"the most celebrated harmonist of Italy, that is to say of the entire world.\"{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=70}}]]\n[[File:Leonardo Leo.jpg|thumb|Leonardo Leo]]\n\n=== Beginnings ===\nThe Partimenti evolved in the late 17th century in educational milieus in Bologna, Rome, and Naples. \n\n=== Golden Age ===\nThe golden age of partimento was presided over by [[Francesco Durante|Francesco Durante]] and [[Leonardo Leo|Leonardo Leo]], the 2nd generation of Neapolitan masters.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=67}} Many important Italian composers emerged from the musical institutions in Naples, Bologna, and Milano, such as [[Giovanni Battista Pergolesi]], [[Giuseppe Verdi]], [[Domenico Cimarosa]], [[Vincenzo Bellini]], [[Gaetano Donizetti]], [[Gaspare Spontini]] and [[Gioachino Rossini]].\n\n=== Influence on Paris Conservatory ===\nThe Paris Conservatory was greatly influenced by the [[music conservatories of Naples||music conservatories of Naples]]. As the Neapolitans did not have a class but called much of it \"Harmony.\" There was \"practical harmony\" improvised from partimenti played at the piano, and there was \"harmony\" as a written subject where a given bass or given soprano was \"realized\" by providing three additional voices. The resulting four-voice counterpoint on four staves (notated in soprano, alto, tenor, and bass clefs) was called a realization (''r\u00e9alisation''). A student would begin by playing elementary material as a ten- or eleven-year-old but would eventually develop the skill to write complicated four-voice counterpoint full of remote modulations and chromatic embellishments.{{sfn|Gjerdingen|2019|p=[http://partimenti.org/harmony/about_harmo/overview.html]}} [[Fran\u00e7ois Bazin (composer)|Fran\u00e7ois Bazin]] was a teacher of harmony at the Paris conservatory and many of his lessons were still titled \"partimenti\".{{sfn|Gjerdingen|2020|p=296}}\n\n=== Revival in the 21st century  ===\nThe rediscovery of the partimento tradition in modern research since around 2000 has enabled new ways of looking at the musical education and composing practice in the 18th and 19th centuries. Nurturing musical creativity beyond mere partimento realizations.  Influential monographs concerning partimento include [[Robert Gjerdingen|Robert O. Gjerdingen]]'s ''Music in the Galant Style'' (2007) and [[Giorgio Sanguinetti]]'s ''The Art of Partimento'' (2012). Partimenti gained increased recognition due to being part of [[Alma Deutscher]]'s early musical training, with her studies with Tobias Cramm and Robert Gjerdingen.{{efn|Her father, Israeli linguist Guy Deutscher, said, \u201cThe greatest moment was when we realized that she was playing her own melodies.\u201d He decided to take Alma\u2019s musical soul seriously, and began searching for methods of teaching classical music composition to children\u2014and for a teacher.He discovered a book, Music in the Galant Style, by Robert Gjerdingen, professor of music at North-western University\u2019s School of Music. Gjerdingen reveals the results of his exhaustive search through the libraries of Naples and other Italian cities to and the original sources, the pedagogical workbooks, known as partimenti (or singular, partimento, using the word to mean the method itself) of 18th-century music masters.}}{{sfn|Rasmussen|2017|p=25}}.\n\n== Partimento Rules ==\n\nSeveral Neapolitan teachers such as Fedele Fenaroli, Giovanni Furno and Giaocomo Insanguine published collections of ''regole'' (rules) and partimenti that were popular pedagogical materials across Europe. In particular, Fenaroli's ''Regole'' enjoyed a long publishing life, from the first edition 1775 to the final edition in 1930.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=78}}\n\n{{Quote|text=To begin with, one will play all unfigured basses with simple consonant chords: from that performance the Master will clearly understand if his pupil has correctly understood the principles thereof. Secondly, one shall introduce all feasible dissonances for that given bass. Lastly, one shall shape the properly said imitation.|author=Emanuele Guarnaccia|title=''Metodo nuovamente riformato de'partimenti'', 3, 1825 ca|source={{sfn|Guarnaccia|1825|p=3}}}}\n\nPartimenti were typically used as exercises to train conventional models of [[voice leading]], [[harmony]], and musical form, such as the so-called [[Rule of the octave|Rule of the Octave]] (the harmonized scale), [[Cadence (music)|cadences]] and [[Sequence (music)|sequences]] (the movimenti, or moti del basso). The beginners\u2019 partimenti treatises usually present rules, which are then followed by exercises of increasing difficulty, presenting [[figured bass]]  as well as [[unfigured bass]] lines, and culminating in the advanced exercises of imitative partimenti and partimento [[fugue|fugues]].\n\n== Consonances and Dissonances ==\nMusic is composed of consonances and dissonances.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=2}}\n\n=== Consonances ===\nThe four consonances are the 3rd, 5th, 6th and 8th. The 5th and 8th are '''perfect consonances''' because one cannot make distinctions between them by expanding them with a sharp or diminishing them with a flat. The 3rd and 6th are considered '''imperfect consonances''' because one can make distinctions between them.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=3}}\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 2 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <g b>1^\\markup { \\center-column { 3rd } }  \\bar \"||\" <d a'>^\\markup { \\center-column { 5th } } \\bar \"||\" <b g'>^\\markup { \\center-column { 6th } }  \\bar \"||\"<g g'>^\\markup { \\center-column { 8th } }\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\nThere is a prohibition against two octaves or two fifths moving in parallel because, due to their perfection, they create no variation in harmony, and these [perfect intervals] are the fundamental basses that rule the key.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=4}}\n\n=== Dissonances ===\nThe four dissonances are the 2nd, 4th, 7th and 9th. They were invented to make the consonances sound more beautiful. These cannot be used unless prepared by a preceding consonance and subsequently resolved to one of the aforementioned consonances.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=14}}\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 2 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <fis, g>1^\\markup { \\center-column { 2nd } }  \\bar \"||\" <d g>^\\markup { \\center-column { 4th } } \\bar \"||\" <a g'>^\\markup { \\center-column { 7th } }  \\bar \"||\"<fis g'>^\\markup { \\center-column { 9th } }\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n== Essential Foundations of the Key  ==\n\nThe ''Essential Foundations of the Key''{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=4}} or ''Rule of the Scale Steps''{{sfn|Furno|1817|p=2}} tell the student how to distribute chords over scale degrees, separate from the Rule of the Octave.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=117}}\n\nOne can give an 8ve to all the degrees of the key, as well as to their consonances, provided that one does not create parallel 8ves, seeing that two 5ths or 8ves, whether above or below, by step or by skip, the one after the other, are prohibited because they make bad harmony.\n\n\u2460 takes a 3rd, 5th.\n\n\u2461 takes a minor 3rd, 4th and major 6th. {{sfn|Furno|1817|p=3}}\n\n\u2462 takes a 3rd and 6th. Both of them should be minor if the said \u2462 is major. If, on the other hand, the said \u2462 is minor, then it takes the major 3rd and major 6th, and this comes about naturally.\n\n\u2463 takes a 3rd and 5th. Whenever the \u2463 ascends to the \u2464, it [\u2463] can take the 6th in addition to the 3rd and 5th. And if \u2463 descends from \u2464, then stay with the same consonances as for the said \u2464, which become in turn a 2nd, major [=augmented] 4th, and 6th.\n\n\u2464 takes a major 3rd and 5th. Give a minor seventh to a \u2464 that returns to the \u2460. This seventh cannot rise, but must resolve by falling to the third of the \u2460.\n\n\u2465 takes a 3rd, and 6th. When \u2465 is major and descends to \u2464, then it is better to use a major 6th in the accompaniment, because it makes better harmony. And one can add to \u2465, as if it were \u2461, by giving it a 3rd, a 4th, and a major 6th. But if the \u2465 neither ascends to \u2466 or descends to \u2460, then give it a 3rd and 5th.\n\n\u2466 takes a 3rd and 6th. Both of them should be minor if the said \u2466 is major. If, on the other hand, the \u2466 is minor, then the 3rd and the 6th in the accompaniment should both be major, and this comes about naturally. Give a diminished fifth to a \u2466 rising to the \u2460, in addition to the 3rd and 6th. This diminished fifth cannot rise, but must also resolve by falling to the third of the \u2460.\n\n== Cadences ==\nA cadence is when the bass goes from \u2460 to \u2464, and [then] from \u2464 to \u2460.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=7a}} There are three types of cadences: Simple, Compound and Double.{{sfn|Fenaroli|1775|p=7b}}\n\n=== Simple Cadence ===\nA simple cadence is when one gives the bass the simple consonances required by both \u2460 and \u2464. That is, the \u2460 takes the 3rd and 5th, and the \u2464 takes the major 3rd and 5th.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                \\stemUp \\clef treble \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 2 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <b, d g>2 <a d fis> <b d g>1\t\t \n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                       <3>2 <5 _+> <3>1\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4\n                g2 d g,1\n                }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>\n\n=== Compound Cadence ===\nA compound cadence is when, above \u2464, one makes a dissonance of a 4th prepared by the 8ve of \u2460 and resolved to the major 3rd of \u2464.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                 \\clef treble \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 2 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n              << { g2~ g4 fis }  \\\\ { d2 d }  \\\\ \\\\ { s2 \\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 a2 } \\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 b2 >> |\n              < b d g >1  |\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                     <3>2 <5 4>4 <_+> <3>1\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4\n                g2 d g,1\n                }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>\n\n=== Double Cadence ===\nA double cadence is when, above \u2464, one puts the major 3rd and 5th, the 6th and 4th, the 5th and 4th, and then the major 3rd and 5th.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                 \\clef treble \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 2 = 45 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n              <b d g>1 | << {fis'4 g~ g fis} \\\\ {s2 d} \\\\ {\\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 d4 \\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 d s2} \\\\ {s2 \\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 a} \\\\ {\\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 a4 \\once \\override NoteColumn.force-hshift = 0 b s2}  >> |\n              < b d g >1  |\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                     <3>1 <5 _+>4 <6 4> <5 4> <5 _+> <3>1\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4\n                g1 d g,\n                }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>\n\n== Rule of the Octave ==\n[[File:Fedele Fenaroli.JPG|thumb|Fedele Fenaroli's version of the Rule of the Octave became the most prominent. {{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=114}}]]\n\nAfter learning cadences, students at the Neapolitan conservatories were immediately taught the Rule of the Octave, or ''scale'' as they were termed in Naples.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=114}}\n\n=== Major mode ===\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                \\stemUp \\clef treble \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <b d g>1 <c d fis> <b d g> <a e' g> <a d fis> <c c g'> <c d a'> <b d g>\t\t \n                }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4\n                g, a b c d e fis g\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                       <8 5 3>1 <6+ 4 3> <6 3 8> <5 3 6> <3 5 8> <6 3> <3 6 5/> <8 5 3>\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>Rule of the Octave Ascending in G major, in 1st position.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                \\stemUp \\clef treble \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <b d g>1 <a d a'> <a cis g'> <a d fis> <a d fis> <b d g> <c d fis> <b d g>\n                }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4\n                g fis e d c b a g\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                       <8 5 3>1 <3 6 3> <3 6+ 4> <3 8 5> <4+ 2 6> <6 3 8> <6+ 4 3> <8 5 3>\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>Rule of the Octave Descending in G major, in 1st position.\n\n=== Minor mode ===\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                \\stemUp \\clef treble \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <bes d g>1 <c d fis> <bes d g> <a es' g> <a d fis> <c c g'> <c d a'> <bes d g>\t\t \n                }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4\n                g, a bes c d e fis g\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                       <8 5 3>1 <6+ 4 3> <6 3 8> <5 3 6> <3+ 8 5> <3 6> <3 6 5/> <8 5 3>\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>Rule of the Octave Ascending in G minor, in 1st position.\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n    {\n      \\new PianoStaff <<\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c'' {\n                \\stemUp \\clef treble \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                <bes d g>1 <a d a'> <a cis g'> <a d fis> <a d fis> <bes d g> <c d fis> <bes d g>\n                }\n            >>\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4\n                g f es d c bes a g\n                }\n                \\new FiguredBass {\n                    \\figuremode {\n                       <8 5 3>1 <3 6 3> <3 6+ 4> <3+ 8 5> <4+ 2 6> <6 3 8> <6+ 4 3> <8 5 3>\n    }\n  }\n            >>\n    >> }\n</score>Rule of the Octave Descending in G minor, in 1st position.\n\n== Suspensions ==\nAccording to partimento theory, it is only suspensions that are deemed to be dissonances.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=125}}\n\n=== The Fourth ===\n\n=== The Seventh ===\n\n=== The Ninth ===\n\n=== Bass Suspension: The Second ===\n\n== Bass Motions ==\nIn addition to the Rule of the Octave, bass motions are fundamental to partimento theory. The ability to identify bass motions in a partimento allows the performer to choose appropriate chords. Bass motions move in a conjunct (stepwise, including chromatic) motion or disjunct motion (sequences).{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=135}}\n\n=== Rises by a 3rd and falls by a step ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c,1 e d f e g f a g c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Falls by a 3rd and rises by a step ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c1 a b g a f g e f d e c g' c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Rises by a 4th and falls by a 3rd ===\n\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c,1 f d g e a  f g c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n=== Falls by a 4th and rises by a step ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c1 g a e f c g' c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Rises by a 4th and falls by a 5th ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                g1 c fis, b e, a d, g c, d g,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Falls by a 5th and rises by a 4th ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\minor \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c1 f, bes es, as d, g c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n=== Rises by a 5th and falls by a 4th ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c,1 g' d a' e b' g c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Rises by a 6th and falls by a 5th ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c,1 a' d, b' e, c' f, g c,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Falls by semitone ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                g1 fis f! e es! d g,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Rises by semitone ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key g \\minor \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                g1 d es e f fis g d g,\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n=== Falls with ties ===\n<score vorbis=\"1\" lang=\"lilypond\">\n   {\n        \\new Staff <<\n            \\new Voice \\relative c' {\n                \\stemDown \\clef bass \\key c \\major \\time 4/4 \\tempo 1 = 60 \\set Score.tempoHideNote = ##t\n                c,2 c'~ c b~ b a~ a g~ g f~ f e d1 c\n                }\n            >>\n     }\n</score>\n\n== Diminution ==\nThe art of turning a basic, slow melody into a more florid, rapid one is called diminution.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=183}}\n\n== Imitation ==\n{{Quote|text=[Imitations] occur when the right hand imitates, that is answers to, the motive of the bass, that the left hand has played; or rather, when the right hand anticipates the motive that the left hand will play shortly after.|author=Pellegrino Tomeoni|title=''Regole pratiche per accompagnare il basso continuo'',39|source={{sfn|Tomeoni|1795}}}}\n\nImitation works to improve a basic accompaniment-like realization into a more proper composition.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=191a}} It is also an important preparatory training for partimento fugues.{{sfn|Sanguinetti|2012|p=191b}}\n\n== Partimento Fugues ==\nThe culmination of partimento training is the realization of partimento fugues.{{sfn|Gjerdingen|2020|p=122}}\n\n== Partimento and Counterpoint ==\n\n{{Quote|text=For those who want to learn counterpoint, it is necessary first to thoroughly study the first and second books of partimenti, and then the moti del basso of the third book.|author=Fedele Fenaroli|title=''Studio de Contrapunto del Sig I-Nc 22-2-6/2, fol. 1''|source={{sfn|van Tour|2015|p=162}}}}\n\nPartimenti were also used as bass lines in written counterpoint exercises, over which students wrote two-, three, and four-part \u201cdisposizione\u201d (multistave settings).\n\n== Notable collections of Partimenti ==\nNotable partimento collections were written by [[Alessandro Scarlatti]], [[Francesco Durante]], [[Leonardo Leo]], [[Fedele Fenaroli]], [[Giovanni Paisiello]], [[Nicola Sala]], [[Giacomo Tritto]], [[Stanislao Mattei]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|3}}\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* {{citation |last=Fenaroli |title=Regole Musicali Per i Principianti Di Cembalo |publisher=Naples, Vincenzo Mazzola-Vocola. |year=1775}}\n* {{citation |last=Tomeoni |title=Regole pratiche per accompagnare il bass continuo |publisher=Florence: Pagani. |year=1795}}\n* {{citation |last=Furno |title=Metodo, Facile breve e chiaro delle prime ed essensiali regole per accompagnare - Partimenti senza numeri |publisher=Naples, near Orlando Vico, S. M. delle Grazie No. 25. |year=1817}}\n* {{citation |last=Guarnaccia |title=Metodo nuovamente riformato de'partimenti...dal maestro Emanuele Guarnaccia |publisher=Milan, Ricordi n.d. |year=1850\u201351}}\n* {{citation |last=Sanguinetti |title=Decline and fall of the \"Celeste Impero\": the theory of composition in Naples during the ottocento |publisher=Studi musicali, Anno XXXIV - n.2, p. 451-502. |year=2005}}\n* {{citation |last=Gjerdingen |title=Images of Galant Music in Neapolitan Partimenti and Solfeggi |publisher=Improvisatorische Praxis vom Mittelalter bis zum 18. Jahrhundert, Regula Rapp and Thomas Drescher, eds., Basler Jahrbuch f\u00fcr historische Musikpraxis 31. |year=2007}}\n* {{citation |last=Gjerdingen |title=Music in the Galant Style |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2007|isbn=978-0195313710}}\n* {{citation |last=Cafiero |title=The Early Reception of Neapolitan Partimento Theory in France |publisher=Journal of Music Theory 51:1, Yale University. |year=2007}}\n* {{citation |last=Serebrennikov |title=From Partimento Fugue To Thoroughbass Fugue: New Perspectives |publisher=Journal of the Riemenschneider, Bach Institute, Baldwin-Wallace College, Volume XL, No. 2. |year=2009}}\n* {{citation |last=Gjerdingen |title=Partimento, Que Me Veux-Tu? |publisher=Journal of Music Theory 52, pg 85\u2013135. |year=2009}}\n* {{citation |last=Gjerdingen |title=The Perfection of Craft Training in the Neapolitan Conservatories. |publisher=Rivista di Analisi e Teoria Musicale 15, pgs 26\u201349 |year=2009}}\n* {{citation |last=Sanguinetti |title=The Realization of Partimenti |publisher=Journal of Music Theory 51:1, Yale University. |year=