=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Stanwick |first=Paul Edmund |title=Portraits of the Ptolemies: Greek Kings as Egyptian Pharaohs |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qllfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Paul+Edmund+Stanwick%22#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn= 9780292777729 |year=2010 }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Svoronos |first=Ioannis |title=Ta nomismata tou kratous ton Ptolemaion |url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=Ta%20nomismata%20tou%20kratous%20ton%20Ptolemaion |volume=Volumes 1 & 2, and 3 & 4 |location=Athens |year=1904 |oclc=54869298 |author-link=Ioannis Svoronos}} (in Greek and German) {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Tyldesley |first=Joyce |date=2006 |title=Chronicle of the Queens of Egypt |url=https://archive.org/details/chronicleofqueen00tyld |location=London |publisher=Thames & Hudson |page= |isbn=9780500051450 |author-link=Joyce Tyldesley }}\n*{{cite book |last=Whitehorne |first=John |title=Cleopatras |publisher=Routledge |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-415-05806-3 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080511211402/http://www.tyndale.cam.ac.uk/Egypt/ptolemies/ptolemy_xii.htm Ptolemy XII] by Christopher Bennett (part of his [http://www.instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/index.htm ''Egyptian Royal Genealogy''])\n*[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Ptolemy-XII-Auletes Ptolemy XII Auletes] from the online ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/home.html Strabo ''The Geography''] in English translation, ed. H.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Jones (1924), at LacusCurtius (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/home.html Cassius Dio ''Roman History''] in English translation by Cary (1914\u20131927), at LacusCurtius (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Africa/Egypt/_Texts/BEVHOP/12*.html The House of Ptolemy, Chapter&nbsp;XII] by [[Edwyn Bevan|E.&nbsp;R.&nbsp;Bevan]] (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://virtualreligion.net/iho/ptolemy_12.html Ptolemy XII Auletes (ca. 112 - 51 BCE)] entry in historical sourcebook by Mahlon H. Smith\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Ptolemaic dynasty]]||ca. 117 BC||ca. 51 BC}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ptolemy XI]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Pharaohs#Ptolemaic Dynasty|Pharaoh of Egypt]]|years=80 BC-58 BC\n|regent1='''[[Cleopatra V]]/[[Cleopatra VI|VI]]'''}}\n{{s-aft|after=Cleopatra V/VI<br>[[Berenice IV]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Berenice IV}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Pharaohs#Ptolemaic Dynasty|Pharaoh of Egypt]]|years=55 BC-51 BC\n|regent1='''[[Cleopatra VII]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ptolemy XIII Theos Philopator|Ptolemy XIII]]<br>Cleopatra VII}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Hellenistic rulers}}\n{{Pharaohs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ptolemy 12}}\n[[Category:51 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Pharaohs]]\n[[Category:Cleopatra]]\n[[Category:Pharaohs of the Ptolemaic dynasty]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC rulers in Africa]]\n[[Category:2nd-century BC Egyptian people]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Egyptian people]]\n[[Category:Flautists]]\n[[Category:Hellenistic Cyprus]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|Egyptian king}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Ptolemy XII Auletes\n| image          = Ptolemy XII Auletes Louvre Ma3449.jpg\n| caption        = Bust of Ptolemy XII housed at the Department of Greek, Etruscan and Roman Antiquities at the [[Louvre]] in [[Paris]]\n| succession     = [[Ptolemaic dynasty|Ptolemaic King]] of [[Ptolemaic Kingdom|Egypt]]\n| reign          = {{c.|80\u201358 BC}}\n| coronation     = 76 BC, [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]]\n| predecessor    = [[Ptolemy XI Alexander&nbsp;II]] \n| successor      = [[Cleopatra V Tryphaena]] and [[Berenice&nbsp;IV Epiphaneia]]\n| regent         = Cleopatra V Tryphaena<br>(79\u201369 BC)\n| reg-type       = Co-ruler \n| reign1         = {{c.|55-51 BC}}\n| predecessor1   = Berenice IV Epiphaneia\n| successor1     = [[Cleopatra VII Philopator]] and [[Ptolemy&nbsp;XIII Theos Philopator]] \n| regent1        = Cleopatra VII Philopator<br>(52\u201351 BC)<br>{{Ancient Egyptian royal titulary case|horus=''\u1e25wnw-nfr bnr-mrwt \u1e6fni-sw-nbt-r\u1e2byt-\u1e25n\ua724-k\ua722.f dw\ua722.n.f-\u1e2bnmw-\u0161ps-r-\u0161zp-n.f-\u1e2b\ua724(t)-m-nsw<br> snsn.n-s\u1e25nw-m-\u1e25\ua724\ua724w-mi-N\u1e0f-it.f \u1e6f\u1e25n-msw(t)-\u1e25r-nst-it.f-mi-\u1e25r-k\ua722-n\u1e2bt ity-ps\u1e0f-m-t\ua722mri-mi-\u1e25pw-\ua724n\u1e2b rdi-n.f-\u1e25\ua722bw-sd-\ua724\u0161\ua722w-wrw-mi-Pt\u1e25-t\ua722\u1e6fnn-it-n\u1e6frw''<br>''Hununefer Benermerut Tjenisunebtrekhyethenakaf Duaenefkhnmushepesershesepenefkha'emnesu<br/> Sensenensehnuemhaawminedjetitef Tjehenmesuthernesetitefmihorkanakht Itypesedjemtamerimihapuankh Redienefhebusedashauwerumiptahtatjenenitnetjeru''<br> The perfect youth, pleasant in his popularity, whom the Two Ladies and the common folk have elevated along with his ka,<br> who the wonderful Khnum praises so that he receives the crown of kingship, who unites himself with the works (of his father)<br> in joy like that which his father protects, who is shining at birth on the throne of his father like Horus,<br> the strong bull, the lord who lights up Egypt like the living Apis, to whom many great Sed festivals will be given through Ptah-Tatenen, the father of the Gods\n| nebty          = First Nebty name:'' wr-p\u1e25ti \u1e2bnt\u0161-n\u1e25\u1e25 smn-hpw-mi-\u1e0f\u1e25wti-\ua724\ua722-\ua724\ua722''<br>''Werpehty Khenteshneheh Semenhepumidjehutia'a''<br>The one great of strength and foremost one of the sea forever, who has established laws like the twice-great Thoth<br>Second Nebty name:''wr-p\u1e25ti \u1e2bnt\u0161-n\u1e25\u1e25 nfr-ib w\u1e6fz-nfrw-mi-\u1e0f\u1e25wti-\ua724\ua722-\ua724\ua722''<br>''Werpehty Khenteshneheh Neferib Wetjesneferumidjehutia'a''<br>The one great of strength and foremost one of the sea forever, perfect of mind, who has raised perfection like the twice-great Thoth\n| golden         = First Golden Horus name:''\ua724\ua722-ib ity nb-\u1e33nw-n\u1e2bt-mi-z\ua722-\ua722st''<br>''A'a-ib Ity Nebqenunakhtmiza'aset''<br> The one great of mind, the sovereign, the possessor of bravery and strength like the son of Isis<br>Second Golden Horus name:'' \ua724\ua722-ib mri-n\u1e6frw-B\ua722\u1e33t ity-mi-r\ua724 \u1e25\u1e33\ua722-w\ua722\u1e0fti''<br>''A'a-ib Merynetjerubaqet Itimire Heqawadjety''<br>The one great of mind who is beloved of the gods of Baqet, a sovereign like Ra and ruler of the two crowns\n| prenomen       = First Praenomens, variants of:<br>'' iw\ua724-n-p\ua722-n\u1e6fr-n\u1e25m stp-n-pt\u1e25...'' \u2014 ''Iwa'enpanetjernehem Setepenptah...'' \u2014  The heir of the saviour god, who is the chosen of Ptah...<br/>''...iri-m\ua722\ua724t-n-r\ua724 s\u1e2bm-\ua724n\u1e2b-imn''<br>''...Irimaatenre Sekhemankhimen''<br>...who brings forth the order of Ra, the living image of Amun<br>''...iri-m\ua722\ua724t-imn-r\ua724''<br>''...Irimaatimenre''<br>...who has brings forth the order of Amun-Ra<br>Second Preanomen:'' p\ua722 n\u1e6fr-mri it snt wsiri \u1e25wnw''<br>''Pa Netjermery It Senet Usiri Hunu''<br>The god who is beloved of his father and brother, the youthful Osiris\n| nomen          = ''ptwlmys \ua724n\u1e2b-\u1e0ft mri-pt\u1e25-\ua722st''<br>''Petulemis Ankdjet Meriptahaset''<br> Ptolemaios, living forever, beloved of Ptah and Isis}}\n| reg-type1      = Co-ruler\n| full name      = Ptolemy Neos Dionysos Philopator Philadelphos\n| spouse         = [[Cleopatra V Tryphaena]]\n| issue          = {{ubl|[[Berenice IV Epiphaneia]]|[[Cleopatra VII Philopator]]|[[Arsinoe IV]]|[[Ptolemy XIII Theos Philopator]]|[[Ptolemy XIV]]}}\n| issue-link     = #Marriage and issue\n| dynasty        = [[Ptolemaic dynasty|Ptolemaic]]\n| father         = [[Ptolemy IX Soter]]\n| birth_date     = {{c.|117 BC}}\n| birth_place    =[[Cyprus]]?\n| death_date     = before 22 March 51 BC\n| death_place    = [[Alexandria]]\n| date of burial =\n| place of burial=\n}}\n'''Ptolemy XII Neos Dionysos Philopator Philadelphos''' ({{lang-grc|\u03a0\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03ad\u03bf\u03c2 \u0394\u03b9\u03cc\u03bd\u03c5\u03c3\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a6\u03b9\u03bb\u03bf\u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03c1 \u03a6\u03b9\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03bf\u03c2}}, ''Ptolemaios N\u00e9os Di\u00f3nysos Philop\u00e1t\u014dr Phil\u00e1delphos'' \"Ptolemy New [[Dionysus]], Father-lover, Sibling-lover\"; {{c.|117 BC}} \u2013 before 22 March 51 BC) was a king of the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]] of [[Ancient Egypt]]. He was commonly known as '''Auletes''' ({{lang-grc|\u0391\u1f50\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2}}, ''Aul\u0113t\u1e17s'' \"the Flautist\"), referring to the king's love of playing the [[flute]] in [[Dionysia]]n festivals. As a member of the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]], he was a descendant of its founder, [[Ptolemy&nbsp;I]]. \n\nPtolemy XII was an [[illegitimate]] son of [[Ptolemy&nbsp;IX]] by an uncertain mother. In 116 BC Ptolemy IX's father, [[Ptolemy&nbsp;VIII]], died and he became co-regent with his mother, [[Cleopatra&nbsp;III]]. However, he was forced into a civil war against his mother and brother, [[Ptolemy&nbsp;X]], leading to his exile in 107 BC. Cleopatra&nbsp;III sent her grandsons to [[Kos]] in 103 BC. They were captured by [[Mithridates&nbsp;VI of Pontus]] probably in 88 BC, around the time Ptolemy&nbsp;IX returned to the Egyptian throne. After their father died in 81 BC, Ptolemy XII's half-sister [[Berenice&nbsp;III]] took the throne. She was soon murdered by her cousin and co-regent, [[Ptolemy&nbsp;XI]], who was then killed. \n\nPtolemy XII was recalled from [[Kingdom of Pontus|Pontus]] and proclaimed king of Egypt, while his brother, also named [[Ptolemy of Cyprus|Ptolemy]], became king of [[Cyprus]]. By his wife [[Cleopatra&nbsp;V Tryphaena]], Ptolemy XII had at least one child, [[Berenice&nbsp;IV]], and probably [[Cleopatra&nbsp;VII]]; he had his three youngest children, [[Arsinoe&nbsp;IV]], [[Ptolemy&nbsp;XIII]], and [[Ptolemy&nbsp;XIV]], with an unknown mother. His uncle, Ptolemy&nbsp;X, had left Egypt to [[Rome]] in the event there were no surviving heirs, making Roman annexation of Egypt a possibility. In an effort to prevent this, Ptolemy&nbsp;XII established an alliance with Rome late into his first reign. Rome annexed Cyprus in 58 BC, causing Ptolemy of Cyprus to commit suicide. \n\nShortly afterwards, Ptolemy XII was deposed by the Egyptian people and fled to Rome; his eldest daughter, Berenice&nbsp;IV, took the throne. With funding and military assistance from the Roman Republic, Ptolemy&nbsp;XII was able to recapture Egypt and have Berenice&nbsp;IV killed in 55 BC. He named his daughter Cleopatra&nbsp;VII as his co-regent in 52 BC. He died the next year and was succeeded by Cleopatra and her brother, Ptolemy&nbsp;XIII, as joint rulers.\n\n==Background and early life==\n[[File:PtolemyIX-StatueHead MuseumOfFineArtsBoston.png|thumb|left|Bust of [[Ptolemy IX Soter]].]]\n[[File:Mithridates VI Louvre.jpg|thumb|Bust of [[Mithridates VI Eupator|Mithridates VI of Pontus]].]]\nPtolemy XII was the oldest son of [[Ptolemy IX Soter]]. The identity of his mother is uncertain. Ptolemy IX was married twice, to his sister [[Cleopatra IV]] from around 119 BC until he was forced to divorce her in 115 BC, and secondly to another sister [[Cleopatra Selene of Syria|Cleopatra Selene]] from 115 BC, until he abandoned her during his flight from Alexandria in 107 BC. However, [[Cicero]] and other ancient sources refer to Ptolemy XII as an [[legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] son; [[Gnaeus Pompeius Trogus|Pompeius Trogus]] called him a \"[[:wikt:nothus|nothos]]\" (bastard), while [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] wrote that Ptolemy IX had no legitimate sons at all.<ref>[[Cicero]] ''Agr.'' 2.42; [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] 1.9.3</ref>{{sfn|Sullivan|1990|p= 92}} Some scholars have therefore proposed that his mother was a concubine \u2013 probably an [[Hellenistic Greeks|Alexandrian Greek]],<ref name=\"DH\">Dodson, Aidan and Hilton, Dyan. The Complete Royal Families of Ancient Egypt. Thames & Hudson. 2004. {{ISBN|0-500-05128-3}}</ref><ref>Ernle Bradford, ''Classic Biography: Cleopatra'' (Toronto: The Penguin Groups, 2000), p. 28.</ref>{{sfnp|Lefkowitz|1997|pp=44\u201345, 50}}{{sfnp|Schiff|2011|pp=24}} but possibly a member of the Egyptian elite.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|p=222}}{{sfn|Hu\u00df|1990|p=203}}<ref group=\"note\">{{harvtxt|Lefkowtiz|1997|}} [[Mary Lefkowitz]] rejects the notion of an Egyptian mother to Ptolemy XII. Afrocentric claims that Cleopatra's paternal grandmother was a black Egyptian woman contend that is why Cleopatra spoke Egyptian. Lefkowitz notes, however, that if Cleopatra's paternal grandmother had been Egyptian, it would have been more likely Ptolemy XII was the first speaker of the Egyptian language, instead of his daughter Cleopatra.</ref> However, Chris Bennett argues that Ptolemy XII's mother was Cleopatra IV and that he was considered illegitimate simply because she had never been co-regent.{{sfn|Bennett|1997|p=46}} This theory is endorsed by the historian [[Adrian Goldsworthy]].{{sfn|Goldsworthy|2011|pp=69\u201370}}\n\nThe date of Ptolemy XII's birth is thus uncertain.{{sfn|Stanwick|2010|p=60}} If he was the son of Cleopatra IV, he was probably born around 117 BC and followed around a year later by a brother, known as [[Ptolemy of Cyprus]]. In 117 BC, Ptolemy IX was governor of [[Cyprus]], but in 116 BC his father [[Ptolemy VIII]] died and he returned to Alexandria, becoming the junior co-regent of his grandmother [[Cleopatra II]] and his mother [[Cleopatra III]]. Cleopatra II died in 115 BC and shortly afterwards Cleopatra III forced Ptolemy IX to divorce his sister-wife Cleopatra IV, who was sent off to marry the [[Seleucid]] king [[Antiochus IX Cyzicenus]]. She was murdered by his rival in 114 BC. Ptolemy IX meanwhile had been remarried to Cleopatra Selene, with whom he had a daughter, [[Berenice III]].{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|p=206-207}} By 109 BC, Ptolemy IX had begun the process of introducing Ptolemy XII to public life. In that year, Ptolemy XII served as the Priest of Alexander and Ptolemaic kings (an office which Ptolemy IX otherwise held himself throughout his reign) and had a festival established in his honour in [[Cyrene, Libya|Cyrene]].<ref>''[[Supplementum Epigraphicum Graecum|SEG]]'' IX.5.</ref><ref name=CBP12>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Ptolemy IX|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/ptolemy_ix_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref> Relations between Ptolemy IX and his mother deteriorated. In 107 BC she forced him to flee Alexandria for Cyprus and replaced him as co-regent with his younger brother [[Ptolemy X Alexander]].{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|p=206-207}} [[Justin (historian)|Justin]] mentions that Ptolemy IX left two sons behind when he fled Alexandria.<ref>Justin ''Epitome of the Philippic History'' 39.4</ref> Chris Bennett argues that these sons should be identified as Ptolemy XII and Ptolemy of Cyprus.{{sfn|Bennett|1997|p=46}}\n\nPtolemy IX made an attempt to reclaim the Ptolemaic throne in 103 BC, by invading [[Judaea]]. At the start of this war, Cleopatra III sent her grandsons to the island of [[Kos]] along with her treasure in order to protect them.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''Antiquities of the Jews'' 13.13.1</ref>{{sfn|Whitehorne|1994|p=139}} There, Ptolemy XII and Ptolemy of Cyprus seem to have been captured by [[Mithridates VI of Pontus]] in 88 BC, at the outbreak of the [[First Mithridatic War]].<ref name=CBP12/>{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|p=211-213}} Ironically, their father had reclaimed the Egyptian throne around the same time. They were held by Mithridates as hostages until 80 BC. At some point during this period, probably in 81 or 80 BC, they were engaged to two of Mithridates' daughters, Mithridatis and Nyssa.<ref>[[Appian]], ''Mithridatica'' 16.111</ref> Meanwhile, Ptolemy IX died in December 81 BC and was succeeded by Berenice III. In April 80 BC, [[Ptolemy XI Alexander II]], the son of Ptolemy X, was installed as her co-regent, promptly murdered her, and was himself killed by an angry Alexandrian mob. The Alexandrians then summoned Ptolemy XII to return to Egypt and assume the kingship; his brother became king of Cyprus, where he would reign until 58 BC.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|p=222}}{{sfn|Bradford|2000|p=33}}{{sfn|Roller|2010|p=17}}\n\n==First reign (80\u201358 BC)==\n[[File:Flickr - archer10 (Dennis) - Egypt-14A-024.jpg|thumb|Egyptian-style statue of Ptolemy XII found at the Temple of the Crocodile in [[Fayoum]], Egypt.]]\n\nOn his arrival in Alexandria, in April 80 BC, Ptolemy XII was proclaimed king. His reign was officially dated as having begun on the death of his father in 81 BC, thereby eliding the reigns of Berenice III and Ptolemy X. Shortly after his accession, Ptolemy married [[Cleopatra V of Egypt|Cleopatra Tryphaena]].{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=222-223}} Her parentage is uncertain - modern scholarship often interprets her as a sister,{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=222-223}} but Christopher Bennett argues that she was a daughter of Ptolemy X.{{sfn|Bennett|1997|p=39}} The couple became co-regents and were encorporated into the Ptolemaic dynastic cult together as the ''Theoi Philopatores kai Philadelphoi'' (Father-loving and Sibling-loving Gods). This title was probably meant to reinforce Ptolemy XII's claim to the throne in the face of claims that his parentage meant that he was an illegitimate son of Ptolemy IX and therefore not entitled to rule.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=222-223}} \n\nIn 76 BC, the [[High Priest of Ptah]] in [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] died and Ptolemy XII travelled to Memphis to appoint his fourteen-year-old son, [[Pasherienptah III]], as the new High Priest. In turn, Pasherienptah III crowned Ptolemy as [[Pharaoh]] and then went to Alexandria, where he was appointed as Ptolemy XII's 'prophet'. These encounters are described in detail on Pasherienptah's funerary stela, ''Stele BM 866'', and they demonstrate the extremely close and mutually reinforcing relationship that had developed between the Ptolemaic kings and the Memphite priesthood by this date.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=222-223}}\n\nIn August 69 BC, Cleopatra V ceases to be mentioned as co-regent. The images of her that had been carved on the main [[Pylon (architecture)|pylon]] of the [[Temple of Horus]] at [[Edfu]] were covered over at this time. The reason for this sudden shift is unknown, but presumably she was divorced at this time.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=222-223}} Ptolemy adopted a new royal epithet ''Neos Dionysos'' (New Dionysus) at some time after this; Chris Bennett proposes that the epithet was linked to the break with Cleopatra.<ref name=CBP12/>\n\n===Relations with Rome===\n[[File:Pompey the Great.jpg|thumb|[[Pompey]], Ptolemy XII's key ally in Rome.]]\n[[File:Ptolemy XII Auletes - 185.jpg|thumb|Relief of Ptolemy XII from the [[Temple of Kom Ombo|double temple at Kom Ombo]].]]\n[[File:Edfu Temple 9609.JPG|thumb|First [[pylon (architecture)|pylon]] at [[Edfu]] [[Temple of Edfu|Temple]], which Ptolemy XII decorated with figures of himself smiting the enemy.]]\nWhen Ptolemy X had died in 88 BC, his will had left Egypt to Rome in the event that he had no surviving heirs. Although the Romans had not acted on this, the possibility that they might forced the following Ptolemies to adopt a careful and respectful policy towards Rome.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=223-224}}{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=307}} Ptolemy XII continued this pro-Roman policy in order to protect himself and secure his dynasty's fate. However, Egypt came under increasing Roman pressure nevertheless. In 65 BC, the [[Roman censor]], [[Marcus Licinius Crassus]] proposed that the Romans annex of Egypt.<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Life of Crassus'' 13.2</ref> This proposal failed in the face of opposition from [[Quintus Lutatius Catulus]] and [[Cicero]]. In light of this crisis, however, Ptolemy XII began to expend significant resources on bribing Roman politicians to support his interests. In 63 BC, when [[Pompey]] was reorganising Syria and Anatolia following his victory in the [[Third Mithridatic War]], Ptolemy sought to form a relationship with Pompey by sending him a golden crown. Ptolemy also provided pay and maintenance for 8,000 cavalry to Pompey for his war with [[Judaea]]. He also asked Pompey to come to Alexandria and help to put down a revolt which had apparently broken out in Egypt; Pompey refused.<ref>[[Appian]], ''Mithridatica'' 114; [[Josephus]], ''Antiquities of the Jews'' 14.35</ref>{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=223-224}}{{sfn|Bradford|2000|p=35}}\n\nThe money required for these bribes was enormous. Initially, Ptolemy XII funded them by raising taxes. A strike by farmers of royal land in [[Herakleopolis]] which is attested in a papyrus document from 61/60 BC has been interpreted as a sign of widespread discontent with this taxation. Increasingly, Ptolemy XII also had recourse to loans from Roman bankers, such as [[Gaius Rabirius Postumus]]. This gave the Romans even more leverage over his regime and meant that the fate of Egypt became an increasingly immediate issue in Roman politics.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=223-224}} \n\nFinally, in 60 BC, Ptolemy XII travelled to Rome, where the [[First Triumvirate]], composed of Pompey, Crassus, and [[Julius Caesar]], had just taken power, in order to negotiate official recognition of his kingship. Ptolemy paid Pompey and Caesar six thousand [[Talent (measurement)|talents]] - an enormous sum, equivalent to the total annual revenue of Egypt.<ref>[[Suetonius]] ''Life of Julius Caesar'' 54.3</ref> In return, a formal alliance or ''foedus'' was formed. The [[Roman Senate]] recognised Ptolemy as king and Caesar passed a law that added Ptolemy to the list of friends and allies of the people of Rome (''amici et socii populi Romani'') in 59 BC.<ref>[[Caesar]] ''[[Commentarii de Bello Civili|Bellum Civile]]'' 3.107; [[Cicero]], ''Pro Rabirio Postumo'' 3; Cicero, ''Letter to Atticus'' 2.16.2</ref>{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=316}}{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=225-226}} \n \nIn 58 BC, the Romans [[Roman Cyprus|took control of Cyprus]], causing its ruler, Ptolemy XII's brother, to commit suicide.{{sfn|Roller|2010|p=22}} Ptolemy XII took no action in response to his brother's death and Cyprus remained a Roman province until returned to Ptolemaic control by Julius Caesar in 48 BC.{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=226-227}}\n\n==Exile in Rome (58-55 BC)==\n{{further|Early life of Cleopatra}}\nThe bribery policy had been unpopular in Egypt for a long time, both because of its obsequiousness and because of the heavy tax burden that it entailed, but the annexation of Cyprus demonstrated its failure and enraged the people of Alexandria. The courtiers in Alexandria forced Ptolemy to step down from the thone and leave Egypt.<ref>[[Cassius Dio]] 39.12; [[Plutarch]], ''Life of Pompey'' 49.7.</ref> He was replaced by his daughter Berenice IV, who ruled jointly with Cleopatra Tryphaena, who is probably Ptolemy XII's former wife but may be an otherwise unattested daughter. Following Cleopatra Tryphaena's death a year later, Berenice ruled alone from 57 to 56 BC.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=324}}{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=226-227}}\n\n[[File:Denier \u00e0 l'effigie de Pomp\u00e9e.jpg|thumb|left|A [[denarius]] of Pompey minted 49-48 BC]]\nTaking his daughter Cleopatra with him, Ptolemy fled for the safety of Rome.{{sfn|Bradford|2000|p=37}} On the way, he stopped in [[Rhodes]] where the exiled [[Cato the Younger]] offered him advice on how to approach the Roman aristocracy, but no tangible support. In Rome, Ptolemy XII prosecuted his restitution but met opposition from certain members of the Senate. His old ally Pompey housed the exiled king and his daughter and argued on behalf of Ptolemy's restoration in the Senate.<ref>[[Strabo]] ''Geography'' 17.1.11; [[Cassius Dio]] 39.14.3</ref>{{sfn|H\u00f6lbl|2001|pp=226-227}} During this time, Roman creditors realized that they would not get the return on their loans to the king without his restoration.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=323}} In 57 BC, pressure from the Roman public forced the Senate's decision to restore Ptolemy. However, Rome did not wish to invade Egypt to restore the king, since the [[Sibylline books]] stated that if an Egyptian king asked for help and Rome proceeded with military intervention, great dangers and difficulties would occur.{{sfn|Bradford|2000|pp=39\u201340}}\n\nEgyptians heard rumours of Rome's possible intervention and disliked the idea of their exiled king's return. The Roman historian [[Cassius Dio]] wrote that a group of one hundred men were sent as envoys from Egypt to make their case to the Romans against Ptolemy XII's restoration. Ptolemy seemingly had their leader [[Dio of Alexandria]] poisoned and most of the other protesters killed before they reached Rome.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=325}}\n\n==Restoration and Second Reign (55\u201351 BC)==\n{{further|Early life of Cleopatra|Reign of Cleopatra}}\n[[File:Ptolemy xii.png|thumb|120px|Rare [[drachma]] of Ptolemy XII minted at [[Paphos]], [[History of Cyprus|Cyprus]] in 53 BC,{{sfn|Svoronos|1904|loc=vol. I-II, [[iarchive:tanomismatatoukrv1v2sbor/page/302|p. 302]] (n\u00b01838), & vol. III-IV, [[iarchive:tanomismatatoukrv3v4sbor/page/n127|plate LXI]], n\u00b022, 23.}} depicting him instead of [[Ptolemy I Soter|Ptolemy I]]]]\n[[File:Cleopatra VII, dalla via appia tra ariccia e genzano, 40-30 ac ca. 02.JPG|thumb|125px|[[Roman portraiture|Roman bust]] of [[Cleopatra VII]], [[Altes Museum]], [[Antikensammlung Berlin]]]]\nIn 55 BC, Ptolemy paid [[Aulus Gabinius]] 10,000 talents to invade Egypt and so recovered his throne. Gabinius defeated the Egyptian frontier forces, marched to Alexandria, and attacked the palace, where the palace guards surrendered without fighting.{{sfn|Bradford|2000|p=43}} The exact date of Ptolemy XII's restoration is unknown; the earliest possible date of restoration was 4 January 55 BC and the latest possible date was 24 June the same year. Upon regaining power, Ptolemy acted against Berenice, and along with her supporters, she was executed. Ptolemy XII maintained his grip on power in Alexandria with the assistance of around two thousand Roman soldiers and mercenaries, known as the [[Gabiniani]]. This arrangement enabled Rome to exert power over Ptolemy, who ruled until he fell ill in 51 BC.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=338}} On 31 May 52 BC his daughter Cleopatra VII was named as his coregent.{{sfn|Roller|2010|p=27}}\n\nAt the moment of Ptolemy XII's restoration, Roman creditors demanded the repayment of their loans, but the Alexandrian treasury could not repay the king's debt. Learning from previous mistakes, Ptolemy XII shifted popular resentment of tax increases from himself to a Roman, his main creditor [[Gaius Rabirius Postumus]], whom he appointed ''[[dioiketes]]'' (minister of finance), and so in charge of debt repayment. Perhaps Gabinius had also put pressure on Ptolemy XII to appoint Rabirius, who now had direct access to the financial resources of Egypt but exploited the land too much. The king had to imprison Rabirius to protect his life from the angry people, then allowed him to escape. Rabirius immediately left Egypt and went back to Rome at the end of 54 BC. There he was accused ''de repetundis'', but defended by [[Cicero]] and probably acquitted.<ref>Cicero.</ref>{{sfn|Hu\u00df|2001|pp=696\u2013697}} Ptolemy also permitted a debasing of the coinage as an attempt to repay the loans. Near the end of Ptolemy's reign, the value of Egyptian coinage dropped to about fifty per cent of its value at the beginning of his first reign.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|pp=332\u2013334}}\n\nPtolemy XII died sometime before 22 March 51 BC.{{sfn|Roller|2010|pp=53, 56}} His will stipulated that Cleopatra VII and her brother Ptolemy XIII should rule Egypt together. To safeguard his interests, he made the people of Rome executors of his will. Since the Senate was busy with its own affairs, his ally Pompey approved the will.{{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=339}} According to the author Mary Siani-Davies:\n\n{{Quote\n|text=Throughout his long-lasting reign the principal aim of Ptolemy was to secure his hold on the Egyptian throne so as to eventually pass it to his heirs. To achieve this goal he was prepared to sacrifice much: the loss of rich Ptolemaic lands, most of his wealth and even, according to Cicero, the very dignity on which the mystique of kingship rested when he appeared before the Roman people as a mere supplicant.\n|author=Mary Siani-Davies\n|title=\"Ptolemy XII Auletes and the Romans\"\n|source=''Historia'' (1997) {{sfn|Siani-Davies|1997|p=339}}\n}}\n\n==Regime==\nGenerally, descriptions of Ptolemy XII portray him as weak and self-indulgent, drunk, or a lover of music.{{sfn|Bradford|2000|p=34}} According to Strabo, his practice of playing the flute earned him the ridiculing [[sobriquet]] ''Auletes'' ('flute player'):\n\n{{Quote\n|text=\"Now all of the kings after the third Ptolemy, being corrupted by luxurious living, administered the affairs of government badly, but worst of all were the fourth, seventh, and the last, Auletes, who, apart from his general licentiousness, practised the accompaniment of choruses with the flute, and upon this he prided himself so much that he would not hesitate to celebrate contests in the royal palace, and at these contests would come forward to vie with the opposing contestants.\"\n|author=Strabo\n|title=XVII, 1, 11\n|source=<!-- ''Book Title'' (date) --><ref>Strabo XVII, 1, 11.</ref>\n}}\n\n==Marriage and issue==\nPtolemy married his sister [[Cleopatra V Tryphaena]] who was with certainty the mother of his eldest known child, [[Berenice IV]].{{sfn|Tyldesley|2006|p=200}} Cleopatra V disappears from court records a few months after the birth of Ptolemy's second known child,{{sfn|Roller|2010|pp=16, 19, 159}} and probably hers, [[Cleopatra VII]] in 69 BC.{{sfn|Roller|2010|pp=16, 19, 159}}{{sfn|Grant|1972|p=4}}{{sfn|Preston|2009|p=22}}{{sfn|Jones|2006|p=xiii}}{{sfn|Schiff|2010|p=28}}{{sfn|Kleiner|2005|p=22}}{{sfn|Tyldesley|2006|pp=30, 235\u2013236}} The identity of the mother of the last three of Ptolemy's children, in birth order [[Arsinoe IV]], [[Ptolemy XIII Theos Philopator]], and [[Ptolemy XIV]], is also uncertain. One hypothesis contends that possibly they (and perhaps Cleopatra VII) were Ptolemy XII's children with a theoretical half [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonian]] [[Ancient Macedonians|Greek]], half Egyptian woman belonging to a priestly family from [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] in northern Egypt,{{sfn|Roller|2010|pp=16, 19, 159}} but this is only speculation.{{sfn|Goldsworthy|2011|pp=127, 128}}\n\nThe philosopher [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] (c. 234 \u2013 c. 305 AD) wrote of Ptolemy XII's daughter [[Cleopatra VI Tryphaena]], who reigned alongside her sister Berenice.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.attalus.org/translate/eusebius1.html#167 |title=Eusebius: Chronicle p. 167, accessed online |access-date=31 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212084230/http://attalus.org/translate/eusebius1.html#167 |archive-date=12 December 2010 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Greek historian [[Strabo]] (c. 63 BC \u2013 c. AD 24) stated that the king had only three daughters of whom the eldest has been referred to as Berenice IV.<ref>[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A2*.html#1.11 Strabo, Geography, Book XVII, pp. 45\u201347, accessed online]</ref> This suggests that the Cleopatra Tryphaena mentioned by Porphyry may not have been Ptolemy's daughter, but his wife. Many experts now identify Cleopatra VI with Cleopatra V.{{sfn|Tyldesley|2006|p=200}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name!!Image!!Birth!!Death!!Notes\n|-\n|[[Berenice IV]]|| || 79-75 BC || early 55 BC|| Queen of Egypt (June 58 BC \u2013 early 55 BC)<ref name=CBB4>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Berenice IV|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/berenice_iii_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cleopatra VII]]||[[File:Bust_of_Cleopatra_VII_-_Altes_Museum_-_Berlin_-_Germany_2017.jpg|90px]]||December 70 BC or January 69 BC||12 August 30 BC|| Queen of Egypt (51 - 30 BC)<ref name=CBC7>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Cleopatra VII|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/cleopatra_vii_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Arsinoe IV]]|| ||63-61 BC?|| 41 BC||Queen of Cyprus in 48 BC, claimed queenship of Egypt from late 48 BC until expelled by [[Julius Caesar]] in early 47 BC<ref name=CBA4>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Arsinoe IV|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/arsinoe_iv_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ptolemy XIII]]|| ||62-61 BC||13 January 47 BC||Co-regent with Cleopatra VII (51 \u2013 47 BC)<ref name=CBP13>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Ptolemy XIII|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/ptolemy_xiii_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Ptolemy XIV]]||[[File:Ptolemy XIV.jpg|90px]]||60-59 BC ||June-September 44 BC||Co-regent with Cleopatra VII (47 \u2013 44 BC)<ref name=CBP14>{{cite web |last1=Bennett |first1=Chris |title=Ptolemy XIV|url=http://instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/ptolemy_xiv_fr.htm|website=Egyptian Royal Genealogy |accessdate=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes|align=left\n|title=Ancestors of Ptolemy XII of Egypt\n\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. [[Ptolemy XII Auletes]]\n|2= 2. [[Ptolemy IX Lathyros]]\n|3= 3. uncertain\n|4= 4. [[Ptolemy VIII Physcon]]\n|5= 5. [[Cleopatra III of Egypt]]\n|6=\n|7=\n|8= 8. [[Ptolemy V Epiphanes]]\n|9= 9. [[Cleopatra I of Egypt]]\n|10= 10. [[Ptolemy VI Philometor]] (brother of no. 4)\n|11= 11. [[Cleopatra II of Egypt]] (sister of no. 4)\n|12=\n|13=\n|14=\n|15=\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n===Primary sources===\n*[[Cassius Dio]] [http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11607/pg11607-images.html 39.12 \u2013 39.14, 39.55 \u2013 39.58]\n*{{cite book |last1=Cicero|first1=Marcus Tullius  |author-link1=Cicero |translator-last1= |translator-first1= |date=2018 |orig-year=54 BC |title=pro Rabirio Postumo|script-title= |trans-title=In Defense of Gaius Rabirius Postumus |url=http://perseus.uchicago.edu/perseus-cgi/citequery3.pl?dbname=LatinAugust2012&query=Cic.%20Rab.%20Post.&getid=1 |series=Latin Texts & Translations |language=English |publication-date= |access-date= }} {{free access}}\n*[[Strabo]] [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0239%3Abook%3D12%3Achapter%3D3%3Asection%3D34 12.3.34] and [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0239%3Abook%3D17%3Achapter%3D1%3Asection%3D12 17.1.11]\n\n===Secondary sources===\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Bennett |first1=Christopher J. |date=1997  |title=Cleopatra V Tryph\u00e6na and the Genealogy of the Later Ptolemies |journal= Ancient Society |volume= 28 |issue= |pages=39\u201366 |doi= 10.2143/AS.28.0.630068|issn=0066-1619|jstor=44079777 }} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last= Bradford |first= Ernle Dusgate Selby|date=2000  |title=Cleopatra |url=https://archive.org/details/cleopatra00brad/page/n1 |location=London |publisher=Penguin Books |page= |isbn=978-0141390147 |author-link=Ernle Bradford }} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Goldsworthy |first=Adrian Keith |title=Antony and Cleopatra |location=London |publisher=Phoenix |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-300-16534-0 |author-link=Adrian Goldsworthy}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last= Grant|first= Michael |date=1972 |title=Cleopatra |url= https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.524570/page/n1 |location=Edison, NJ |publisher=Barnes and Noble Books |page= |isbn=978-0880297257 |author-link=Michael Grant (classicist) }} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |last1=H\u00f6lbl |first1=G\u00fcnther |title=A History of the Ptolemaic Empire |date=2001 |publisher=Routledge |location=London & New York |isbn=0415201454 |pages=222-230|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Hu\u00df |first=Werner |title=\u00c4gypten in hellenistischer Zeit 332\u201330 v. Chr. (Egypt in Hellenistic times 332\u201330 BC) |location=Munich |year=2001 |issn=0307-5133 |author-link=Werner Hu\u00df}} (in German)\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Jones  |first=Prudence J. |date=2006  |title=Cleopatra: a sourcebook |url=https://archive.org/details/cleopatrasourceb0000jone|url-access=registration |location=Norman, Oklahoma |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |page= |isbn=9780806137414 |author-link= }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Kleiner |first=Diana E. E. |date=2005 |title=Cleopatra and Rome |url=https://archive.org/details/cleopatrarome00dian |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University Press |page= |isbn=9780674019058 |author-link= }} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Lefkowitz |first=Mary R. |title=Not out of Africa: How Afrocentrism became an Excuse to Teach Myth as History |url=https://archive.org/details/notoutofafricaho00lefk_1 |location=New York |publisher=Basic Books |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-465-09838-5 |author-link=Mary Lefkowitz}} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Mahaffy |first=John Pentland |title=A History of Egypt under the Ptolemaic Dynasty |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.88831/page/n8 |volume=IV |location=New York |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |year=1899 |isbn= |author-link=John Pentland Mahaffy }} {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Preston |first=Diana |date=2009 |title=Cleopatra and Antony |url=https://archive.org/details/cleopatraantonyp00pres_0 |location=New York |publisher=Walker & Company |page= |isbn=978-0802710598 |author-link=Diana Preston }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Roller |first=Duane W. |date=2010 |title=Cleopatra: a Biography |url=https://archive.org/details/cleopatrabiograp00roll_0 |location= |publisher=Oxford University Press |page= |isbn=978-0-195-36553-5 |author-link= }} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Schiff |first=Stacy |title=Cleopatra: A Life |location=New York |publisher=Back Bay Books |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-316-12180-4 |author-link=Stacy Schiff }}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last=Siani-Davies |first=Mary |title=Ptolemy XII Auletes and the Romans |journal=Historia |volume=46 |issue=3 |pages=306\u2013340 |year=1997 |jstor=4436474 }} {{registration required|nolink=1}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Stanwick |first=Paul Edmund |title=Portraits of the Ptolemies: Greek Kings as Egyptian Pharaohs |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qllfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Paul+Edmund+Stanwick%22#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn= 9780292777729 |year=2010 }}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Svoronos |first=Ioannis |title=Ta nomismata tou kratous ton Ptolemaion |url=https://archive.org/search.php?query=Ta%20nomismata%20tou%20kratous%20ton%20Ptolemaion |volume=Volumes 1 & 2, and 3 & 4 |location=Athens |year=1904 |oclc=54869298 |author-link=Ioannis Svoronos}} (in Greek and German) {{free access}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv |last=Tyldesley |first=Joyce |date=2006 |title=Chronicle of the Queens of Egypt |url=https://archive.org/details/chronicleofqueen00tyld |location=London |publisher=Thames & Hudson |page= |isbn=9780500051450 |author-link=Joyce Tyldesley }}\n*{{cite book |last=Whitehorne |first=John |title=Cleopatras |publisher=Routledge |year=1994 |isbn=978-0-415-05806-3 |ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080511211402/http://www.tyndale.cam.ac.uk/Egypt/ptolemies/ptolemy_xii.htm Ptolemy XII] by Christopher Bennett (part of his [http://www.instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/index.htm ''Egyptian Royal Genealogy''])\n*[https://www.britannica.com/biography/Ptolemy-XII-Auletes Ptolemy XII Auletes] from the online ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/home.html Strabo ''The Geography''] in English translation, ed. H.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Jones (1924), at LacusCurtius (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/home.html Cassius Dio ''Roman History''] in English translation by Cary (1914\u20131927), at LacusCurtius (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Africa/Egypt/_Texts/BEVHOP/12*.html The House of Ptolemy, Chapter&nbsp;XII] by [[Edwyn Bevan|E.&nbsp;R.&nbsp;Bevan]] (Bill Thayer's Web Site)\n*[http://virtualreligion.net/iho/ptolemy_12.html Ptolemy XII Auletes (ca. 112 - 51 BCE)] entry in historical sourcebook by Mahlon H. Smith\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Ptolemaic dynasty]]||ca. 117 BC||ca. 51 BC}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ptolemy XI]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Pharaohs#Ptolemaic Dynasty|Pharaoh of Egypt]]|years=80 BC-58 BC\n|regent1='''[[Cleopatra V]]/[[Cleopatra VI|VI]]'''}}\n{{s-aft|after=Cleopatra V/VI<br>[[Berenice IV]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Berenice IV}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Pharaohs#Ptolemaic Dynasty|Pharaoh of Egypt]]|years=55 BC-51 BC\n|regent1='''[[Cleopatra VII]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ptolemy XIII Theos Philopator|Ptolemy XIII]]<br>Cleopatra VII}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Hellenistic rulers}}\n{{Pharaohs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ptolemy 12}}\n[[Category:51 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Pharaohs]]\n[[Category:Cleopatra]]\n[[Category:Pharaohs of the Ptolemaic dynasty]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC rulers in Africa]]\n[[Category:2nd-century BC Egyptian people]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Egyptian people]]\n[[Category:Flautists]]\n[[Category:Hellenistic Cyprus]]\n", "name_user": "Sodacan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFirst reign (80\u201358 BC)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ptolemy_XII_Auletes"}
{"title_page": "Metro-land", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Metroland (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Metro-Land (1921).png|thumb|250px|The cover of the Metro-Land guide published in 1921|alt=A painting of a half-timbered house set behind a drive and flower garden. Below the painting the title \"METRO-LAND\" is in capitals and in smaller text is the price of two-pence.]]\n'''Metro-land''' (or '''Metroland''') is a name given to the [[suburban]] areas that were built to the north-west of London in the counties of [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Middlesex]] in the early part of the 20th century that were served by the [[Metropolitan Railway]]. The railway company was in the privileged position of being allowed to retain surplus land; from 1919 this was developed for housing by the nominally independent [[Metropolitan Railway Country Estates|Metropolitan Railway Country Estates Limited]] (MRCE). The term \"Metro-land\" was coined by the Met's marketing department in 1915 when the ''Guide to the Extension Line'' became the ''Metro-land guide''. It promoted a dream of a modern home in beautiful countryside with a fast railway service to central London until the Met was absorbed into the  [[London Passenger Transport Board]] in 1933.\n\n==Metropolitan Railway==\n[[File:Metro-land-map.jpg|right|thumb|Map of \"Metro-land\", from the 1924 ''Metro-land'' booklet published by the Metropolitan Railway]]\n[[File:Electric locomotive and train, Metropolitan Railway (CJ Allen, Steel Highway, 1928).jpg|thumb|Metropolitan Railway electric locomotive and train (c.1928)]]\nThe [[Metropolitan Railway]] was a passenger and goods railway that served London from 1863 to 1933, its mainline heading north from the capital's financial heart in [[City of London|the City]] to what were to become the [[Middlesex]] suburbs. Its first line connected the mainline railway termini at {{stnlnk|Paddington}}, {{stnlnk|Euston}} and [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] to the City, and when, on 10 January 1863, this line opened with gas-lit wooden carriages hauled by steam locomotives, it was the world's first underground railway.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=3\u20135}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edwards|first1=Dennis|last2=Pigram|first2=Ron|year=1988|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]|title=The Golden Years of the Metropolitan Railway and the Metro-land Dream|isbn=1-870630-11-4|page=32}}</ref> When, in 1871 plans were presented for an underground railway in Paris, it was called the ''[[Paris M\u00e9tro|M\u00e9tropolitain]]'' in imitation of the line in London.<ref>{{cite book|first=Benson|last=Bobrick|title=Labyrinths of Iron|url=https://archive.org/details/labyrinthsofiron00bobr|url-access=registration|publisher=Newsweek books|year=1981|page=[https://archive.org/details/labyrinthsofiron00bobr/page/142 142]}}</ref> The modern word [[rapid transit|metro]] is a short form of the French word. The railway was soon extended from both ends and northwards via a branch from [[Baker Street tube station|Baker Street]]. It reached [[Hammersmith tube station (Circle and Hammersmith & City lines)|Hammersmith]] in 1864, [[Richmond station (London)|Richmond]] in 1877 and completed the ''[[Circle line (London Underground)|Inner Circle]]'' in 1884,{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=7\u201310}} but the most important route became the line north into the Middlesex countryside, where it stimulated the development of new suburbs. [[Harrow-on-the-Hill station|Harrow]] was reached in 1880, and the line eventually extended as far as {{stnlnk|Verney Junction}} in [[Buckinghamshire]], more than {{convert|50|mi|km|abbr=off}} from Baker Street and the centre of London. From the end of the 19th century, the railway shared tracks with the [[Great Central Railway]] route out of {{rws|Marylebone}}.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=11\u201314}}\n\nElectric traction was introduced in 1905 with [[electric multiple unit]]s operating services between Uxbridge, Harrow-on-the-Hill and Baker Street. To remove steam and smoke from the tunnels in central London, the Metropolitan Railway purchased [[Metropolitan Railway electric locomotives|electric locomotives]], and these were exchanged for steam locomotives on trains at Harrow from 1908.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=24\u201326}} To improve services, more powerful electric and steam locomotives were purchased in the 1920s. A short branch opened from Rickmansworth to Watford in 1925. The {{convert|4|mi|km|adj=on}} long Stanmore branch from Wembley Park was completed in 1932.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=43\u201345}}\n\n===Metro-land===\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n\n | image1 = New houses, Nathans Road, North Wembley, Middlesex - geograph.org.uk - 60876.jpg\n | alt1 = A row of suburban houses with white gabled ends and black timber beams\n | caption1 =\n\n | image2 = Kenmore Road, Kenton - geograph.org.uk - 99153.jpg\n | alt2 = A row of suburban houses with white gabled ends and black timber beams\n | caption2 =\n\n | footer = Metro-Land was characterised by the construction of [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor Revival]] suburban houses (pictured: North Wembley, top, and Kenton, bottom)\n}}\nUnlike other railway companies, which were required to dispose of surplus land, the Met was in a privileged position with clauses in its acts allowing it to retain land that it believed was necessary for future railway use.{{efn|The Land Clauses Consolidation Act 1845 required railways to sell off surplus lands within ten years of the time given for completion of the work in the line's enabling Act.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=134}}}} Initially the surplus land was managed by the Land Committee, made up of Met directors.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=134, 137}} In the 1880s, at the same time as the railway was extending beyond Swiss Cottage and building the workers' estate at Neasden,{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=82\u201383}} roads and sewers were built at Willesden Park Estate, and the land was sold to builders. Similar developments followed at Cecil Park, near [[Pinner]] and, after the failure of the tower at Wembley, plots were sold at Wembley Park.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=140\u2013142}}{{efn|As at Neasden, Cecil Park<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/5829326/Suburbia-that-inspired-Sir-John-Betjeman-to-get-heritage-protection.html|title=Suburbia that inspired Sir John Betjeman to get heritage protection|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2009|accessdate=19 May 2012|author=Adams, Stephen}}</ref> and Willesden<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/tps.nsf/Conservation%20area%20pages/LBB-349|title=Willesden Green Conservation Area|work=[[Brent Council]]|date=19 September 2010|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> have both been declared [[Conservation Area (United Kingdom)|conservation areas]].}}\n\nRobert Selbie, then General Manager, thought in 1912 that some professionalism was needed and suggested a company be formed to take over from the Surplus Lands Committee to develop estates near the railway.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=240}} The First World War delayed these plans however, and it was 1919, with the expectation of a housing boom,{{sfn|Green|1987|p=43}} before the MRCE was formed. Concerned that Parliament might reconsider the unique position the Met held, the railway company sought legal advice. The legal opinion was that although the Met had authority to hold land, it had none to develop it, so an independent company was created, although all but one of its directors were also directors of the railway company.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=241\u2013242}} The MRCE went on to develop estates at [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury Garden Village]] near [[Neasden]], [[Wembley Park]], Cecil Park and Grange Estate at [[Pinner]] and the Cedars Estate at [[Rickmansworth]] and create places such as [[Harrow Garden Village]].{{sfn|Green|1987|p=43}}{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=241\u2013242}}\n\nThe term Metro-land was coined by the Met's marketing department in 1915 when the ''Guide to the Extension Line'' became the ''Metro-land'' guide, priced at 1[[\u00a3sd|d]]. This promoted the land served by the Met for the walker, the visitor and later the house-hunter.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=240}} Published annually until 1932, the last full year of independence for the Met, the guide extolled the benefits of \"The good air of the Chilterns,\" using language such as \"Each lover of Metroland may well have his own favourite wood beech and coppice&nbsp;\u2013 all tremulous green loveliness in Spring and russet and gold in October.\"{{sfn|Rowley|2006|pp=206, 207}} The dream promoted was of a modern home in beautiful countryside with a fast railway service to central London.{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}}\n\nFrom about 1914 the company had promoted itself as The Met, but after 1920 the commercial manager, John Wardle, ensured that timetables and other publicity material used the term Metro instead.<ref>{{harvnb|Jackson|1986|pp=195, 325}}, see also the publicity material reprinted in {{harvnb|Simpson|2003|p=70}}</ref>{{efn|Wardle wished a new sign at Euston Square to read EUSTON SQUARE METRO, but he was overruled by Selbie and METROPOLITAN RAILWAY was spelt in full.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=352}}}} Land development also occurred in central London when in 1929 a large, luxurious block of apartments called Chiltern Court opened at Baker Street,{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}}{{efn|Chiltern Court became one of the most prestigious addresses in London. It was home to, among others, the novelists [[Arnold Bennett]] and [[H. G. Wells|H.&nbsp;G.&nbsp;Wells]].{{sfn|Foxell|1996|p=54}} A [[blue plaque]] commemorating Wells was added to the building on 8 May 2002.{{sfn|Horne|2003|p=37}}}} designed by the Met's architect Charles W. Clark, who was also responsible for the design of a number of station reconstructions in outer \"Metro-land\" at this time.{{sfn|Green|1987|p=44}}\n\nA few large houses had been built on parts of [[Wembley Park]], south-west of the Metropolitan station, as early as the 1890s.  In 1906, when [[Edward Watkin|Watkin]]\u2019s Tower closed, the Tower Company had become the Wembley Park Estate Company (later Wembley Ltd.), with the aim of developing [[Wembley]] as a residential suburb.\n\nUnlike other railways, from an early date the Metropolitan Railway had bought land alongside its line and then developed housing on it.  In the 1880s and 1890s it had done so with the Willesden Park Estate near Willesden Green station, and in the early 1900s it developed on land in Pinner, as well as planning the expansion of [[Wembley Park]].\n\nIn 1915 by the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s publicity department had created the term Metro-land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2015/sep/10/metroland-100-years-england-original-vision-suburbia|title=Metroland, 100 years on: what's become of England\u2019s original vision of suburbia?|last=Forrest|first=Adam|date=2015-09-10|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>  It was used as the new name for the company\u2019s annual guide to the places it served (known as Guide to the Extension Line prior to 1915).  The ''Metro-land'' guide, although partly written to attract walkers and day trippers, was clearly primarily intended to encourage the building of suburban homes and create middle-class commuters who would use the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s trains for all their needs.  It was published annually until 1932, but when the Metropolitan became part of London Transport in 1933 the term and guide were abandoned.  By then North-West London was well on the road to its reputation for suburbanisation.\n\nThe 1924 ''Metro-land'' guide describes [[Wembley Park]] as \"rapidly developed of recent years as a residential district\", pointing out that there are several golf courses within a few minutes journey of it.\n\nOver the years during which the guide was published, large numbers of Londoners moved out to the new estates in North-West London.  Some of these estates were developed by MRCE, a company that Robert H. Selbie, the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s General Manager, set up in 1919.  It would eventually build houses along the line, from Neasden reaching far out as Amersham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://middlesexcountypress.com/?page_id=675|title=Metroland: the golden age of mock Tudor {{!}} MIDDLESEX: A ROUNDTRIP IN NOWHERE LAND|website=middlesexcountypress.com|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>\n\nOne of the earliest of these MRCE developments was a 123-acre one at Chalkhill, within the bounds of what was [[Repton]]\u2019s [[Wembley Park]].  MRCE acquired the land shortly after it was created and began selling plots in 1921.  The railway even put in a siding to bring building materials to the estate.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A History of Wembley|last=Hewlett|first=Geoffrey|publisher=Brent Library Service|year=1979|isbn=|location=|pages=215|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe term \u2018Metroland\u2019 (usually seen now without the hyphen) has become shorthand for the suburban areas that were built in North-West London and in Buckinghamshire, Hertfordshire and Middlesex following the Metropolitan branches. It had become immortalised well before the guide stopped being published.  A song called \"My Little Metro-land Home\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.20thcenturylondon.org.uk/mol-nn24634|title=My Little Metroland Home - song sheet {{!}} Explore 20th Century London|website=www.20thcenturylondon.org.uk|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Amersham Museum|title=My Little Metro-Land Home|date=2013-12-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X2PLwXhHoTU|accessdate=2016-07-20}}</ref> had been published in 1920, and [[Evelyn Waugh]]\u2019s novel ''[[Decline and Fall]]'' (1928) has a character marrying a Viscount Metroland.  She reappears, with the title Lady Metroland, in two more of Waugh\u2019s novels; ''Vile Bodies'' (1930) and ''A Handful of Dust'' (1934).\n\nThe [[British Empire Exhibition]] further encouraged the new phenomenon of suburban development.   Wembley\u2019s sewerage was improved, many roads in the area were straightened and widened and new bus services began operating.  Visitors were steadily introduced to Wembley and some later moved to the area when houses had been built to accommodate them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brent.gov.uk/media/387392/Wembley.pdf|title=Places in Brent Wembley and Tokyngton|last=Barres-Baker|first=Malcolm|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1921 and 1928 season ticket sales at [[Wembley Park tube station|Wembley Park]] and neighbouring Metropolitan stations rose by over 700%.  Like the rest of West London, most of [[Wembley Park]] and its environs was fully developed, largely with relatively low-density suburban housing, by 1939.\n\n===Absorption of the Met===\nOn 1 July 1933 the Metropolitan Railway amalgamated with other Underground railways, tramway companies and bus operators to form the [[London Passenger Transport Board]] (LPTB), and the railway became the [[Metropolitan line]] of London Transport. The LPTB was not interested in running goods and freight services and the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) took over all freight traffic. At the same time the LNER became responsible for hauling passenger trains with steam locomotives north of Rickmansworth. The lines north of Aylesbury to Verney Junction and Brill were closed; last train to Brill ran on 30 November 1935 and to Quainton Road and Verney Junction on 2 April 1936. Quainton Road continued to be served by the LNER.{{sfn|Horne|2003|pp=54\u201356}} For a time, the LPTB used the \"Metro-land\" tag: \"Cheap fares to Metro-land and the sea\" were advertised in 1934{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} but the \"Metro-land\" brand was rapidly dropped.{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}} London Transport introduced new slogans such as \"Away by Metropolitan\" and \"Good spot, the Chilterns\".{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nSteam traction continued to be used on the outer sections of what had become the \"[[Metropolitan line]]\" until 1961. From that date Metropolitan trains ran only as far as [[Amersham tube station|Amersham]], with main line services from [[Marylebone railway station|Marylebone]] covering stations between [[Great Missenden railway station|Great Missenden]] and Aylesbury.\n\n==Defining Metro-land==\n[[File:HarrowPanorama.jpg|thumb|250px|The town of [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], referred to as the \"capital city\" of Metro-land]]\nThe ''Metro-land'' guide insisted that Metro-land was \"a country with elastic borders that each visitor can draw for himself\". Indeed, to the extent that the principal features of Metro-land were not unique to the Metropolitan, it has been invoked more generically: for example, by Kathryn Bradley-Hole writing about [[Gunnersbury Park]],<ref>''Country Life'', 22 July 2004{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> and by the London ''Evening Standard'', which, in 2009, under the heading, \"Down the line into Metroland\", identified [[High Barnet]] (Northern line), [[Loughton]] (Central line) and two Metropolitan suburbs, Amersham and Rickmansworth, as \"top locations with an easy commute\".<ref>Anthea Masey in ''Evening Standard'', 21 October 2009{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Even so, ''Metro-land'' was quite firm that, so far as the Buckinghamshire Chilterns were concerned, its \"Grand Duchy\" was confined to the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|hundred]] of [[Burnham (hundred)|Burnham]]: \"the Chilterns round [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire|Marlow]] and the [[High Wycombe|Wycombes]] are not in Metro-land\".\n\nThe architect [[Hugh Casson]] regarded [[Harrow, London|Harrow]] as the \"capital city\" of Metro-land,<ref name=\"StephenHalliday\">Stephen Halliday (2001) ''Underground to Everywhere''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> while [[Arthur Mee]]'s ''King's England'' described [[Wembley]] as its \"epitome\".<ref>Arthur Mee, ''The King's England: London North of the Thames'' (revised Ann Saunders, 1972){{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>  In 2012 a writer for ''Country Life'', referring to plans to build a new high-speed rail link (\"[[HS2]]\") through the Chilterns, dismissed the style of development around Aylesbury as not \"so much suburban as just sub, there being no ''urbs''. However, the spirits lift when, down the road, you reach Waddesdon. You hardly need to be told you're in Rothschildland\", the latter tag an allusion to [[Waddesdon Manor]], the estate managed by the [[Jacob Rothschild, 4th Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] family and owned by the [[National Trust]].<ref>\"CA\" in ''Country Life'', 18 January 2012{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Slogans and references==\nThe Metropolitan\u2019s terminus at Baker Street was \"the gateway to Metro-land\" and Chiltern Court, which opened over the station in 1929 and was headquarters during the [[Second World War]] of the [[Special Operations Executive]], was \"''at'' the gateway to Metro-land\". In similar vein, [[Chorleywood|Chorley Wood]] and [[Chenies]], later described by [[Metro-land#John Betjeman|John Betjeman]] as \"the essential Metro-land\",<ref>''Metro-land'', BBC TV 1973</ref> were \"at the gateway\" of the Chiltern Hills (of which [[Wendover]] was the \"pearl\").<ref>''Metro-land'', 1924 edition{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Literature and songs===\n[[File:Croxley Tube Station - exterior.JPG|thumb|[[Croxley tube station|Croxley Green]] (now Croxley) station (C. W. Clark, 1925)]]\nBefore the end of the First World War [[George R. Sims]] had incorporated the term in verse: \"I know a land where the wild flowers grow/Near, near at hand if by train you go,/Metroland, Metroland\".\n\nBy the 1920s, the word was so ingrained in the consciousness that, in [[Evelyn Waugh]]\u2019s novel, ''[[Decline and Fall]]'' (1928), the Hon Margot Beste-Chetwynd took Viscount Metroland as her second husband. Lady Metroland's second appearance in ''[[Vile Bodies]]'' in 1930 and ''[[A Handful of Dust]]'' in 1934 further reinforces this.<ref>Waugh, Evelyn, A Handful of Dust (London, 1934), 10.</ref>\n\nMetro-land further entered the public psyche with the song ''My Little Metro-land Home'' (lyrics by Boyle Lawrence and music by Henry Thraile, 1920), while another ditty extolled the virtues of the Poplars estate at [[Ruislip]] with the assertion that \"It's a very short distance by rail on the Met/And at the gate you'll find waiting, sweet Violet\".<ref name=\"StephenHalliday\" />\n\n[[Queensbury, London|Queensbury]] and its local surroundings and characters were cited in the song \"Queensbury Station\" by the Berlin-based punk-jazz band [[The Magoo Brothers]] on their album \"Beyond Believable\", released on the Bouncing Corporation label in 1988. The song was written by [[Paul Bonin]] and Melanie Hickford, who both grew up and lived in the area.<ref>[https://mgonline.gema.de/werke/detail.do?title=QUEENSBURY+STATION&dbkey=540612 GEMA database listing for Queensbury Station song, work no.: 2181020-001]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, ''[[Metroland (film)|Metroland]]'' was the title and setting for a movie starring [[Christian Bale]] about the development of the relationship between a husband and wife living in the area. The movie was based on the novel of the same name written by Julian Barnes.\n\n[[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] recorded a song ''Metroland'' on the [[English Electric (album)|English Electric]] album. It was released as a single, with the video showing the singer dreamily gazing out from a train at an idealised suburban landscape.\n\n===\"Live in Metro-land\"===\nIn 1903 the Metropolitan developed a housing estate at Cecil Park, [[Pinner]], the first of many such enterprises over the next thirty years. Overseen by the Metropolitan's general manager from 1908 to 1930, Robert H Selbie, the railway formed its own Country Estates Company in 1919. The slogan, \"Live in Metro-land\", was even etched on the door handles of Metropolitan carriages.\n\nSome stations, such as [[Hillingdon tube station|Hillingdon]] (1923), were built specifically to serve the company's suburban developments. A number, including Wembley Park, [[Croxley tube station|Croxley Green]] (1925) and Stanmore (1932), were designed by Charles W. Clark (who was responsible also for Chiltern Court) in an [[Arts and Crafts movement|Arts and crafts]] \"villa\" style. These were intended to blend with their surroundings, though, in retrospect, they arguably lacked the panache and vision of [[Charles Holden]]'s striking, modern designs for the [[London Underground|Underground]] group in the late 1920s and early 1930s.\n\n===Imitators===\nNearly 70 years later the Chilterns Conservation Board was advertising \"Chilterns Country \u2013 countryside walks from rail stations\" (2004). Drawing no doubt on \"Metro-land, a guide for ramblers\", published by British Railways Southern Region shortly after the Second World War, it referred to the \"Rambleland\" stations of Surrey and Sussex.<ref>S P B Mais (2nd ed 1949) ''Southern Rambles for Londoners''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Spirit of Metro-land==\nThe sentimental and somewhat archaic prose of the ''Metro-land'' guide (\"the Roman road aslant the eastern border ... the innumerable field-paths which mark the labourer's daily route from hamlet to farm\")<ref name=\"ML32\">''Metro-land'', 1932 edition{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> conjured up a rustic [[Garden of Eden|Eden]] \u2013 a [[Middle England]], perhaps<ref>Dominic Sandbrook (2010) ''State of Emergency \u2013 The Way We Were: Britain 1970-1974''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> \u2013 similar to that invoked by [[Stanley Baldwin]] (Prime Minister three times between 1923 and 1937) who, though of manufacturing stock, famously donned the mantle of countryman (\"the tinkle of the hammer on the anvil in the country smithy, the sound of the scythe against the whetstone\").<ref>Speech at the Hotel Cecil, 6 May 1924</ref> As one historian of the London Underground put it wryly, \"the world of Metroland is not cluttered with people: its suburban streets are empty ... There are, it seems, more farm animals than people.\"<ref>Christian Wolmar (2004) ''The Subterranean Railway''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nA more cynical view, that sought to contrast illusion with changing times, was offered in 1934 by the composer and conductor [[Constant Lambert]] who \"conjure[d] up the hideous faux bonhomie of the [[hiker]], noisily wading his way through the petrol pumps of Metroland, singing obsolete [[sea shanty|sea chanties]] ''[sic]'' with the aid of the Week-End Book, imbibing chemically flavoured synthetic beer under the impression that he is tossing off a tankard of 'jolly good [[ale]] and old' ... and astonishing the local garage proprietor by slapping him on the back and offering him a pint of 'four 'alf'\".<ref name=\"ConstantLambert\">Constant Lambert (1934) ''Music Ho!''.</ref> {{efn|'Jolly Good Ale and Old' was a poem by [[John Still]] (''c.''1543\u20131608), [[Bishop of Bath and Wells]], that was included in ''The Week-End Book'', an anthology edited by [[Francis Meynell|Francis]] & Vera Meynell, whose first edition was published in 1924. 'The Wreck of the \"What's Her Name\"' by Ronald Bagnall & Denham Harrison (1912) contained the lines: \"The men they called for smelling-salts, the women shrieked for beer!/Good old glorious beer my lads, not arf, four alf beer!\".<ref name=\"ConstantLambert\" />}}\n\n===Town ''v.'' country===\nWith similar ambiguity, ''Metro-land'' combined idyllic photographs of rural tranquillity with advertising spreads for new, though leafy, housing developments. Herein lay the contradictions well captured by [[Leslie Thomas]] in his novel, ''The Tropic of Ruislip'' (1974): \"in the country but not of it. The fields seemed touchable and yet remote\". Writer and historian [[A. N. Wilson]] reflected how suburban developments of the early 20th century that had been brought within easy reach of London by the railways, \"merely ended up creating an endless [[ribbon development|ribbon]] ... not perhaps either town or country\".<ref name=\"Wilson\">A.N.Wilson (2005) ''After the Victorians''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> In the process, despite ''Metro-land'''s promotion of rusticity, a number of outlying towns and villages were \"swallowed up and lost their identity\".<ref>Charles Whynne-Hammond (1976) ''Towns''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Influence of ''Country Life''====\nWilson noted that the magazine ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'', which had been founded by [[Edward Hudson (magazine owner)|Edward Hudson]] as ''Country Life Illustrated'' in 1897, had influenced this pattern with its advertisements for country houses: \"If you were a stockbroker or a lawyer's wife ... you could perhaps afford a new [[Tudorbethan]] mansion, with an oak staircase and mullioned windows and half-timbered gables, in Godalming or Esher, or [[Amersham]] or Penn\".<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> Of the surrounding landscape, ''Country Life'' itself has observed that, in its early days, it offered\n{{quote|a rose-tinted view of the English countryside ... idyllic villages, vernacular buildings and already dying rural crafts. All were illustrated with hauntingly beautiful photographs. They portrayed a utopian never-never world of peace and plenty in a pre-industrial Britain.<ref>Francesca Scoones in ''Country Life'', 23 November 2006{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n====Growth of Metro-land====\nBy the 1930s the availability of mortgages with an average rate of interest of 4{{1/4}} per cent meant that private housing was well within the range of most middle class and many working-class pockets.<ref>John Stevenson (1984) ''British Society 1914-45''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> This was a potent factor in the  growth of Metro-land: for example, in the first three decades of the 20th century the population of [[Harrow Weald]] rose from 1,500 to 11,000 and that of Pinner from 3,000 to 23,000.<ref>1901 & 1931 censuses</ref> In 1932 Northwick Park was said to have grown over the previous five years at the rate of 1,000 houses annually and [[Rayners Lane]] to \"repay a visit at short intervals to see it grow\".<ref name=\"ML32\"/>\n\n===Sir John Betjeman===\nIn the mid-20th century the spirit of Metro-land was evoked in three \"late chrysanthemums\"<ref>John Betjeman (1954) ''A Few Late Chrysanthemums''</ref> by Sir [[John Betjeman]] (1906\u20131984), Poet Laureate from 1972 until his death: \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\" (\"When melancholy autumn comes to Wembley / And electric trains are lighted after tea\"), \"Middlesex\" (\"Gaily into Ruislip Gardens / Runs the red electric train\") and \"The Metropolitan Railway\" (\"Early Electric! With what radiant hope / Men formed this many-branched electrolier\"). In his autobiographical ''[[Summoned by Bells]]'' (1960) Betjeman recalled that \"Metroland / Beckoned us out to lanes in beechy Bucks\".\n[[File:JB Plaque.JPG|thumb|300px|Betjeman centenary: commemorative plaque unveiled by [[Candida Lycett Green]], Marylebone station, 2 September 2006]]\nDescribed much later by ''The Times'' as the \"hymnologist of Metroland\",<ref>Bill Stock & Alan Hamilton  ''The Times'', 6 January 2007{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Betjeman reached a wider audience with his celebrated documentary for BBC Television, ''[[Metro-land (TV)|Metro-land]]'', directed by [[Edward Mirzoeff]], which was first broadcast on 26 February 1973 and was released as a [[DVD]] 33 years later. The critic [[Clive James]], who judged the programme \"an instant classic\", observed that \"it saw how the district had been destroyed by its own success\".<ref>''The Observer'', 15 December 1974{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nTo mark the centenary of Betjeman's birth his daughter [[Candida Lycett Green]] (born 1942) spearheaded a series of celebratory railway events, including an excursion on 2 September 2006 from Marylebone to Quainton Road, now home of the [[Buckinghamshire Railway Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/UK%20News%20Pages%20Sept%2006/030906_Betj.html|title=Betjeman 'Metroland' special from Marylebone to Quainton Road|date=3 September 2006|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> Lycett Green noted of the planning of this trip that among the fine details considered were which filling to have in the baguettes on the train through Metro-land and how long it would stop on the track so that the poem \"Middlesex\" could be read over the tannoy.<ref>''Country Life'', 8 June 2006{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> The event was in the tradition of earlier commemorations of \"Metro-land\", such as a centenary parade of rolling stock at [[Neasden]] in 1963 and celebrations in 2004 to mark the centenary of the Uxbridge branch.\n\n===''Avenger''land===\nMetro-land (notably west Hertfordshire) formed the backdrop for the 1960s ABC TV series ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'', whose popular imagery was deployed with a twist of fantasy. The archetypal Metro-land subjects (such as the railway station and the quiet suburb) became the settings for fiendish plots and treachery in this series and others, such as ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'', ''[[The Baron]]'' and ''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)]]'', all of which made regular use of locations within easy reach of film studios at [[Borehamwood]] and [[Pinewood Studios|Pinewood]].<ref>[http://avengerland.theavengers.tv/ Avengerland]</ref>\n\n==Escaping Metro-land==\nSome abhorred Metro-land for its predictability and sameness. A. N. Wilson observed that, although semi-detached dwellings of the kind built in the inner Metro-land suburbs in the 1930s \"aped larger houses, the stockbroker Tudorbethan of Edwardian Surrey and Middlesex\", they were in fact \"pokey\". He reflected that\n{{quote|as [the husband] went off to the nearest station every morning ... the wife, half liberated and half slave, stayed behind wondering how many of the newly invented domestic appliances they could afford to purchase, and how long the man would hold on to his job in the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Slump]]. No wonder, when war came, that so many of these suburban prisoners felt a sense of release.<ref name=\"Wilson\" />}}\n\n===Post-war attitudes===\nBy the end of the Second World War architects in general were turning their backs on suburbia; the very word tended to be used pejoratively, even contemptuously. In 1951 [[Michael Young (politician)|Michael Young]], one of the architects of the Labour Party's electoral victory in 1945, observed that \"one suburb is much like another in an atomised society. Rarely does community flourish\", while the American [[Lewis Mumford]], wrote in the ''New Yorker'' in 1953 that \"monotony and suburbanism\" were the result of the \"unimaginative\" design of Britain's post-war [[New Towns]].<ref>[[David Kynaston]] (2009) ''Family Britain 1951-57''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> When the editor of the ''Architectural Review'', [[James Maude Richards|J. M. Richards]], wrote in ''The Castles on the Ground'' (1946) that \"for all the alleged deficiencies of suburban taste ... it holds for ninety out of a hundred Englishmen an appeal which cannot be explained away as some strange instance of mass aberration\", he was, in his own words, \"scorned by my contemporaries as either an irrelevant eccentricity or a betrayal of the forward looking views of the [[Modernism|Modern]] Movement\".<ref>Quoted in David Kynaston (2007) ''Austerity Britain''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nJohn Betjeman admired [[John Piper (artist)|John Piper]]'s illustrations for ''Castles on the Ground'', describing the \"fake half-timber, the leaded lights and bow windows of the Englishman's castle\" as \"the beauty of the despised, patronised suburb\".<ref>John Betjeman (ed Candida Lycett Green, 1997) ''Coming Home''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> However, as the historian [[David Kynaston]] observed sixty years later, \"the time was far from ripe for Metroland nostalgia\".<ref>David Kynaston (2007) ''Austerity Britain''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Julian Barnes: ''Metroland''===\n[[Valerie Grove]], who conceded that Metro-land was \"a kinder word than 'suburbia'\" and referred to the less spoilt areas beyond Rickmansworth as \"Outer Metro-land\", maintained that \"suburbia had no visible history. Anyone with any spirit ... had to get out of Metro-land to make their mark\".<ref>''Times Weekend Review'', 4 September 2004{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThus, the central character of ''[[Metroland (book)|Metroland]]'' (1980), a novel by [[Julian Barnes]] (born 1946) that was [[Metroland (1997 film)|filmed in 1997]], ended up in [[Paris]] during the disturbances of May 1968 \u2013 though, by the late 1970s, having thrown off the yearnings of his youth, he was back in Metro-land. ''Metroland'' recounted the essence of suburbia in the early 1960s and the features of daily travel by a schoolboy, Christopher Lloyd, on the Metropolitan line to and from London. During a French lesson, Christopher declared, \"''J\u2019habite Metroland''\" [\"I live in Metroland\"], because it \"sounds better than Eastwick [the fictional location of his home], stranger than Middlesex\".\n\nIn real life, some schoolboys had made similar journeys for more [[hedonistic]] reasons. Betjeman recalled that, between the wars, boys from [[Harrow School]] had used the Metropolitan for illicit excursions to [[night clubs]] in London: \"Whenever the police raided the [[Hypocrites' Club]] or the Coconut Club, the '43 or the Blue Lantern there would always be Harrovians there\".<ref>David Faber (2005) ''Speaking for England''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Social mobility: ''Tropic of Ruislip''===\nBetween Metro-land\u2019s heyday before the Second World War and the end of the 20th century, the proportion of [[Owner-occupier|owner-occupied]] dwellings in England, already rising fast from the mid-1920s, doubled from a third to two-thirds.<ref>Proportion of dwellings by household tenure, 1938 and 1997: ''Independent Inquiry into Inequalities in Health'' (Chair, Sir Donald Acheson), 1998</ref> In ''[[Tropic of Ruislip]]'', [[Leslie Thomas]]\u2019s humorous account of suburban sexual and social [[mores]] in the mid-1970s (adapted for television as ''Tropic'', ATV 1979), the steady flow of families from council housing on one side of the railway to an executive estate on the other side served to illustrate what was becoming known as \"[[social mobility|upward mobility]]\".{{efn|In 1962 [[Philip Goodhart]], MP for [[Beckenham]], wrote of the parliamentary by-election of that year in the Kent suburb of [[Orpington]], at which a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] majority of over 14,000 was turned into a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] victory, that \"now the extent and growth of this social mobility can be seen for the first time\"<ref>Letter to ''Daily Telegraph'', 23 March 1962, quoted in D. R. Thorpe (2010) ''Supermac: The Life of Harold Macmillan''.{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>}} Another sign was that, by the end of the book, \"half the neighbourhood\" of Plummers Park (probably based on Carpenders Park, on the outskirts of [[Watford]]{{efn|In ''Tropic of Ruislip'', it was possible to hear the rattle of the Metropolitan from Plummers Park. However, although Plummers Park was placed close to Watford \"in the latitude of [[Ruislip]]\", it was said to be thirty miles from Central London, whereas ''Metro-land'' (1932 edition) gave the distance from Ruislip to Baker Street as 13\u00bc miles.}}) had moved south of the [[River Thames]] to [[Wimbledon (London)|Wimbledon]] or nearby [[Southfields]]. This was put down to the \"attractions of [[Victoriana]]\", which, like suburbia itself, championed at the time by Betjeman\u2019s ''Metro-land'', was coming back into fashion; however, it appeared to have just as much to do with couples following each other round in order to maintain extramarital affairs.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAnother glimpse of Metro-land in the 1970s was provided by ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'', the BBC TV comedy series (1975-8) about suburban self sufficiency. Though set in [[Surbiton]], the programme's location filming was carried out in [[Northwood, London|Northwood]], an area reached by the Metropolitan in 1885. A less benign view of Metro-land was offered in the mid [[noughties]] by the detective series, ''[[Murder in Suburbia]]'' (ITV 2004-6), which, though set in the fictional town of Middleford, was also filmed in Northwood and other parts of North West London.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Note on spelling==\nThe form ''Metroland'' is now in common use, but the \"brand\" was hyphenated as ''Metro-land'' or ''METRO-LAND''. Evelyn Waugh, John Betjeman (in \"Summoned by Bells\") and Julian Barnes all dispensed with the hyphen, though Betjeman's documentary of 1973 correctly used \"Metro-land\", as that was the form always employed by the Metropolitan Railway in its brochures and on the trains themselves.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Streetcar suburb]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Oliver|year=1987|title=The London Underground: An illustrated history|publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]]|isbn=0-7110-1720-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Metro-Land|edition=British Empire Exhibition 1924 reprinted|year=2004|isbn=1-904915-00-0|editor-first=Oliver|editor-last=Green|publisher=Southbank Publishing|ref=harv|url=http://www.southbankpublishing.com/9781904915003/introduction.php|accessdate=22 April 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20080628202202/http://www.southbankpublishing.com/9781904915003/introduction.php|archive-date=28 June 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foxell|first=Clive|title=Chesham Shuttle: The Story of a Metropolitan Branch Line|edition=2nd|year=1996|publisher=Clive Foxell|isbn=0-9529184-0-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Horne|first=Mike|title=The Metropolitan Line|year=2003|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=1-85414-275-5|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/metropolitanline00mike}}\n* {{cite book|title=London's Metropolitan Railway|last=Jackson|first=Alan|year=1986|publisher=David & Charles|isbn=0-7153-8839-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The English landscape in the twentieth century|last=Rowley|first=Trevor|year=2006|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Hambledon Continuum]]|isbn=1-85285-388-3|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/englishlandscape0000rowl}}\n* {{cite book|last=Simpson|first=Bill|title=A History of the Metropolitan Railway. Volume 1: The Circle and Extended Lines to Rickmansworth.|publisher=Lamplight Publications|year=2003|isbn=1-899246-07-X|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Alan A. |title=London's Metroland|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=978-1-85414-300-6}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lucey.net/metro-link.htm The Metropolitan and Great Central Railway Joint Committee Survey of 1907]\n* [http://www.metroland.org.uk/ Website for metroland.org.uk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050413040350/http://www.southbankpublishing.com/metroland/ Metro-land from Southbank Publishing]\n* [http://www.davros.org/rail/culg/metropolitan.html Metropolitan line] from Clive's UndergrounD Line Guides\n* [http://avengerland.theavengers.tv/ Avengerland]\n* [http://westlondonchat.com/photos/showphoto.php?photo=1326&title=ruislip-houses-for-sale-in27metro-land-27-magazine-advert&cat=508/ Metroland magazine advert for houses in Ruislip]\n\n{{Metropolitan line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:History of Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:History of Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Amersham]]\n[[Category:Transport design in London]]\n[[Category:History of the London Underground]]\n[[Category:Social history of London]]\n[[Category:Rickmansworth]]\n[[Category:History of Watford]]\n[[Category:Transport in Watford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Metroland (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Metro-Land (1921).png|thumb|250px|The cover of the Metro-Land guide published in 1921|alt=A painting of a half-timbered house set behind a drive and flower garden. Below the painting the title \"METRO-LAND\" is in capitals and in smaller text is the price of two-pence.]]\n'''Metro-land''' (or '''Metroland''') is a name given to the [[suburban]] areas that were built to the north-west of London in the counties of [[Buckinghamshire]], [[Hertfordshire]] and [[Middlesex]] in the early part of the 20th century that were served by the [[Metropolitan Railway]]. The railway company was in the privileged position of being allowed to retain surplus land; from 1919 this was developed for housing by the nominally independent [[Metropolitan Railway Country Estates|Metropolitan Railway Country Estates Limited]] (MRCE). The term \"Metro-land\" was coined by the Met's marketing department in 1915 when the ''Guide to the Extension Line'' became the ''Metro-land guide''. It promoted a dream of a modern home in beautiful countryside with a fast railway service to central London until the Met was absorbed into the  [[London Passenger Transport Board]] in 1933.\n\n==Metropolitan Railway==\n[[File:Metro-land-map.jpg|right|thumb|Map of \"Metro-land\", from the 1924 ''Metro-land'' booklet published by the Metropolitan Railway]]\n[[File:Electric locomotive and train, Metropolitan Railway (CJ Allen, Steel Highway, 1928).jpg|thumb|Metropolitan Railway electric locomotive and train (c.1928)]]\nThe [[Metropolitan Railway]] was a passenger and goods railway that served London from 1863 to 1933, its mainline heading north from the capital's financial heart in [[City of London|the City]] to what were to become the [[Middlesex]] suburbs. Its first line connected the mainline railway termini at {{stnlnk|Paddington}}, {{stnlnk|Euston}} and [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] to the City, and when, on 10 January 1863, this line opened with gas-lit wooden carriages hauled by steam locomotives, it was the world's first underground railway.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=3\u20135}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edwards|first1=Dennis|last2=Pigram|first2=Ron|year=1988|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]]|title=The Golden Years of the Metropolitan Railway and the Metro-land Dream|isbn=1-870630-11-4|page=32}}</ref> When, in 1871 plans were presented for an underground railway in Paris, it was called the ''[[Paris M\u00e9tro|M\u00e9tropolitain]]'' in imitation of the line in London.<ref>{{cite book|first=Benson|last=Bobrick|title=Labyrinths of Iron|url=https://archive.org/details/labyrinthsofiron00bobr|url-access=registration|publisher=Newsweek books|year=1981|page=[https://archive.org/details/labyrinthsofiron00bobr/page/142 142]}}</ref> The modern word [[rapid transit|metro]] is a short form of the French word. The railway was soon extended from both ends and northwards via a branch from [[Baker Street tube station|Baker Street]]. It reached [[Hammersmith tube station (Circle and Hammersmith & City lines)|Hammersmith]] in 1864, [[Richmond station (London)|Richmond]] in 1877 and completed the ''[[Circle line (London Underground)|Inner Circle]]'' in 1884,{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=7\u201310}} but the most important route became the line north into the Middlesex countryside, where it stimulated the development of new suburbs. [[Harrow-on-the-Hill station|Harrow]] was reached in 1880, and the line eventually extended as far as {{stnlnk|Verney Junction}} in [[Buckinghamshire]], more than {{convert|50|mi|km|abbr=off}} from Baker Street and the centre of London. From the end of the 19th century, the railway shared tracks with the [[Great Central Railway]] route out of {{rws|Marylebone}}.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=11\u201314}}\n\nElectric traction was introduced in 1905 with [[electric multiple unit]]s operating services between Uxbridge, Harrow-on-the-Hill and Baker Street. To remove steam and smoke from the tunnels in central London, the Metropolitan Railway purchased [[Metropolitan Railway electric locomotives|electric locomotives]], and these were exchanged for steam locomotives on trains at Harrow from 1908.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=24\u201326}} To improve services, more powerful electric and steam locomotives were purchased in the 1920s. A short branch opened from Rickmansworth to Watford in 1925. The {{convert|4|mi|km|adj=on}} long Stanmore branch from Wembley Park was completed in 1932.{{sfn|Green|1987|pp=43\u201345}}\n\n===Metro-land===\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width = 220\n\n | image1 = New houses, Nathans Road, North Wembley, Middlesex - geograph.org.uk - 60876.jpg\n | alt1 = A row of suburban houses with white gabled ends and black timber beams\n | caption1 =\n\n | image2 = Kenmore Road, Kenton - geograph.org.uk - 99153.jpg\n | alt2 = A row of suburban houses with white gabled ends and black timber beams\n | caption2 =\n\n | footer = Metro-Land was characterised by the construction of [[Tudor Revival architecture|Tudor Revival]] suburban houses (pictured: North Wembley, top, and Kenton, bottom)\n}}\nUnlike other railway companies, which were required to dispose of surplus land, the Met was in a privileged position with clauses in its acts allowing it to retain land that it believed was necessary for future railway use.{{efn|The Land Clauses Consolidation Act 1845 required railways to sell off surplus lands within ten years of the time given for completion of the work in the line's enabling Act.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=134}}}} Initially the surplus land was managed by the Land Committee, made up of Met directors.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=134, 137}} In the 1880s, at the same time as the railway was extending beyond Swiss Cottage and building the workers' estate at Neasden,{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=82\u201383}} roads and sewers were built at Willesden Park Estate, and the land was sold to builders. Similar developments followed at Cecil Park, near [[Pinner]] and, after the failure of the tower at Wembley, plots were sold at Wembley Park.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=140\u2013142}}{{efn|As at Neasden, Cecil Park<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/culturenews/5829326/Suburbia-that-inspired-Sir-John-Betjeman-to-get-heritage-protection.html|title=Suburbia that inspired Sir John Betjeman to get heritage protection|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2009|accessdate=19 May 2012|author=Adams, Stephen}}</ref> and Willesden<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/tps.nsf/Conservation%20area%20pages/LBB-349|title=Willesden Green Conservation Area|work=[[Brent Council]]|date=19 September 2010|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> have both been declared [[Conservation Area (United Kingdom)|conservation areas]].}}\n\nRobert Selbie, then General Manager, thought in 1912 that some professionalism was needed and suggested a company be formed to take over from the Surplus Lands Committee to develop estates near the railway.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=240}} The First World War delayed these plans however, and it was 1919, with the expectation of a housing boom,{{sfn|Green|1987|p=43}} before the MRCE was formed. Concerned that Parliament might reconsider the unique position the Met held, the railway company sought legal advice. The legal opinion was that although the Met had authority to hold land, it had none to develop it, so an independent company was created, although all but one of its directors were also directors of the railway company.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=241\u2013242}} The MRCE went on to develop estates at [[Kingsbury, London|Kingsbury Garden Village]] near [[Neasden]], [[Wembley Park]], Cecil Park and Grange Estate at [[Pinner]] and the Cedars Estate at [[Rickmansworth]] and create places such as [[Harrow Garden Village]].{{sfn|Green|1987|p=43}}{{sfn|Jackson|1986|pp=241\u2013242}}\n\nThe term Metro-land was coined by the Met's marketing department in 1915 when the ''Guide to the Extension Line'' became the ''Metro-land'' guide, priced at 1[[\u00a3sd|d]]. This promoted the land served by the Met for the walker, the visitor and later the house-hunter.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=240}} Published annually until 1932, the last full year of independence for the Met, the guide extolled the benefits of \"The good air of the Chilterns,\" using language such as \"Each lover of Metroland may well have his own favourite wood beech and coppice&nbsp;\u2013 all tremulous green loveliness in Spring and russet and gold in October.\"{{sfn|Rowley|2006|pp=206, 207}} The dream promoted was of a modern home in beautiful countryside with a fast railway service to central London.{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}}\n\nFrom about 1914 the company had promoted itself as The Met, but after 1920 the commercial manager, John Wardle, ensured that timetables and other publicity material used the term Metro instead.<ref>{{harvnb|Jackson|1986|pp=195, 325}}, see also the publicity material reprinted in {{harvnb|Simpson|2003|p=70}}</ref>{{efn|Wardle wished a new sign at Euston Square to read EUSTON SQUARE METRO, but he was overruled by Selbie and METROPOLITAN RAILWAY was spelt in full.{{sfn|Jackson|1986|p=352}}}} Land development also occurred in central London when in 1929 a large, luxurious block of apartments called Chiltern Court opened at Baker Street,{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}}{{efn|Chiltern Court became one of the most prestigious addresses in London. It was home to, among others, the novelists [[Arnold Bennett]] and [[H. G. Wells|H.&nbsp;G.&nbsp;Wells]].{{sfn|Foxell|1996|p=54}} A [[blue plaque]] commemorating Wells was added to the building on 8 May 2002.{{sfn|Horne|2003|p=37}}}} designed by the Met's architect Charles W. Clark, who was also responsible for the design of a number of station reconstructions in outer \"Metro-land\" at this time.{{sfn|Green|1987|p=44}}\n\nA few large houses had been built on parts of [[Wembley Park]], south-west of the Metropolitan station, as early as the 1890s.  In 1906, when [[Edward Watkin|Watkin]]\u2019s Tower closed, the Tower Company had become the Wembley Park Estate Company (later Wembley Ltd.), with the aim of developing [[Wembley]] as a residential suburb.\n\nUnlike other railways, from an early date the Metropolitan Railway had bought land alongside its line and then developed housing on it.  In the 1880s and 1890s it had done so with the Willesden Park Estate near Willesden Green station, and in the early 1900s it developed on land in Pinner, as well as planning the expansion of [[Wembley Park]].\n\nIn 1915 by the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s publicity department had created the term Metro-land.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2015/sep/10/metroland-100-years-england-original-vision-suburbia|title=Metroland, 100 years on: what's become of England\u2019s original vision of suburbia?|last=Forrest|first=Adam|date=2015-09-10|website=the Guardian|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>  It was used as the new name for the company\u2019s annual guide to the places it served (known as Guide to the Extension Line prior to 1915).  The ''Metro-land'' guide, although partly written to attract walkers and day trippers, was clearly primarily intended to encourage the building of suburban homes and create middle-class commuters who would use the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s trains for all their needs.  It was published annually until 1932, but when the Metropolitan became part of London Transport in 1933 the term and guide were abandoned.  By then North-West London was well on the road to its reputation for suburbanisation.\n\nThe 1924 ''Metro-land'' guide describes [[Wembley Park]] as \"rapidly developed of recent years as a residential district\", pointing out that there are several golf courses within a few minutes journey of it.\n\nOver the years during which the guide was published, large numbers of Londoners moved out to the new estates in North-West London.  Some of these estates were developed by MRCE, a company that Robert H. Selbie, the Metropolitan Railway\u2019s General Manager, set up in 1919.  It would eventually build houses along the line, from Neasden reaching far out as Amersham.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://middlesexcountypress.com/?page_id=675|title=Metroland: the golden age of mock Tudor {{!}} MIDDLESEX: A ROUNDTRIP IN NOWHERE LAND|website=middlesexcountypress.com|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>\n\nOne of the earliest of these MRCE developments was a 123-acre one at Chalkhill, within the bounds of what was [[Repton]]\u2019s [[Wembley Park]].  MRCE acquired the land shortly after it was created and began selling plots in 1921.  The railway even put in a siding to bring building materials to the estate.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A History of Wembley|last=Hewlett|first=Geoffrey|publisher=Brent Library Service|year=1979|isbn=|location=|pages=215|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe term \u2018Metroland\u2019 (usually seen now without the hyphen) has become shorthand for the suburban areas that were built in North-West London and in Buckinghamshire, Hertfordshire and Middlesex following the Metropolitan branches. It had become immortalised well before the guide stopped being published.  A song called \"My Little Metro-land Home\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.20thcenturylondon.org.uk/mol-nn24634|title=My Little Metroland Home - song sheet {{!}} Explore 20th Century London|website=www.20thcenturylondon.org.uk|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Amersham Museum|title=My Little Metro-Land Home|date=2013-12-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X2PLwXhHoTU|accessdate=2016-07-20}}</ref> had been published in 1920, and [[Evelyn Waugh]]\u2019s novel ''[[Decline and Fall]]'' (1928) has a character marrying a Viscount Metroland.  She reappears, with the title Lady Metroland, in two more of Waugh\u2019s novels; ''Vile Bodies'' (1930) and ''A Handful of Dust'' (1934).\n\nThe [[British Empire Exhibition]] further encouraged the new phenomenon of suburban development.   Wembley\u2019s sewerage was improved, many roads in the area were straightened and widened and new bus services began operating.  Visitors were steadily introduced to Wembley and some later moved to the area when houses had been built to accommodate them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://brent.gov.uk/media/387392/Wembley.pdf|title=Places in Brent Wembley and Tokyngton|last=Barres-Baker|first=Malcolm|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-07-20}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1921 and 1928 season ticket sales at [[Wembley Park tube station|Wembley Park]] and neighbouring Metropolitan stations rose by over 700%.  Like the rest of West London, most of [[Wembley Park]] and its environs was fully developed, largely with relatively low-density suburban housing, by 1939.\n\n===Absorption of the Met===\nOn 1 July 1933 the Metropolitan Railway amalgamated with other Underground railways, tramway companies and bus operators to form the [[London Passenger Transport Board]] (LPTB), and the railway became the [[Metropolitan line]] of London Transport. The LPTB was not interested in running goods and freight services and the London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) took over all freight traffic. At the same time the LNER became responsible for hauling passenger trains with steam locomotives north of Rickmansworth. The lines north of Aylesbury to Verney Junction and Brill were closed; last train to Brill ran on 30 November 1935 and to Quainton Road and Verney Junction on 2 April 1936. Quainton Road continued to be served by the LNER.{{sfn|Horne|2003|pp=54\u201356}} For a time, the LPTB used the \"Metro-land\" tag: \"Cheap fares to Metro-land and the sea\" were advertised in 1934{{citation needed|date=December 2012}} but the \"Metro-land\" brand was rapidly dropped.{{sfn|Green|2004|loc=introduction}} London Transport introduced new slogans such as \"Away by Metropolitan\" and \"Good spot, the Chilterns\".{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nSteam traction continued to be used on the outer sections of what had become the \"[[Metropolitan line]]\" until 1961. From that date Metropolitan trains ran only as far as [[Amersham tube station|Amersham]], with main line services from [[Marylebone railway station|Marylebone]] covering stations between [[Great Missenden railway station|Great Missenden]] and Aylesbury.\n\n==Defining Metro-land==\n[[File:HarrowPanorama.jpg|thumb|250px|The town of [[Harrow, London|Harrow]], referred to as the \"capital city\" of Metro-land]]\nThe ''Metro-land'' guide insisted that Metro-land was \"a country with elastic borders that each visitor can draw for himself\". Indeed, to the extent that the principal features of Metro-land were not unique to the Metropolitan, it has been invoked more generically: for example, by Kathryn Bradley-Hole writing about [[Gunnersbury Park]],<ref>''Country Life'', 22 July 2004{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> and by the London ''Evening Standard'', which, in 2009, under the heading, \"Down the line into Metroland\", identified [[High Barnet]] (Northern line), [[Loughton]] (Central line) and two Metropolitan suburbs, Amersham and Rickmansworth, as \"top locations with an easy commute\".<ref>Anthea Masey in ''Evening Standard'', 21 October 2009{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Even so, ''Metro-land'' was quite firm that, so far as the Buckinghamshire Chilterns were concerned, its \"Grand Duchy\" was confined to the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|hundred]] of [[Burnham (hundred)|Burnham]]: \"the Chilterns round [[Marlow, Buckinghamshire|Marlow]] and the [[High Wycombe|Wycombes]] are not in Metro-land\".\n\nThe architect [[Hugh Casson]] regarded [[Harrow, London|Harrow]] as the \"capital city\" of Metro-land,<ref name=\"StephenHalliday\">Stephen Halliday (2001) ''Underground to Everywhere''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> while [[Arthur Mee]]'s ''King's England'' described [[Wembley]] as its \"epitome\".<ref>Arthur Mee, ''The King's England: London North of the Thames'' (revised Ann Saunders, 1972){{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>  In 2012 a writer for ''Country Life'', referring to plans to build a new high-speed rail link (\"[[HS2]]\") through the Chilterns, dismissed the style of development around Aylesbury as not \"so much suburban as just sub, there being no ''urbs''. However, the spirits lift when, down the road, you reach Waddesdon. You hardly need to be told you're in Rothschildland\", the latter tag an allusion to [[Waddesdon Manor]], the estate managed by the [[Jacob Rothschild, 4th Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] family and owned by the [[National Trust]].<ref>\"CA\" in ''Country Life'', 18 January 2012{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Slogans and references==\nThe Metropolitan\u2019s terminus at Baker Street was \"the gateway to Metro-land\" and Chiltern Court, which opened over the station in 1929 and was headquarters during the [[Second World War]] of the [[Special Operations Executive]], was \"''at'' the gateway to Metro-land\". In similar vein, [[Chorleywood|Chorley Wood]] and [[Chenies]], later described by [[Metro-land#John Betjeman|John Betjeman]] as \"the essential Metro-land\",<ref>''Metro-land'', BBC TV 1973</ref> were \"at the gateway\" of the Chiltern Hills (of which [[Wendover]] was the \"pearl\").<ref>''Metro-land'', 1924 edition{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Literature and songs===\n[[File:Croxley Tube Station - exterior.JPG|thumb|[[Croxley tube station|Croxley Green]] (now Croxley) station (C. W. Clark, 1925)]]\nBefore the end of the First World War [[George R. Sims]] had incorporated the term in verse: \"I know a land where the wild flowers grow/Near, near at hand if by train you go,/Metroland, Metroland\".\n\nBy the 1920s, the word was so ingrained in the consciousness that, in [[Evelyn Waugh]]\u2019s novel, ''[[Decline and Fall]]'' (1928), the Hon Margot Beste-Chetwynd took Viscount Metroland as her second husband. Lady Metroland's second appearance in ''[[Vile Bodies]]'' in 1930 and ''[[A Handful of Dust]]'' in 1934 further reinforces this.<ref>Waugh, Evelyn, A Handful of Dust (London, 1934), 10.</ref>\n\nMetro-land further entered the public psyche with the song ''My Little Metro-land Home'' (lyrics by Boyle Lawrence and music by Henry Thraile, 1920), while another ditty extolled the virtues of the Poplars estate at [[Ruislip]] with the assertion that \"It's a very short distance by rail on the Met/And at the gate you'll find waiting, sweet Violet\".<ref name=\"StephenHalliday\" />\n\n[[Queensbury, London|Queensbury]] and its local surroundings and characters were cited in the song \"Queensbury Station\" by the Berlin-based punk-jazz band [[The Magoo Brothers]] on their album \"Beyond Believable\", released on the Bouncing Corporation label in 1988. The song was written by [[Paul Bonin]] and Melanie Hickford, who both grew up and lived in the area.<ref>[https://mgonline.gema.de/werke/detail.do?title=QUEENSBURY+STATION&dbkey=540612 GEMA database listing for Queensbury Station song, work no.: 2181020-001]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, ''[[Metroland (film)|Metroland]]'' was the title and setting for a movie starring [[Christian Bale]] about the development of the relationship between a husband and wife living in the area. The movie was based on the novel of the same name written by Julian Barnes.\n\n[[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]] recorded a song ''Metroland'' on the [[English Electric (album)|English Electric]] album. It was released as a single, with the video showing the singer dreamily gazing out from a train at an idealised sub-urban landscape.\n\n===\"Live in Metro-land\"===\nIn 1903 the Metropolitan developed a housing estate at Cecil Park, [[Pinner]], the first of many such enterprises over the next thirty years. Overseen by the Metropolitan's general manager from 1908 to 1930, Robert H Selbie, the railway formed its own Country Estates Company in 1919. The slogan, \"Live in Metro-land\", was even etched on the door handles of Metropolitan carriages.\n\nSome stations, such as [[Hillingdon tube station|Hillingdon]] (1923), were built specifically to serve the company's suburban developments. A number, including Wembley Park, [[Croxley tube station|Croxley Green]] (1925) and Stanmore (1932), were designed by Charles W. Clark (who was responsible also for Chiltern Court) in an [[Arts and Crafts movement|Arts and crafts]] \"villa\" style. These were intended to blend with their surroundings, though, in retrospect, they arguably lacked the panache and vision of [[Charles Holden]]'s striking, modern designs for the [[London Underground|Underground]] group in the late 1920s and early 1930s.\n\n===Imitators===\nNearly 70 years later the Chilterns Conservation Board was advertising \"Chilterns Country \u2013 countryside walks from rail stations\" (2004). Drawing no doubt on \"Metro-land, a guide for ramblers\", published by British Railways Southern Region shortly after the Second World War, it referred to the \"Rambleland\" stations of Surrey and Sussex.<ref>S P B Mais (2nd ed 1949) ''Southern Rambles for Londoners''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Spirit of Metro-land==\nThe sentimental and somewhat archaic prose of the ''Metro-land'' guide (\"the Roman road aslant the eastern border ... the innumerable field-paths which mark the labourer's daily route from hamlet to farm\")<ref name=\"ML32\">''Metro-land'', 1932 edition{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> conjured up a rustic [[Garden of Eden|Eden]] \u2013 a [[Middle England]], perhaps<ref>Dominic Sandbrook (2010) ''State of Emergency \u2013 The Way We Were: Britain 1970-1974''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> \u2013 similar to that invoked by [[Stanley Baldwin]] (Prime Minister three times between 1923 and 1937) who, though of manufacturing stock, famously donned the mantle of countryman (\"the tinkle of the hammer on the anvil in the country smithy, the sound of the scythe against the whetstone\").<ref>Speech at the Hotel Cecil, 6 May 1924</ref> As one historian of the London Underground put it wryly, \"the world of Metroland is not cluttered with people: its suburban streets are empty ... There are, it seems, more farm animals than people.\"<ref>Christian Wolmar (2004) ''The Subterranean Railway''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nA more cynical view, that sought to contrast illusion with changing times, was offered in 1934 by the composer and conductor [[Constant Lambert]] who \"conjure[d] up the hideous faux bonhomie of the [[hiker]], noisily wading his way through the petrol pumps of Metroland, singing obsolete [[sea shanty|sea chanties]] ''[sic]'' with the aid of the Week-End Book, imbibing chemically flavoured synthetic beer under the impression that he is tossing off a tankard of 'jolly good [[ale]] and old' ... and astonishing the local garage proprietor by slapping him on the back and offering him a pint of 'four 'alf'\".<ref name=\"ConstantLambert\">Constant Lambert (1934) ''Music Ho!''.</ref> {{efn|'Jolly Good Ale and Old' was a poem by [[John Still]] (''c.''1543\u20131608), [[Bishop of Bath and Wells]], that was included in ''The Week-End Book'', an anthology edited by [[Francis Meynell|Francis]] & Vera Meynell, whose first edition was published in 1924. 'The Wreck of the \"What's Her Name\"' by Ronald Bagnall & Denham Harrison (1912) contained the lines: \"The men they called for smelling-salts, the women shrieked for beer!/Good old glorious beer my lads, not arf, four alf beer!\".<ref name=\"ConstantLambert\" />}}\n\n===Town ''v.'' country===\nWith similar ambiguity, ''Metro-land'' combined idyllic photographs of rural tranquillity with advertising spreads for new, though leafy, housing developments. Herein lay the contradictions well captured by [[Leslie Thomas]] in his novel, ''The Tropic of Ruislip'' (1974): \"in the country but not of it. The fields seemed touchable and yet remote\". Writer and historian [[A. N. Wilson]] reflected how suburban developments of the early 20th century that had been brought within easy reach of London by the railways, \"merely ended up creating an endless [[ribbon development|ribbon]] ... not perhaps either town or country\".<ref name=\"Wilson\">A.N.Wilson (2005) ''After the Victorians''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> In the process, despite ''Metro-land'''s promotion of rusticity, a number of outlying towns and villages were \"swallowed up and lost their identity\".<ref>Charles Whynne-Hammond (1976) ''Towns''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Influence of ''Country Life''====\nWilson noted that the magazine ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'', which had been founded by [[Edward Hudson (magazine owner)|Edward Hudson]] as ''Country Life Illustrated'' in 1897, had influenced this pattern with its advertisements for country houses: \"If you were a stockbroker or a lawyer's wife ... you could perhaps afford a new [[Tudorbethan]] mansion, with an oak staircase and mullioned windows and half-timbered gables, in Godalming or Esher, or [[Amersham]] or Penn\".<ref name=\"Wilson\" /> Of the surrounding landscape, ''Country Life'' itself has observed that, in its early days, it offered\n{{quote|a rose-tinted view of the English countryside ... idyllic villages, vernacular buildings and already dying rural crafts. All were illustrated with hauntingly beautiful photographs. They portrayed a utopian never-never world of peace and plenty in a pre-industrial Britain.<ref>Francesca Scoones in ''Country Life'', 23 November 2006{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n====Growth of Metro-land====\nBy the 1930s the availability of mortgages with an average rate of interest of 4{{1/4}} per cent meant that private housing was well within the range of most middle class and many working-class pockets.<ref>John Stevenson (1984) ''British Society 1914-45''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> This was a potent factor in the  growth of Metro-land: for example, in the first three decades of the 20th century the population of [[Harrow Weald]] rose from 1,500 to 11,000 and that of Pinner from 3,000 to 23,000.<ref>1901 & 1931 censuses</ref> In 1932 Northwick Park was said to have grown over the previous five years at the rate of 1,000 houses annually and [[Rayners Lane]] to \"repay a visit at short intervals to see it grow\".<ref name=\"ML32\"/>\n\n===Sir John Betjeman===\nIn the mid-20th century the spirit of Metro-land was evoked in three \"late chrysanthemums\"<ref>John Betjeman (1954) ''A Few Late Chrysanthemums''</ref> by Sir [[John Betjeman]] (1906\u20131984), Poet Laureate from 1972 until his death: \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\" (\"When melancholy autumn comes to Wembley / And electric trains are lighted after tea\"), \"Middlesex\" (\"Gaily into Ruislip Gardens / Runs the red electric train\") and \"The Metropolitan Railway\" (\"Early Electric! With what radiant hope / Men formed this many-branched electrolier\"). In his autobiographical ''[[Summoned by Bells]]'' (1960) Betjeman recalled that \"Metroland / Beckoned us out to lanes in beechy Bucks\".\n[[File:JB Plaque.JPG|thumb|300px|Betjeman centenary: commemorative plaque unveiled by [[Candida Lycett Green]], Marylebone station, 2 September 2006]]\nDescribed much later by ''The Times'' as the \"hymnologist of Metroland\",<ref>Bill Stock & Alan Hamilton  ''The Times'', 6 January 2007{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> Betjeman reached a wider audience with his celebrated documentary for BBC Television, ''[[Metro-land (TV)|Metro-land]]'', directed by [[Edward Mirzoeff]], which was first broadcast on 26 February 1973 and was released as a [[DVD]] 33 years later. The critic [[Clive James]], who judged the programme \"an instant classic\", observed that \"it saw how the district had been destroyed by its own success\".<ref>''The Observer'', 15 December 1974{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nTo mark the centenary of Betjeman's birth his daughter [[Candida Lycett Green]] (born 1942) spearheaded a series of celebratory railway events, including an excursion on 2 September 2006 from Marylebone to Quainton Road, now home of the [[Buckinghamshire Railway Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/UK%20News%20Pages%20Sept%2006/030906_Betj.html|title=Betjeman 'Metroland' special from Marylebone to Quainton Road|date=3 September 2006|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> Lycett Green noted of the planning of this trip that among the fine details considered were which filling to have in the baguettes on the train through Metro-land and how long it would stop on the track so that the poem \"Middlesex\" could be read over the tannoy.<ref>''Country Life'', 8 June 2006{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> The event was in the tradition of earlier commemorations of \"Metro-land\", such as a centenary parade of rolling stock at [[Neasden]] in 1963 and celebrations in 2004 to mark the centenary of the Uxbridge branch.\n\n===''Avenger''land===\nMetro-land (notably west Hertfordshire) formed the backdrop for the 1960s ABC TV series ''[[The Avengers (TV series)|The Avengers]]'', whose popular imagery was deployed with a twist of fantasy. The archetypal Metro-land subjects (such as the railway station and the quiet suburb) became the settings for fiendish plots and treachery in this series and others, such as ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'', ''[[The Baron]]'' and ''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)]]'', all of which made regular use of locations within easy reach of film studios at [[Borehamwood]] and [[Pinewood Studios|Pinewood]].<ref>[http://avengerland.theavengers.tv/ Avengerland]</ref>\n\n==Escaping Metro-land==\nSome abhorred Metro-land for its predictability and sameness. A. N. Wilson observed that, although semi-detached dwellings of the kind built in the inner Metro-land suburbs in the 1930s \"aped larger houses, the stockbroker Tudorbethan of Edwardian Surrey and Middlesex\", they were in fact \"pokey\". He reflected that\n{{quote|as [the husband] went off to the nearest station every morning ... the wife, half liberated and half slave, stayed behind wondering how many of the newly invented domestic appliances they could afford to purchase, and how long the man would hold on to his job in the [[Great Depression in the United Kingdom|Slump]]. No wonder, when war came, that so many of these suburban prisoners felt a sense of release.<ref name=\"Wilson\" />}}\n\n===Post-war attitudes===\nBy the end of the Second World War architects in general were turning their backs on suburbia; the very word tended to be used pejoratively, even contemptuously. In 1951 [[Michael Young (politician)|Michael Young]], one of the architects of the Labour Party's electoral victory in 1945, observed that \"one suburb is much like another in an atomised society. Rarely does community flourish\", while the American [[Lewis Mumford]], wrote in the ''New Yorker'' in 1953 that \"monotony and suburbanism\" were the result of the \"unimaginative\" design of Britain's post-war [[New Towns]].<ref>[[David Kynaston]] (2009) ''Family Britain 1951-57''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> When the editor of the ''Architectural Review'', [[James Maude Richards|J. M. Richards]], wrote in ''The Castles on the Ground'' (1946) that \"for all the alleged deficiencies of suburban taste ... it holds for ninety out of a hundred Englishmen an appeal which cannot be explained away as some strange instance of mass aberration\", he was, in his own words, \"scorned by my contemporaries as either an irrelevant eccentricity or a betrayal of the forward looking views of the [[Modernism|Modern]] Movement\".<ref>Quoted in David Kynaston (2007) ''Austerity Britain''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nJohn Betjeman admired [[John Piper (artist)|John Piper]]'s illustrations for ''Castles on the Ground'', describing the \"fake half-timber, the leaded lights and bow windows of the Englishman's castle\" as \"the beauty of the despised, patronised suburb\".<ref>John Betjeman (ed Candida Lycett Green, 1997) ''Coming Home''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref> However, as the historian [[David Kynaston]] observed sixty years later, \"the time was far from ripe for Metroland nostalgia\".<ref>David Kynaston (2007) ''Austerity Britain''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Julian Barnes: ''Metroland''===\n[[Valerie Grove]], who conceded that Metro-land was \"a kinder word than 'suburbia'\" and referred to the less spoilt areas beyond Rickmansworth as \"Outer Metro-land\", maintained that \"suburbia had no visible history. Anyone with any spirit ... had to get out of Metro-land to make their mark\".<ref>''Times Weekend Review'', 4 September 2004{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThus, the central character of ''[[Metroland (book)|Metroland]]'' (1980), a novel by [[Julian Barnes]] (born 1946) that was [[Metroland (1997 film)|filmed in 1997]], ended up in [[Paris]] during the disturbances of May 1968 \u2013 though, by the late 1970s, having thrown off the yearnings of his youth, he was back in Metro-land. ''Metroland'' recounted the essence of suburbia in the early 1960s and the features of daily travel by a schoolboy, Christopher Lloyd, on the Metropolitan line to and from London. During a French lesson, Christopher declared, \"''J\u2019habite Metroland''\" [\"I live in Metroland\"], because it \"sounds better than Eastwick [the fictional location of his home], stranger than Middlesex\".\n\nIn real life, some schoolboys had made similar journeys for more [[hedonistic]] reasons. Betjeman recalled that, between the wars, boys from [[Harrow School]] had used the Metropolitan for illicit excursions to [[night clubs]] in London: \"Whenever the police raided the [[Hypocrites' Club]] or the Coconut Club, the '43 or the Blue Lantern there would always be Harrovians there\".<ref>David Faber (2005) ''Speaking for England''{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Social mobility: ''Tropic of Ruislip''===\nBetween Metro-land\u2019s heyday before the Second World War and the end of the 20th century, the proportion of [[Owner-occupier|owner-occupied]] dwellings in England, already rising fast from the mid-1920s, doubled from a third to two-thirds.<ref>Proportion of dwellings by household tenure, 1938 and 1997: ''Independent Inquiry into Inequalities in Health'' (Chair, Sir Donald Acheson), 1998</ref> In ''[[Tropic of Ruislip]]'', [[Leslie Thomas]]\u2019s humorous account of suburban sexual and social [[mores]] in the mid-1970s (adapted for television as ''Tropic'', ATV 1979), the steady flow of families from council housing on one side of the railway to an executive estate on the other side served to illustrate what was becoming known as \"[[social mobility|upward mobility]]\".{{efn|In 1962 [[Philip Goodhart]], MP for [[Beckenham]], wrote of the parliamentary by-election of that year in the Kent suburb of [[Orpington]], at which a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] majority of over 14,000 was turned into a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] victory, that \"now the extent and growth of this social mobility can be seen for the first time\"<ref>Letter to ''Daily Telegraph'', 23 March 1962, quoted in D. R. Thorpe (2010) ''Supermac: The Life of Harold Macmillan''.{{page needed|date=December 2012}}</ref>}} Another sign was that, by the end of the book, \"half the neighbourhood\" of Plummers Park (probably based on Carpenders Park, on the outskirts of [[Watford]]{{efn|In ''Tropic of Ruislip'', it was possible to hear the rattle of the Metropolitan from Plummers Park. However, although Plummers Park was placed close to Watford \"in the latitude of [[Ruislip]]\", it was said to be thirty miles from Central London, whereas ''Metro-land'' (1932 edition) gave the distance from Ruislip to Baker Street as 13\u00bc miles.}}) had moved south of the [[River Thames]] to [[Wimbledon (London)|Wimbledon]] or nearby [[Southfields]]. This was put down to the \"attractions of [[Victoriana]]\", which, like suburbia itself, championed at the time by Betjeman\u2019s ''Metro-land'', was coming back into fashion; however, it appeared to have just as much to do with couples following each other round in order to maintain extramarital affairs.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nAnother glimpse of Metro-land in the 1970s was provided by ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'', the BBC TV comedy series (1975-8) about suburban self sufficiency. Though set in [[Surbiton]], the programme's location filming was carried out in [[Northwood, London|Northwood]], an area reached by the Metropolitan in 1885. A less benign view of Metro-land was offered in the mid [[noughties]] by the detective series, ''[[Murder in Suburbia]]'' (ITV 2004-6), which, though set in the fictional town of Middleford, was also filmed in Northwood and other parts of North West London.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Note on spelling==\nThe form ''Metroland'' is now in common use, but the \"brand\" was hyphenated as ''Metro-land'' or ''METRO-LAND''. Evelyn Waugh, John Betjeman (in \"Summoned by Bells\") and Julian Barnes all dispensed with the hyphen, though Betjeman's documentary of 1973 correctly used \"Metro-land\", as that was the form always employed by the Metropolitan Railway in its brochures and on the trains themselves.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Streetcar suburb]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Oliver|year=1987|title=The London Underground: An illustrated history|publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]]|isbn=0-7110-1720-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=Metro-Land|edition=British Empire Exhibition 1924 reprinted|year=2004|isbn=1-904915-00-0|editor-first=Oliver|editor-last=Green|publisher=Southbank Publishing|ref=harv|url=http://www.southbankpublishing.com/9781904915003/introduction.php|accessdate=22 April 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20080628202202/http://www.southbankpublishing.com/9781904915003/introduction.php|archive-date=28 June 2008|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foxell|first=Clive|title=Chesham Shuttle: The Story of a Metropolitan Branch Line|edition=2nd|year=1996|publisher=Clive Foxell|isbn=0-9529184-0-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Horne|first=Mike|title=The Metropolitan Line|year=2003|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=1-85414-275-5|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/metropolitanline00mike}}\n* {{cite book|title=London's Metropolitan Railway|last=Jackson|first=Alan|year=1986|publisher=David & Charles|isbn=0-7153-8839-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The English landscape in the twentieth century|last=Rowley|first=Trevor|year=2006|publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Hambledon Continuum]]|isbn=1-85285-388-3|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/englishlandscape0000rowl}}\n* {{cite book|last=Simpson|first=Bill|title=A History of the Metropolitan Railway. Volume 1: The Circle and Extended Lines to Rickmansworth.|publisher=Lamplight Publications|year=2003|isbn=1-899246-07-X|ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Jackson|first=Alan A. |title=London's Metroland|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Capital Transport|isbn=978-1-85414-300-6}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lucey.net/metro-link.htm The Metropolitan and Great Central Railway Joint Committee Survey of 1907]\n* [http://www.metroland.org.uk/ Website for metroland.org.uk]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050413040350/http://www.southbankpublishing.com/metroland/ Metro-land from Southbank Publishing]\n* [http://www.davros.org/rail/culg/metropolitan.html Metropolitan line] from Clive's UndergrounD Line Guides\n* [http://avengerland.theavengers.tv/ Avengerland]\n* [http://westlondonchat.com/photos/showphoto.php?photo=1326&title=ruislip-houses-for-sale-in27metro-land-27-magazine-advert&cat=508/ Metroland magazine advert for houses in Ruislip]\n\n{{Metropolitan line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:History of Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:History of Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Amersham]]\n[[Category:Transport design in London]]\n[[Category:History of the London Underground]]\n[[Category:Social history of London]]\n[[Category:Rickmansworth]]\n[[Category:History of Watford]]\n[[Category:Transport in Watford]]\n", "name_user": "Costesseyboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLiterature and songs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metro-land"}
{"title_page": "Lamborghini Egoista", "text_new": " \n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lamborghini Egoista\n| image = Lamborghini Egoista front.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Automobili Lamborghini S.p.A]]\n| aka = selfish\n| production = 2013\n| class = [[Concept car]]\n| body_style = Hatch-top [[coup\u00e9]]\n| doors = [[Canopy door]]\n| model_years = \n| engine = 5.2&nbsp;L [[V10 engine|V10]]  \n| assembly = \n| related = [[Lamborghini Gallardo]]\n| transmission = \n| successor = terzo millennio\n| length = \n| width = \n| height = \n| wheelbase = \n| layout = [[Mid-engine]], [[all-wheel drive]]\n| platform = \n| designer = [[Walter de Silva]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Lamborghini Egoista''' is a [[concept car]] unveiled by [[Lamborghini]] for the company's 50th anniversary. The fully functioning model is based on the [[Lamborghini Gallardo|Gallardo]]. It features a {{convert|5.2|L|cid|0|abbr=on}} V10 engine producing {{convert|600|hp|kW PS|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}.<ref name=MT>{{cite journal |last=Sanchez |first=Edward A. |title=One Rider, One Bull |journal=[[Motor Trend]]|date=August 2013 |volume=65 |issue=8 |pages=16-17}}</ref> \n\nThe Lamborghini Egoista has a unique one-seat cockpit, which is similar to that of a modern fighter jet, and has a [[canopy door]] that is completely removable. The steering wheel must be removed to enter and exit the vehicle like a [[Formula One car]].<ref name=MT/>  \n\nThe unique exterior of the Lamborghini Egoista is meant to resemble a bull ready to charge if looked at from the side.<ref name=MT/> The lighting resembles that of a modern airplane, with sidemarkers and indicators on the sides and top of the car as well as front and rear. The bodywork consists of active aerodynamic panels that raise and lower for optimum downforce and stability. The body and wheels are made of antiradar material to even more identify with fighter jets.In 2014, the car was sold to an unknown customer for 110 million dollars at the [[unveiling]].\n\nIn Czech, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Romanian and French, Egoista literally means \"selfish\". According to the model's designer [[Walter de Silva]], the Egoista \"represents hedonism taken to the extreme.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automoblog.net/2013/05/12/lamborghini-egoista/|title=Lamborghini Feeds Their Ego with the Egoista Concept|publisher=Automoblog.net |date=2013-05-12 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>.\n[[File:Lamborghini Egoista right.jpg|thumb|Side view]]\nThe car is now on display at the [[Museo Lamborghini]] located in [[Sant'Agata Bolognese]].<ref>[http://www.topgear.com/uk/car-news/lamborghini-egoista-museum-2014-05-16 Lamborghini Egoista: now on display] - Vijay Pattni, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]]'', 16 May 2014</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lamborghini modern timeline}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n[[Category:Lamborghini custom and concept cars|Egoista]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:One-off cars]]\n[[Category:hyper cars]]\n\n{{Modern-auto-stub}}\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, all-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "text_old": " \n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lamborghini Egoista\n| image = Lamborghini Egoista front.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Automobili Lamborghini S.p.A]]\n| aka = selfish\n| production = 2013\n| class = [[Concept car]]\n| body_style = Hatch-top [[coup\u00e9]]\n| doors = [[Canopy door]]\n| model_years = \n| engine = 5.2&nbsp;L [[V10 engine|V10]]  \n| assembly = \n| related = [[Lamborghini Gallardo]]\n| transmission = \n| successor = terzo millennio\n| length = \n| width = \n| height = \n| wheelbase = \n| layout = [[Mid-engine]], [[all-wheel drive]]\n| platform = \n| designer = [[Walter de Silva]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Lamborghini Egoista''' is a [[concept car]] unveiled by [[Lamborghini]] for the company's 50th anniversary. The fully functioning model is based on the [[Lamborghini Gallardo|Gallardo]]. It features a {{convert|5.2|L|cid|0|abbr=on}} V10 engine producing {{convert|600|hp|kW PS|0|lk=on|abbr=on}}.<ref name=MT>{{cite journal |last=Sanchez |first=Edward A. |title=One Rider, One Bull |journal=[[Motor Trend]]|date=August 2013 |volume=65 |issue=8 |pages=16-17}}</ref> \n\nThe Lamborghini Egoista has a unique one-seat cockpit, which is similar to that of a modern fighter jet, and has a [[canopy door]] that is completely removable. The steering wheel must be removed to enter and exit the vehicle like a [[Formula One car]].<ref name=MT/>  \n\nThe unique exterior of the Lamborghini Egoista is meant to resemble a bull ready to charge if looked at from the side.<ref name=MT/> The lighting resembles that of a modern airplane, with sidemarkers and indicators on the sides and top of the car as well as front and rear. The bodywork consists of active aerodynamic panels that raise and lower for optimum downforce and stability. The body and wheels are made of antiradar material to even more identify with fighter jets.In 2014, the car was sold to an unknown customer for 110 million dollars at the [[unveiling]], now the car is at [[Lamborghini meuseu]]\n\nIn Czech, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Polish, Romanian and French, Egoista literally means \"selfish\". According to the model's designer [[Walter de Silva]], the Egoista \"represents hedonism taken to the extreme.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automoblog.net/2013/05/12/lamborghini-egoista/|title=Lamborghini Feeds Their Ego with the Egoista Concept|publisher=Automoblog.net |date=2013-05-12 |accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>.\n[[File:Lamborghini Egoista right.jpg|thumb|Side view]]\nThe car is now on display at the [[Museo Lamborghini]] located in [[Sant'Agata Bolognese]].<ref>[http://www.topgear.com/uk/car-news/lamborghini-egoista-museum-2014-05-16 Lamborghini Egoista: now on display] - Vijay Pattni, ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]]'', 16 May 2014</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lamborghini modern timeline}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n[[Category:Lamborghini custom and concept cars|Egoista]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n[[Category:One-off cars]]\n[[Category:hyper cars]]\n\n{{Modern-auto-stub}}\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, all-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "720sgt3", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed to existing article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamborghini_Egoista"}
{"title_page": "Bukit Merah, Perak", "text_new": "{{For|the planning area located in the Central Region of Singapore|Bukit Merah}}\n\nOne of two towns in the [[Malaysia]]n state of [[Perak]].\n\n== District of [[Kerian]], Northern Perak==\n\n'''Bukit Merah''' (Chinese: \u6b66\u5409\u7f8e\u62c9) is a town and a popular tourist destination. It is famous for the Bukit Merah Laketown Resort. {{coord|5|02|N|100|39|E|region:MY_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline}}\n\n== District of [[Kinta District|Kinta]], Central Perak ==\n[[File:Bukit Merah New Village Main Entrance (Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia).jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bukit Merah New Village, Kinta, Perak]]\n\n'''Bukit Merah''' (Chinese: \u7ea2\u6ce5\u5c71) is a village with population of 11,000, located near [[Ipoh]]. In 1992 and again notably in 2011, it attracted attention for [[1982 Bukit Merah radioactive pollution|radioactive pollution and health problems]] due to [[Rare-earth element#Global rare-earth production|rare-earth mining]] in the decade or more before the mine closed in 1992.<ref>Bradsher, Keith, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/business/energy-environment/09rareside.html?ref=energy-environment \"Mitsubishi Quietly Cleans Up Its Former Refinery\"], ''The New York Times'', March 8, 2011 (March 9, 2011 p. B4 NY ed.). Retrieved 2011-03-16.</ref> {{Coord|4.555378|101.041331|display=inline}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090417041500/http://www.bukitmerahresort-taiping.com/ppc/ Bukit Merah Laketown Resort]\n\n{{Perak}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Perak]]\n[[Category:Towns in Perak]]\n\n\n{{Perak-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the planning area located in the Central Region of Singapore|Bukit Merah}}\n\nOne of two towns in the [[Malaysia]]n state of [[Perak]].\n\n== District of [[Kerian]], Northern Perak==\n\n'''Bukit Merah''' is a town and a popular tourist destination. It is famous for the Bukit Merah Laketown Resort. {{coord|5|02|N|100|39|E|region:MY_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline}}\n\n== District of [[Kinta District|Kinta]], Central Perak ==\n[[File:Bukit Merah New Village Main Entrance (Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia).jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bukit Merah New Village, Kinta, Perak]]\n\n'''Bukit Merah''' is a village with population of 11,000, located near [[Ipoh]]. In 1992 and again notably in 2011, it attracted attention for [[1982 Bukit Merah radioactive pollution|radioactive pollution and health problems]] due to [[Rare-earth element#Global rare-earth production|rare-earth mining]] in the decade or more before the mine closed in 1992.<ref>Bradsher, Keith, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/09/business/energy-environment/09rareside.html?ref=energy-environment \"Mitsubishi Quietly Cleans Up Its Former Refinery\"], ''The New York Times'', March 8, 2011 (March 9, 2011 p. B4 NY ed.). Retrieved 2011-03-16.</ref> {{Coord|4.555378|101.041331|display=inline}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090417041500/http://www.bukitmerahresort-taiping.com/ppc/ Bukit Merah Laketown Resort]\n\n{{Perak}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Perak]]\n[[Category:Towns in Perak]]\n\n\n{{Perak-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "NCTb", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bukit_Merah,_Perak"}
{"title_page": "Lali Esp\u00f3sito", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lali\n| image        = Lali Esp\u00f3sito Premios F\u00e9nix (31915561718) (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Lali in 2018\n| birth_name   = Mariana Esp\u00f3sito<ref>{{cita web|url= https://twitter.com/laliespos/status/60535538763038720|title= Lali Esp\u00f3sito's Tweet, in her official account|accessdate=March 3, 2014|date= April 19, 2011}}</ref> \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|10|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* actress\n* dancer\n* model \n}}\n| years_active = 2003\u2013present\n| family       = \n| module       = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"dance\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/nueva-princesita-dance_0_950905093.html|title=La nueva princesita del dance|date=6 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]}}</ref>\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]<ref name=\"paparazzi\" /><ref name=\"elsol\" />\n* [[dubstep]]<ref name=\"paparazzi\">{{cite journal |last1=Costelo |first1=Soledad |date=26 July 2013 |title='Ya en TeenAngels me decian que tenia que hacer mi m\u00fasica' |journal=Paparazzi Magazine |issue=611 |pages= |publisher=Atl\u00e1ntida |quote=Tiene base de dance, de hip hop y mucho sonidito de dubstep |url=http://www.3musica.com/fotos/13_Revista%20Paparazzi.pdf |accessdate=30 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193921/http://www.3musica.com/fotos/13_Revista%20Paparazzi.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n| label       = [[Sony Music|Sony]]\n| instruments = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* drums\n* guitar\n* harmonica\n}}\n| website     = {{URL|laliesposito.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Mariana \"Lali\" Esp\u00f3sito''' (born 10 October 1991),  who records as '''Lali''', is an Argentine singer, songwriter, actress, dancer and model.\n\nEsp\u00f3sito began her career as an [[Child actor|actress and singer]] in 2003 when she joined the cast of the [[Children's television series|children's]] [[telenovela]] ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz]]'', created by producer [[Cris Morena]]. She had other subsequent [[supporting character|supporting roles]] in telenovelas ''[[Chiquititas]]'' and ''[[Floricienta]]'' and a main role in ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'', the latter of which increased her fame in [[Latin America]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Europe]].\n\nFrom 2007 to 2012, Esp\u00f3sito, along with four other cast members from ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', was part of the [[teen pop]] band [[Teen Angels]], which originated from the series. The group was commercially successful internationally, and toured throughout Argentina and countries such as Israel, Spain, Italy and Latin America. Esp\u00f3sito also sang in the soundtracks of ''Rinc\u00f3n de Luz'' and ''[[Chiquititas]]''. Following her role in the unsuccessful 2011 telenovela ''Cuando me sonre\u00eds'' and her portrayal of [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]] in the Buenos Aires production of ''[[The Crucible]]'', Esp\u00f3sito made her film debut in ''La pelea de mi vida'' in 2012, starring alongside [[Mariano Mart\u00ednez (actor)|Mariano Mart\u00ednez]] and Federico Amador. In January 2013, she began acting in the television comedy ''[[Solamente Vos]],'' as the daughter of [[Adri\u00e1n Suar]]'s character. In 2015, Esp\u00f3sito portrayed her first lead role on TV as \"Esperanza\" on ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda]]''. [[Esperanza m\u00eda (soundtrack)|Its soundtrack album]], in which she appeared on nine of the eleven tracks, received a platinum certification in Argentina for selling over 40,000 copies.\n\nHer debut solo studio album, ''[[A Bailar (Lali Esposito album)|A Bailar]]'', was released on 21 March 2014, featuring [[pop music|pop]] and [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/Lali-Esposito-Presento-primer-solista_0_986901422.html |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito. Present\u00f3 \"Lali\", su primer disco solista. |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |language=Spanish}}</ref>  \"[[A Bailar (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|A Bailar]]\" was released as the [[lead single]] of the homonymous album. The album spawned the singles \"[[Asesina (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Asesina]]\", \"[[Mil A\u00f1os Luz (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Mil A\u00f1os Luz]]\", \"[[Del Otro Lado (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Del Otro Lado]]\" and \"[[Histeria (song)|Histeria]]\". The album peaked at No. 5 in Argentina and at No. 3 in Uruguay. In 2016, she released her second studio album ''[[Soy (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Soy]]'' after the previous release of the songs \"[[Unico (song)|Unico]]\" and \"[[Soy (song)|Soy]]\". Both albums were certified gold in Argentina by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] (CAPIF).\n\n[[List of awards and nominations received by Lali Esp\u00f3sito|Esp\u00f3sito's accolades]] include five [[Premios Gardel|Gardel Awards]], four [[MTV Europe Music Awards]], one [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Award]], thirteen [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina|Argentine Kids' Choice Awards]], six [[MTV Millennial Awards]], one [[Heat Latin Music Awards|Heat Latin Music Award]], one [[Martin Fierro Awards|Martin Fierro Award]], one [[Tato Award]], and nominations for the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], [[Premios Lo Nuestro]], and the [[Seoul International Drama Awards]]. In 2015, ''[[Infobae]]'' named Esp\u00f3sito one of the 10 most influential women in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2015/12/15/1776501-las-10-mujeres-mas-influyentes-la-argentina-el-2015|title=Las 10 mujeres m\u00e1s influyentes de la Argentina en el 2015|publisher=[[Infobae]]|accessdate=18 April 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Artistic career ==\n=== 1998\u20132006: Early work; ''Rinc\u00f3n de Luz'', ''Floricienta'' and ''Chiquititas'' ===\nEsp\u00f3sito made her television debut on the children's program ''Caramelito y vos'' ({{lang-en|Caramelito And You}}) in 1998, when she was 6 years old.<ref name=\"elmundo\">{{cite news |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012 |url=http://elmundo.com.sv/espectaculos/2480-mariana-esposito-ya-no-esta-chiquitita.html |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |title=Mariana Esp\u00f3sito ya no est\u00e1 \"chiquitita\" |date=20 September 2010 |first=Sonia |last=V\u00e1squez |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126214954/http://www.elmundo.com.sv/espectaculos/2480-mariana-esposito-ya-no-esta-chiquitita.html |archivedate=26 November 2010  }}</ref> She made her acting debut in ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz|Rinc\u00f3n de luz]]'' (''Corner of Light''), a children's television series created by [[Cris Morena]], in which she played one of the main supporting characters Malena \"Coco\" Cabrera. A year later, Esp\u00f3sito appeared as Roberta in ''[[Floricienta]]'', another successful series by Cris Morena. In 2006, she portrayed Agustina Ross in a new rendition of Cris Morena's highly successful children's series ''[[Chiquititas]]'' (''Tiny Girls''). She also participated in stage adaptations of these three series.<ref name=\"cm\">{{cite news |url=http://crismorenagroup.com.ar/ingles/ingles-11.html |title=Chiquititas |work=[[Cris Morena Group]] |accessdate=7 September 2012  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430000238/http://crismorenagroup.com.ar/ingles/ingles-11.html |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00f3sito debuted as a singer on soundtrack albums for ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz|Rinc\u00f3n de luz]]'', ''[[Floricienta]]'' and ''[[Chiquititas]]''. These albums were a commercial success in [[Argentina]] and numerous other countries, most notably [[Israel]].<ref name=\"cm\"/>\n\n=== 2007\u20132010: Success with ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'' and ''Teen Angels'' ===\nIn 2007, Esp\u00f3sito landed her first leading role on television, as [[List of Casi \u00c1ngeles characters|Marianella \"Mar\" Rinaldi]] in ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'' (''Almost Angels''), also created by Morena and produced by [[Cris Morena Group]]. It became one of the most popular adolescent television programs in [[Argentina]], [[Latin America]] and [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Gente2\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=16362 |title=Queremos ser felices, enamorarnos y cambiar el mundo |date=13 October 2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Juan Cruz |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021749/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=16362 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series lasted from 2007 to 2010 and held high viewer ratings and earning four [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]] for Best Juvenile Program.<ref name=\"clarin\">{{cite news|url=http://edant.clarin.com/diario/2010/04/09/espectaculos/c-02176672.htm |title=Todos los nominados al Mart\u00edn Fierro |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012 |date=9 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhile acting in ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', Esp\u00f3sito became one of five members of successful [[pop music|pop]] band [[Teen Angels]], signed to [[Sony BMG]], along with [[Gast\u00f3n Dalmau]], [[Juan Pedro Lanzani]], [[Nicol\u00e1s Riera]] and [[Mar\u00eda Eugenia Su\u00e1rez]].<ref name=\"cm\"/> Teen Angels reached success in countries such as Argentina, Israel, [[Chile]], [[Peru]], [[Spain]] and [[Uruguay]].<ref name=\"los40\">{{cite news|work=[[Los 40 Principales]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=9 March 2010 |url=http://www.los40.com/actualidad/noticias/teenangels-visita-espana-y-edita-nuevo-disco/nota/1296250.aspx |title=Teenangels visita Espa\u00f1a y edita nuevo disco}}</ref><ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news|url=http://elcomercio.pe/espectaculos/471230/noticia-teen-angels-conquistaron-jovenes-limenos |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=2 May 2010 |title=Los Teen Angels conquistaron a los j\u00f3venes lime\u00f1os |work=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]}}</ref><ref name=\"latercera\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/entretencion/2010/08/661-281919-9-teenangels-llega-a-chile.shtml |title=TeenAngels llega a Chile |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=[[La Tercera]]}}</ref> Although ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'' ended in 2010, the band members announced they would continue working together, with [[Roc\u00edo Igarz\u00e1bal|Rochi Igarz\u00e1bal]] replacing Mar\u00eda Eugenia Su\u00e1rez.<ref name=\"Gente4\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17249 |title=Nos queremos mucho como para separarnos |date=27 January 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Juan Cruz |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021813/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17249 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Gente3\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17353 |title=Los cambios siempre te hacen madurar |date=1 March 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Joaqu\u00edn |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021818/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17353 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to 2012, Teen Angels released six studio albums, of which five were certified [[Platinum record|platinum]] and one was certified [[Gold record|gold]] by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]].<ref name=\"ndw\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nuevodiarioweb.com.ar/notas/2008/5/4/espectaculo-253659.asp |title=El segundo CD de \u2018Casi Angeles\u2018 alcanz\u00f3 el platino |date=4 May 2008 |work=Nuevo diario web |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"terra\">{{cite news|url=http://www.terra.com.ar/teen/201/201078.html |title=Teen Angels logra un Disco de Platino con su \u00faltima placa |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.terra.com.ar}}</ref><ref name=\"ddo\">{{cite news |url=http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/08/teenangels-recibio-el-disco-de-oro/ |work=[[Teen Angels]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Teen Angels recibi\u00f3 el Disco de Oro |date=25 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101231147/http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/08/teenangels-recibio-el-disco-de-oro/ |archive-date=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They were also spokespersons for numerous brands, such as [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"cocacola\">{{cite news|accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Coca Cola pisa fuerte con \"Hoy quiero\" en la costa |url=http://infokioscos.com.ar/593/coca-cola-pisa-fuerte-con-hoy-quiero-en-la-costa.html |year=2008 |work=infokioscos.com.ar}}</ref> The band won a [[Clar\u00edn Awards|Clar\u00edn Award]], a [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina|Kids' Choice Award Argentina]],<ref name=\"kcaa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.26noticias.com.ar/teen-angels-y-suena-conmigo-los-mas-nominados-a-los-kids-choice-awards-argentina-137623.html |title=Teen Angels y Sue\u00f1a Conmigo, los m\u00e1s nominados a los Kids' Choice Awards Argentina |work=www.26noticias.com.ar |year=2011}}</ref> two [[Los 40 Principales|Los 40 Principales Awards]],<ref name=\"los401\">{{cite news|url=http://casiangeles.com/mexico/novedades/teenangels-ganadores-de-los-premios-40-principales-%E2%80%9Cmejor-artista-nacional-de-argentina%E2%80%9D-gracias-por-votar-a-teenangels/ |title=Teen Angels ganadores de los Premios 40 Principales a la mejor artista nacional de Argentina |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=[[Casi \u00c1ngeles|Casi \u00e1ngeles]] |year=2009}}</ref><ref name=\"los402\">{{cite news |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |url=http://www.primiciasya.com/primicias/TeenAngels-Ganadores-de-Los-Premios-40-Principales-por-segundo-a241o-consecutivo-20101210-86248.html |date=10 December 2010 |title=TeenAngels: Ganadores de Los Premios 40 Principales por segundo a\u00f1o consecutivo |work=Primicias Ya |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106021125/http://www.primiciasya.com/primicias/TeenAngels-Ganadores-de-Los-Premios-40-Principales-por-segundo-a241o-consecutivo-20101210-86248.html |archive-date=6 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and a Quiero Award, and three nominations for [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers|Carlos Gardel Awards]].<ref name=\"gardel1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/espectaculos/todos-los-nominados-a-los-premios-gardel-2009/20090401172238011766.html |title=Todos los nominados a los Premios Gardel 2009 |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Pronto |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102082506/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/espectaculos/todos-los-nominados-a-los-premios-gardel-2009/20090401172238011766.html |archive-date=2 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"gardel2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tododecris.net/2010/09/teen-angels-nominados-los-premios.html |title=Teen Angels nominados a los premios Gardel |work=Todo de Cris |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=21 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"gardel3\">{{cite news |url=http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/10/tennangels-nominado-a-los-premios-gardel-2011/ |work=[[Teen Angels]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Teen Angels nominado a los Premios Gardel 2011 |date=26 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101231221/http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/10/tennangels-nominado-a-los-premios-gardel-2011/ |archive-date=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTeen Angels disbanded in 2012,<ref name=\"sonicomusica2\">{{cite news|accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.sonicomusica.com |url=http://www.sonicomusica.com/pop/teen-angels/noticias/se-separan-los-teen-angels/ |date=20 January 2012 |title=\u00bfSe separan los Teen Angels?}}</ref> and held its last concert on 11 October 2012 in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]].<ref name=\"sonicomusica\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sonicomusica.com/pop/teen-angels/noticias/el-ultimo-show-de-teenangels-en-fotos/ |title=El \u00faltimo show de TeenAngels en fotos |date=11 October 2012 |work=www.sonicomusica.com |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> ''Teen Angels, el adi\u00f3s'', a [[3D film|3D]] [[concert film]] about Teen Angels, was released in 2013 and marked the end of the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yups.tv/noticias/272/TeenAngels+en+3D |title=Se confirm\u00f3 el esperado regreso de Casi \u00c1ngeles |work=YUPS |year=2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718055918/http://www.yups.tv/noticias/272/TeenAngels+en+3D |archive-date=18 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.infobae.com/2013/03/13/700757-los-teen-angels-hablaron-su-pelicula |title=Los Teen Angels hablaron de su pel\u00edcula |date=13 March 2013 |work=Infobae |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132013: ''Cuando me sonreis'', ''The Crucible'', ''Solamente vos'' and \"A Bailar\" ===\nAfter the end of ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', Esp\u00f3sito adopted her nickname ''Lali'', by which she had been known to her friends and family, as her stage name.\n\n[[File:Lali Esp\u00f3sito 2012.jpg|200px|thumb|left||Lali Esp\u00f3sito in 2012]]\nIn 2011, Esp\u00f3sito starred on ''Cuando me sonre\u00eds'' (When you smile at me), a new television series by [[Tom\u00e1s Yankelevich]], opposite [[Facundo Arana]], [[Julieta D\u00edaz]] and [[Benjam\u00edn Rojas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1378923-lali-esposito-la-nueva-heroina|title=Lali Esposito, la nueva hero\u00edna|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2011/12/30/624588-finalizo-la-novela-cuando-me-sonreis-telefe|title=Finaliz\u00f3 la novela Cuando me sonre\u00eds por Telefe - Teleshow|publisher=}}</ref> The following year, Esp\u00f3sito portrayed [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]] in the Buenos Aires production of ''[[The Crucible]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/teatro/clasico-rejuvenecido_0_722327772.html|title=Las brujas de Salem: un cl\u00e1sico rejuvenecido|first=Mar\u00eda Ana|last=Rag|publisher=}}</ref> by [[Arthur Miller]], and made her film debut with ''La pelea de mi vida'' (''The Fight of My Life''), which also starred [[Mariano Mart\u00ednez (actor)|Mariano Mart\u00ednez]] and Federico Amador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/cine/mariano-martinez-esta-cordoba-hablo-con-vos|title=Mariano Mart\u00ednez est\u00e1 en C\u00f3rdoba, y habl\u00f3 con Vos|first=VOS - La Voz del|last=Interior|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.larazon.com.ar/cine/la-pelea-de-mi-vida_4850-p.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101011448/http://www.larazon.com.ar/cine/la-pelea-de-mi-vida_4850-p.html |archivedate=1 November 2014  }}</ref>\n\nSince January 2013, Esp\u00f3sito had starred the [[Pol-ka]] series ''[[Solamente Vos|Solamente vos]]'' (''Only You''), along with [[Adri\u00e1n Suar]] and [[Natalia Oreiro]], as Daniela, one of its leading characters.<ref name=\"televisionar\">{{cite news|url=http://television.com.ar/diario-online/minuto-a-minuto/noticias/190092/arrancan-las-grabaciones-de-solamente-vos/ |work=television.com.ar |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Arrancan las grabaciones de Solamente vos |year=2012}}</ref>\nIn 2013, Esp\u00f3sito announced she would release her first album as a solo artist,<ref name=\"elsol\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito lanza un proyecto musical como solista: \"Va a ser una locura\"|url=http://elsolonline.com/noticias/view/176731/lali-esposito-lanza-un-proyecto-musical-como-solista-va-a-ser-una-locura-|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130730061223/http://elsolonline.com/noticias/view/176731/lali-esposito-lanza-un-proyecto-musical-como-solista-va-a-ser-una-locura-|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 July 2013|date=7 July 2013|work=Diario El Sol}}</ref> titled ''A Bailar''.<ref name=\"dance\" /><ref name=\"videoclip\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish |title=La chica del videoclip|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/chica-videoclip_0_964703590.html|date=29 July 2013|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]}}</ref> When asked about the album's genre, she described it as mainly [[dance music|dance]] with [[hip hop]] influences.<ref name=\"elsol\" /><ref name=\"videoclip\" /><ref name=\"prontoclip\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito grab\u00f3 su primer videoclip, 'A Bailar': 'Estoy con todas las pilas puestas'|url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-grabo-primer-videoclip-bailar-llena-orgullo-tratar-ser-pionera-genero/20130729150036113585.html|date=29 July 2013|work=Pronto.com.ar|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804021546/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-grabo-primer-videoclip-bailar-llena-orgullo-tratar-ser-pionera-genero/20130729150036113585.html|archivedate=4 August 2013}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"A Bailar\", was released for [[Music download|digital download]] on her website on 5 August,<ref name=\"adulta\">{{cite journal|last1=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o|first1=Juan Cruz|date=6 August 2013|title=Hoy me siento m\u00e1s adulta y mandada|journal=Gente|url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=18050|issue=2507|pages=93\u201398|publisher=Atl\u00e1ntida|accessdate=9 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021822/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=18050|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> causing the website to crash because of a spike in traffic.<ref>{{cite news|language=Spanish |accessdate=9 August 2013|url=http://www.diariopopular.com.ar/notas/165349-lali-esposito-colapso-la-web-se-lanzo-como-solista|work=Diario Popular|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito colaps\u00f3 la web: se lanz\u00f3 como solista|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> On 2 September, Esp\u00f3sito presented the music video for \"A Bailar\" at the prominent [[La Trastienda Club]].<ref>{{cite journal|year=2013|title=A bailar con Lali y ONMAG|journal=OMAG|url=http://on-mag.net/site/?p=274|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923071858/http://on-mag.net/site/?p=274|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 September 2013|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-presenta-video-clip-bailar-y-invita-acompanes/20130820114924115326.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito presenta el video clip de \"A bailar\" y te invita a que la acompa\u00f1es|date=27 August 2013|accessdate=27 August 2013|language=Spanish|work=Pronto|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823023003/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-presenta-video-clip-bailar-y-invita-acompanes/20130820114924115326.html|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref> \"A Bailar\" received 100,000 [[YouTube]] views on its release day, and the single entered the top 20 on [[iTunes]] Latin and iTunes Israel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mundotkm.com/hot-news-114284-lali-esposito-rompe-record |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito rompe r\u00e9cord! |work=Mundo TKM |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |date=12 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911154019/http://www.mundotkm.com/hot-news-114284-lali-esposito-rompe-record |archive-date=11 September 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It also was popular in music charts and radio channels in [[Latin America]], [[Italy]] and [[Israel]].\n\n=== 2014\u20132015: ''A Bailar'', ''A los 40'' and ''Esperanza m\u00eda'' ===\nPrevious to the release of her debut album, Esp\u00f3sito released ''A Bailar EP'', which included the tracks \"A Bailar\", \"[[Asesina (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Asesina]]\" and \"[[Del Otro Lado (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Del Otro Lado]]\". The music video for \"Asesina\", the second single, was uploaded to the singer's official YouTube account on 10 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.infobae.com/2014/03/10/1549190-el-sensual-video-lali-esposito/ | title=El sensual video de Lali Esp\u00f3sito | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work= Teleshow |date=10 March 2014 |publisher= [[Infobae]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/poprock/asesina-el-infartante-nuevo-videoclip-de-lali-esposito-que-viene-cordoba | title=\"Asesina\": El infartante nuevo videoclip de Lali Esp\u00f3sito, que viene a C\u00f3rdoba | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work= Vos |date=11 March 2014 |publisher= La Voz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/582423/ocio-espectaculos/lali-esposito-derrite-pantalla-asesina-nuevo-videoclip.html | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito, una \"Asesina\" que derrite la pantalla | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=10 March 2014 |publisher= La Gaceta}}</ref> The ten-track album ''[[A Bailar (Lali Esposito album)|A Bailar]]'' (English: ''Let's Dance'') was released on 21 March 2014.\n\nIn support of the album, Esp\u00f3sito embarked on the [[A Bailar Tour]] of Argentina, with several later stops in Uruguay, Chile, Spain, Italy and Israel.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.diarioveloz.com/notas/122349-lali-esposito-debuto-como-cantante-e-hizo-delirar-sus-fans | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito debut\u00f3 como cantante e hizo delirar a sus fans | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work=Diario Veloz | date=20 April 2014 | publisher=Cia. General de Producciones | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715114827/http://www.diarioveloz.com/notas/122349-lali-esposito-debuto-como-cantante-e-hizo-delirar-sus-fans | archive-date=15 July 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The tour earned  million in the first five shows at [[Teatro Opera|Teatro Opera Allianz]] and was later named the highest-grossing tour of 2015 in Argentina.<ref name=gross>{{cite web |url= http://www.perfil.com/mobile/?nota=/contenidos/2016/01/02/noticia_0079.html |title= El a\u00f1o en que Lali fue la reina |accessdate= 12 January 2016 |author= ''Perfil'' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160202043843/http://www.perfil.com/mobile/?nota=%2Fcontenidos%2F2016%2F01%2F02%2Fnoticia_0079.html |archive-date= 2 February 2016 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=gross2>{{cite web |url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/argentinian-pop-and-tv-star-mariana-lali-esposito-visited-the-friends-of-zion-museum-and-received-a-special-friendship-award-300258585.html |title= Argentinian Pop and T.V. Star Mariana \"Lali\" Esp\u00f3sito Visited the Friends of Zion Museum and Received a Special Friendship Award |accessdate= 6 May 2016|work= [[PR Newswire]]}}</ref> Following the tour's success, more dates were added, and the tour concluded on 25 April 2016 at [[Menora Mivtachim Arena]], [[Tel Aviv]], after a total of 74 dates.\n\nIn May 2014, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the Peruvian film ''A los 40'', directed by Bruno Ascenzo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40|title=Actriz argentina Lali Esp\u00f3sito ser\u00e1 parte de la pel\u00edcula \u2018A los 40\u2019|date=27 September 2013|publisher=|access-date=5 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024110801/http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40|archive-date=24 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpp.com.pe/2013-09-27-lali-esposito-pronto-en-lima-para-promocionar-pelicula-a-los-40-noticia_634676.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito pronto en Lima para promocionar pel\u00edcula A los 40|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014 she starred in the Peruvian film \"A los 40\" (At 40), directed by Bruno Ascenzo.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40 | title=Actriz argentina Lali Esp\u00f3sito ser\u00e1 parte de la pel\u00edcula \u2018A los 40\u2019 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=23 September 2013 | work=La Rep\u00fablica | publisher=Grupo La Rep\u00fablica | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024110801/http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40 | archive-date=24 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://rpp.pe/famosos/celebridades/lali-esposito-pronto-en-lima-para-promocionar-pelicula-a-los-40-noticia-634676 | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito pronto en Lima para promocionar pel\u00edcula A los 40 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=23 September 2013 | work=RPP Noticias |publisher= Grupo RPP}}</ref> In the same year, she became the first ever Argentine artist to win a [[Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Award]] in the [[United States]] for Best Latin Artist.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/mira/ella-es-la-unica-argentina-nominada-los-kids-choice-awards-2014 | title=Ella es la \u00fanica argentina nominada a los Kids\u2019 Choice Awards 2014 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=2 February 2014 | work=Vos |publisher= La Voz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eleconomista.es/evasion/noticias/5851812/06/14/Cinco-divas-latinas-que-estan-por-llegar.html#.Kku8ZX3CQgintIs | title=Cinco divas latinas que est\u00e1n por llegar | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=13 June 2014 | work=El Economista |author=Iwan, M. |publisher= Ecoprensa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prensariomusica.com/8618-3-Musica-trabajo-de-vanguardia-con-Lali-Esposito.note.aspx | title=3 M\u00fasica: trabajo de vanguardia con Lali Esp\u00f3sito | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=28 April 2014 | work=Prensario M\u00fasica & Video |author=Iwan, M. |publisher= Editorial Prensario}}</ref>\n\nIn later 2014, the singer signed an exclusive publishing contract with [[Sony Music|Sony Music Entertainment Argentina]] and released \"[[Mil A\u00f1os Luz (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Mil A\u00f1os Luz]]\" as the third single from ''A Bailar''. To celebrate her incorporation to Sony Music, Esp\u00f3sito released a deluxe edition of ''A Bailar'', which contained unpublished material including a new song, a remix, several video clips and a documentary of the tour. The album peaked at No. 3 in Uruguay and at No. 5 in Argentina, where it was certified gold a few days after its release.\n\nIn 2015, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the [[Pol-ka]] telenovela ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda]]'' (''My lovely hope'') alongside [[Mariano Martinez (actor)|Mariano Martinez]] as Julia \"Esperanza\" Albarrazin, a young woman who settles in a convent by posing as a novice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2014/09/08/1593283-como-sera-la-nueva-tira-que-protagonizaran-mariano-martinez-y-lali-esposito|title=C\u00f3mo ser\u00e1 la nueva tira que protagonizar\u00e1n Mariano Mart\u00ednez y Lali Esp\u00f3sito - Infoshow, Lali Esp\u00f3sito, David Bisbal, El Trece, Solamente vos, Telefe - Teleshow|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://urushow.com/se-avanza-en-la-ficcion-2015-de-lali-esposito/|title=Se avanza en la ficci\u00f3n 2015 de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe A Bailar Tour, continued to 2016 across national cities like [[Buenos Aires]], [[Rosario]], [[Mar del Plata]] and [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and included international stops in [[Uruguay]], [[Italy]], [[Spain]] and [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/divertite/musica/lali-esposito-trae-bailar-tour.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito trae su \"A bailar tour\" a Montevideo|first=|last=elpais.com.uy|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, the singer performed as the opening act for [[Ricky Martin]] show, held in [[Buenos Aires]] and in 2015 for [[Katy Perry]]'s [[The Prismatic World Tour]].\n\n=== 2016\u20132017: ''Soy'', ''Permitidos'' and collaborations ===\nEsp\u00f3sito released her second studio album ''[[Soy (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Soy]]'' on 20 May 2016, with ''[[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]'' newspaper writing that \"she takes one more step with this album, she experiments, shows herself as she is, and that is always valuable\".<ref name=soycr>{{cite news | url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/divertite/musica/sensacion-que-empieza-mostrar.html | title=Una sensaci\u00f3n que empieza a mostrar | accessdate=6 June 2016 | last= Fourment | first= Bel\u00e9n |date=30 May 2016 |newspaper= [[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Intrusos en el espect\u00e1culo|Intrusos]]'', the singer referred to the album's title (''Soy'', English: ''I Am'') saying that \"it is called Soy because I am sharing the truth about what I think and feel. It is super personal\".<ref name=\"interview2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2016/05/19/1812834-lali-esposito-conto-que-se-inspiro-mariano-martinez-algunos-temas-su-disco|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito cont\u00f3 que se inspir\u00f3 en Mariano Mart\u00ednez para algunos temas de su disco|publisher=[[Infobae]]|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016|language=Spanish|author=Ver\u00f3nica Guerman}}</ref> It sold more than 20,000 copies in Argentina in just three hours, being certified gold by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] (CAPIF).<ref name=\"interview3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1900809-las-lagrimas-de-emocion-de-lali-esposito-recibio-un-disco-de-oro-a-horas-de-lanzar-su-nuevo-album|title=Las l\u00e1grimas de emoci\u00f3n de Lali Esp\u00f3sito: recibi\u00f3 un disco de oro a horas de lanzar su nuevo \u00e1lbum|newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in Argentina, Uruguay and Israel, and at No. 5 and No. 6 in Italy and Spain, respectively. Its lead single, \"[[Soy (song)|Soy]]\", was released on 5 May and peaked at No. 5 on the ''[[Monitor Latino]]'' Argentina Top 20 chart and at No. 15 on the Ecuador Pop Songs chart. The second single, \"[[Boomerang (Lali song)|Boomerang]]\", was released on 5 September 2016. As of June 2017, its music video has been viewed more than 17 million times. ''Soy'' was listed as one of the best albums of 2016 by [[Billboard Brasil]] along with [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'', [[Lady Gaga]]'s ''[[Joanne (album)|Joanne]]'', [[J Balvin]]'s ''[[Energia (J Balvin album)|Energ\u00eda]]'' and others.<ref name=bilbra>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com.br/noticias/os-melhores-discos-de-2016-ate-agora/ | title=Os melhores discos de 2016 \u2013 At\u00e9 agora | accessdate=21 October 2016 | work= [[Billboard Brasil]] |date=26 July 2016 |publisher= [[IG Group]]}}</ref> In the same year, Esp\u00f3sito was featured on [[Abraham Mateo]]'s remix of the song \"Mueve\" from the re-issue of his album ''Are You Ready?'', on [[Brian Cross]] song \"Firestarter\" from his second studio album ''Darkness to Life'' and on [[Baby K (artist)|Baby K]]'s Spanish version of the international hit \"[[Roma-Bangkok]]\".\n\nIn August, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the [[romantic comedy]] film ''[[That's Not Cheating|Permitidos]]'' as Camila Boecchi alongside [[:es:Mart\u00edn Piroyansky|Mart\u00edn Piroyansky]]. The film, which was directed by [[:es:Ariel Winograd|Ariel Winograd]], grossed [[United States dollar|$]]1.9 million and has been viewed more than 370,000 times. The [[review aggregator]] website Todas Las Cr\u00edticas assigned the film a weighted average score of 67 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"tlc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.todaslascriticas.com.ar/pelicula/permitidos/criticas|title=Permitidos, cr\u00edticas|website=Todas Las Cr\u00edticas|accessdate=2 August 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe singer embarked on the [[Soy Tour]] of Latin America, Europe and Asia on 8 September. Reviews of the tour performances generally praised Esp\u00f3sito's vocals and the show's staging, which is said that \"fulfills the expectations of a nowadays international pop show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/musica/cinco-detalles-del-explosivo-show-de-lali-esposito|title=Cinco detalles del explosivo show de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|website=vos.lavoz.com.ar|accessdate=7 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00f3sito's 2016 most notable accolades include Favorite Artist and Favorite Song for \"Soy\" at the [[:es:Anexo:Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards Argentina 2016|2016 Argentine Kids' Choice Awards]], [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Latin America South Act|Best Latin America South Act]] at the [[2016 MTV Europe Music Awards]], Argentine Artist of the Year at the 2016 MTV Millennial Awards, and nominations for Best Actress at both the 2016 [[Seoul International Drama Awards]] and the 2016 [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]], where she won Best Theme Song for \"Tengo Esperanza\". The singer became the first ever Argentine artist to enter the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[List of Billboard Social 50 number-one artists|Social 50]] and [[List of number-one artists on the Billboard Artist 100|Artist 100]] charts, peaking at No. 2 and No. 69, respectively.\n\nIn July and November, respectively, Esp\u00f3sito released \"[[Una Na]]\" and \"Tu Novia\" as the first two singles from her upcoming third studio album.<ref name=\"2018BB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/7934094/argentina-lali-esposito-interview|title=Lali Esposito Talks Getting Noticed in 'The Age of Song': Interview|date=18 August 2017|accessdate=18 August 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|first=Santiago|last=Torres}}</ref> The former one rapidly reached the top of the [[Monitor Latino|Argentine National Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Argentina/Nacionalidad/20170911|publisher=[[Monitor Latino]]|accessdate=18 September 2017|title=Top 20 Nacional Argentina \u2013 Del 11 al 17 de Septiembre, 2017|language=Spanish|date=11 September 2017}}</ref> In November, the siner kicked off her second concert tour in support of ''Soy'', titled [[Lali en Vivo]], with two sold-out shows at the [[Estadio Luna Park|Luna Park Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/fama/lali-esposito-agrega-nueva-funcion-luna-park_0_Hkjf-c9UZ.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito agrega nueva funci\u00f3n en el Luna Park|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn.com]]|date=29 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn that period of time Lali was the most popular in the global ranking of different topics in multilingual Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wikirank.net/en/Lali%20Esp%C3%B3sito | access-date=2019-08-13 | website=WikiRank | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito | archive-date=13 August 2019 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20190813103520/https://wikirank.net/en/Lali%20Esp%C3%B3sito | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2018\u20132019: ''Brava'', ''The Accused'' and ''Talento FOX''===\nFrom January to July, the singer continued with her [[Lali en Vivo]] tour, which visited [[Peru]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Israel]] and the [[United States]]. In February, Esp\u00f3sito was featured on [[Mau y Ricky]] and [[Karol G]]'s [[Mi Mala#Remix version|remix of \"Mi Mala\"]], with [[Becky G]] and [[Leslie Grace]], and, in May, she teamed up with [[CD9 (band)|CD9]] and [[Ana Mena]] for the remix of \"Prohibido\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8099267/becky-g-karol-g-leslie-grace-lali-mau-y-ricky-mi-mala-remix|title=Becky G, Karol G, Leslie Grace & Lali Are Squad Goals in Mau y Ricky's 'Mi Mala (Remix)' Video Premiere|author=Billboard Staff|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=12 February 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> Preceded by the release of \"[[100 Grados]]\", in April, and \"Besarte Mucho\", in July, the singer released her third studio album, ''[[Brava (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Brava]]'', in August 2018. One week after, the album received a gold certification by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] for having sold ten thousand copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmtv.com.ar/noticias/noticia_completa.php?bnid=2318&nid=20041&artista=Lali_Esposito&titulo=Ser_Genuina_-_Lali_Esposito |title=Ser Genuina - Lali Esp\u00f3sito |website=CMTV.com.AR |language=Spanish |accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Esp\u00f3sito embarked on the [[Brava Tour]] immediately after the album release, on 23 August, with two sold-out shows at the [[Estadio Luna Park|Luna Park Arena]].<ref name=\"Brava\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtv.com.ar/noticias/noticia_completa.php?bnid=2318&nid=21200&artista=Lali_Esposito&titulo=#BravaTour_-_La_gira_de_Lali|title=#BravaTour - La gira de Lali|website=[[:es:Canal CM|CMTV]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref> The album was succeeded by the release of the singles \"[[Sin Querer Queriendo]]\" with Mau y Ricky, and \"[[Caliente (Lali song)|Caliente]]\", with Brazilian [[drag queen]] [[Pabllo Vittar]]. The singles peaked at number 14 and 51 on the ''[[Billboard Argentina|Billboard]]'' [[Argentina Hot 100]], respectively.\n\nOutside of recording music, Esp\u00f3sito made her debut as a judge on [[Fox Latin America]]'s original television [[talent show]] ''[[Talento FOX]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/fama/lali-esposito-nueva-sorpresiva-faceta-laboral_0_SJHE6BamG.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito tiene una nueva y sorpresiva faceta laboral|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=5 January 2017|accessdate=5 January 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://television.com.ar/lali-esposito-diego-torres-y-wisin-juntos-por-talento-fox/78592|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito, Diego Torres y Wisin juntos por Talento FOX|accessdate=8 May 2018|date=4 May 2018|website=television.com.ar|language=Spanish}}</ref> In September, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the film ''[[The Accused (2018 film)|The Accused]]'', as Dolores Dreier, a girl accused of killing her best friend.<ref name=\"2018BB\" /> The film was directed by Gonzalo Tobal and is made its premiere in the main competition of the [[75th Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/salio-el-primer-poste/20180418141324279705.html|title=Sali\u00f3 el primer p\u00f3ster de la nueva pel\u00edcula de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|website=pronto.com.ar|last=Cuschnir|first=Tatiana|language=Spanish|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLali started off 2019 performing in [[Times Square]], [[New York City]], for [[Univision]]'s [[Feliz! (Univision program)|Countdown Feliz 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/lali-gives-historic-performance-in-times-square-for-new-year-s-eve-cou-135809|title=Lali gives historic performance in Times Square for New Year's Eve countdown|date=3 January 2019|accessdate=4 January 2019|website=[[AXS (company)|axs.com]]|first=Lucas|last=Villa}}</ref> Early that year, the music video for \"[[Lindo Pero Bruto]]\", her collaboration with [[Thal\u00eda]], was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8495715/thalia-lali-lindo-pero-bruto-video|title=Thal\u00eda and Lali Drop Candy-Colored 'Lindo Pero Bruto' Video: Watch|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=30 January 2019|accessdate=30 January 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> The singer received notable nominations for the [[Premio Lo Nuestro]] and the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]].<ref name=\"Nods\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8492678/premio-lo-nuestro-2019-nominations-full-list|title=Premio Lo Nuestro 2019 Nominations: Natti Natasha, J Balvin, Bad Bunny Lead Nods|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8497865/ozuna-leads-2019-billboard-latin-music-awards-finalists-complete-list|title=Ozuna Leads 2019 Billboard Latin Music Awards Finalists: Complete List of Nominees|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=12 February 2019|date=12 February 2019|first=Leila|last=Cobo}}</ref> During the first months of the year, Lali continued touring with ''Brava'', which was certified four times platinum in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/gossip/con-musica-y-actuacion-lali-esposito-busca-romper-prejuicios-3644858.html|title=Con m\u00fasica y actuaci\u00f3n, Lali Esp\u00f3sito busca romper prejuicios|work=[[:es:El Sol de M\u00e9xico|El Sol de M\u00e9xico]]|accessdate=21 May 2019|date=20 May 2019|first=Adolfo|last=L\u00f3pez|language=Spanish}}</ref> For the [[21st Annual Gardel Awards]], Lali won three awards, the most of the night, in the categories for Best Female Pop Album and Best Cover Design for ''Brava'', and Song of the Year for \"Sin Querer Queriendo\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8511545/lali-sebastian-yatra-bad-bunny-latin-notas|title=Lali Wins Big at Premios Gardel|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the last months of 2019, Lali took her Brava Tour to Europe, the United States and the [[Rock in Rio]] music festival in [[Brazil]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8528386/latin-notas-lali-tour-dates-farruko-en-letra-de-otro|title=This Week in Latin Notas: Lali's Tour Dates, HBO Latino Presents 'Farruko: En Letra de Otro' & More|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=27 August 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Suzette|last=Fernandez}}</ref> where she also received a gold certification for \"Caliente.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portalpopline.com.br/na-casa-do-popline-lali-recebe-certificado-de-ouro-por-caliente-parceria-com-pabllo-vittar/|title=Na Casa do POPline, Lali recebe certificado de Ouro por \u201cCaliente\u201d, parceria com Pabllo Vittar|first=Kavad|last=Madeiros|website=POPline|accessdate=13 November 2019|date=29 September 2019|language=Portuguese}}</ref> It was in these months that Lali officially kicked off her fouth music era: in October, she released her fourth studio album's lead single, \"[[Laligera]]\", which peaked at number 24 on the ''Billboard'' Argentina Hot 100;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8532708/favorite-lali-music-video-poll|title=What's Your Favorite Lali Music Video? Vote!|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 November 2019|first=Jessica|last=Roiz}}</ref> in November, she released \"Como As\u00ed\", which features boy band [[CNCO]], with whom she co-hosted the [[2019 Premios Juventud]] ceremony back in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8543096/viva-friday-lali-cnco-j-alvarez|title=Viva Friday Playlist: Lali Joins Forces With CNCO, J Alvarez Releases 'La Fama Que Camina Vol. 2' & More|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8512499/premios-juventud-2019-nominees-list|title=Maluma, Bad Bunny and Anuel AA Lead Premios Juventud Nominations: Full List|first=Suzette|last=Fernandez|date=21 May 2019|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n== Other work ==\n=== Modeling ===\nEsp\u00f3sito has been a spokesperson for numerous brands, either independently or with her [[Teen Angels]] bandmates.<ref name=\"cocacola\"/> Her first commercial was for the children's fashion label MCbody Jeans. In 2007, she signed an exclusive contract with the Argentine [[lingerie]] brand Promesse,<ref name=\"univision\">{{cite news |url=http://foro.univision.com/t5/Erreway/Mariana-Esposito-tambien-cara-de-Promesse/td-p/152514631 |work=foro.univision.com |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Mariana Esposito tambien cara de Promesse |date=23 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130205034818/http://foro.univision.com/t5/Erreway/Mariana-Esposito-tambien-cara-de-Promesse/td-p/152514631 |archivedate=5 February 2013  }}</ref> and she has done most of her photo sessions with [[Luisana Lopilato]].<ref name=\"solocristv2\">{{cite news |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2009/08/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |title=Fotos de Mariana Esp\u00f3sito en Promesse Primavera/Verrano 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012154116/http://www.solocristv.net/2009/08/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |archivedate=12 October 2016  }}</ref><ref name=\"solocristv1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2009/03/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |title=Fotos de Mariana Esp\u00f3sito en Promesse Oto\u00f1o/Invierno 2009 |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012191306/http://www.solocristv.net/2009/03/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |archivedate=12 October 2016  }}</ref> In 2009, Esp\u00f3sito and [[Juan Pedro Lanzani|Peter Lanzani]] did a special promotion for KEFF body spray for the Israeli market.<ref name=\"lali\">{{cite news |url=http://www.marianae.com.ar/marianaesposito/index.php |title=Mariana Esp\u00f3sito \u2013 La p\u00e1gina |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.marianae.com.ar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026174951/http://www.marianae.com.ar/marianaesposito/index.php |archivedate=26 October 2009  }}</ref> Since 2011, she has been the spokesperson for the lingerie brand Lara Teens. In 2014 she starred in a commercial for hair conditioner Biokur in Uruguay and a commercial for feminine wipes company Carefree in Argentina.\n[[File:Lali Esp\u00f3sito (logo).png|thumb|right|150px|Esp\u00f3sito's logo as a solo artist.]]\nEsp\u00f3sito has been the cover model for magazines such as ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''Galore'', ''Caras'', ''OnMag'', ''Las Rosas'', ''Twees'', ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''Luz'', ''Viva'', ''Watt'', ''Nueva'', ''Upss'' and ''Fack'', among others.\n\n=== Entrepreneurship ===\nOn 21 September 2013, Esp\u00f3sito launched her own line of eponymous [[perfume]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/podes-oler_0_969503180.html |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Tambi\u00e9n me pod\u00e9s oler |date=6 August 2013 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-lanzara-su-perfume/20130711090929112057.html |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito lanzar\u00e1 su perfume |date=18 September 2013 |work=Pronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715013542/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-lanzara-su-perfume/20130711090929112057.html |archivedate=15 July 2013  }}</ref> In 2018, she launched an item of clothing for [[47 Street]].\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\nIn May 2010, Esp\u00f3sito and her [[Teen Angels]] bandmates participated in an action organized by the Biodiversity Foundation on the occasion of the [[World Biodiversity Day]] and raised awareness of the importance of preserving biodiversity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fundacion-biodiversidad.es/inicio/noticias/noticias/113354-concierto-bravo-por-la-tierra |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Concierto \"Bravo por la Tierra\" |date=19 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102222754/http://www.fundacion-biodiversidad.es/inicio/noticias/noticias/113354-concierto-bravo-por-la-tierra |archivedate=2 November 2013  }}</ref> In 2013, Esp\u00f3sito supported Best Buddies International, a [[non-governmental organization]] that promotes social inclusion and employment of people with intellectual disabilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://infolaliesposito.blogspot.com.ar/2013/08/pineiro-prod-y-lali-esposito-juntos.html |title=Pi\u00f1eiro Prod y Lali Esp\u00f3sito juntos acompa\u00f1ando a Best Buddies |date=16 August 2013 |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |work=infolaliesposito.blogspot.com.ar}}</ref> In 2014 she participated in the concert at [[Teatro Opera]] by the Guest Foundation that marked the 25th anniversary of the fight against [[HIV]]. In 2015 she starred in the solidarity campaign \"Flood, what are we doing?\" for the foundation to help flood victims in the city of C\u00f3rdoba.\n\nEsp\u00f3sito has been named \"Godmother\" of Dono x Vos foundation, a nongovernmental organization dedicated to raising awareness about [[organ donation]]. In 2017, the singer joined forces with Red Solidaria and [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate Football Club]] to launch a solidarity campaign named \"Amor Es Presente\". The campaign received donated toys that were later gifted to more than twelve-thousand children as part of [[Christmas]] festivities.\n\n===Activism===\nEsp\u00f3sito has proclaimed herself in favor of the [[voluntary termination of pregnancy]] in Argentina, where [[Abortion in Argentina|abortion]] is still illegal. The bill proposed that an abortion may be performed during the first 14 weeks of pregnancy, with no requirements other than the woman's desire. Esp\u00f3sito is part of a [[Feminism in Argentina|Feminist]] group of Argentine actresses and singers, such as [[Jimena Bar\u00f3n]], [[Griselda Siciliani]], [[Carla Peterson (actress)|Carla Peterson]], [[Florencia Pe\u00f1a]] and [[Florencia de la V]], among others. Although the bill was approved by the [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|Chamber of Deputies]], it was rejected by the [[Argentine Senate|Senate]]. Esp\u00f3sito has expressed her position in major events such as the 48th annual [[Martin Fierro Awards]], in which she lifted up a green scarf, sign of the pro-legal abortion movement in Argentina, at the end of her performance. Moreover, in her [[Brava Tour]], she dedicates her song \"Tu Revoluci\u00f3n\" to the movement, while the stage lights turn green and green hearts are displayed in the screens.\n\n== Personal life ==\nLali is the daughter of Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Riera, who road-manages her tour, and Carlos Esp\u00f3sito, a [[Association football|football]] coach. She has two siblings, Patricio Esp\u00f3sito and Ana Laura Esp\u00f3sito. She was born and grew up in Parque Patricios. After high school, they moved to Banfield.<ref name=\"lali\"/><ref name=\"solocristv3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2008/08/biografia-y-entrevista-mariana-esposito.html |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |title=Biograf\u00eda y entrevista a Mariana Esp\u00f3sito |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910203657/http://www.solocristv.net/2008/08/biografia-y-entrevista-mariana-esposito.html |archive-date=10 September 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> She currently resides in [[Palermo, Buenos Aires]].<ref name=\"solocristv3\"/>\nShe has Italian ancestors from her father's lineage.\n\nFrom 2006 to 2010, Esp\u00f3sito dated her ''[[Chiquititas]]'' and ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'' co-star [[Peter Lanzani]].<ref>http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/informacion/peter-lanzani-y-lali-espsito-nos-amamos-como-cualquier-hijo-de-vecino/20081209171838077164.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, the 23-year-old Esp\u00f3sito was ranked third sexiest Argentine woman in a survey reported by [[Radio Continental]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.continental.com.ar/noticias/espectaculos/jesica-cirio-encabeza-una-lista-de-las-mujeres-mas-sexys-de-argentina/20140318/nota/2134949.aspx |title=J\u00e9sica Cirio encabeza una lista de las mujeres m\u00e1s sexys de Argentina (J\u00e9sica Cirio tops a list of the sexiest women in Argentina) |publisher=[[Radio Continental]] |date=2014-03-18 |access-date=2020-03-25 |language=Spanish}}</ref> That same year, she was ranked the 27th-most influential Spanish-speaking celebrity on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yosoyred.com/2014/03/las-100-cuentas-de-twitter-mas-influyentes-en-espanol-usando-analisis-de-redes/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317232153/http://yosoyred.com/2014/03/las-100-cuentas-de-twitter-mas-influyentes-en-espanol-usando-analisis-de-redes/|title=las 100 cuentas de twitter mas influyentes en espa\u00f1ol usando an\u00e1lisis de redes.|archivedate=17 March 2014 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{Main|Lali Esp\u00f3sito videography}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz]]''\n| Malena \"Coco\" Cabrera\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2004-2005\n| ''[[Floricienta]]''\n| Roberta Espinosa\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Chiquititas#Chiquititas Sin Fin|Chiquititas Sin Fin]]''\n| Agustina Ross\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2007-2010\n| ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]''\n| Marianella Rinaldi\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Cuando Me Sonre\u00eds''\n| Milagros Rivas\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Dulce amor (telenovela)|Dulce Amor]]''\n| Ana\n| Episode 36\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Solamente Vos]]''\n| Daniela Cousteau\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2015-2016\n| ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda|Esperanza M\u00eda]]''\n| Julia Albarrac\u00edn / Esperanza\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Showmatch]]''\n| Makeup seller\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Diary (TV series)|MTV Diary]]''\n| Herself\n| Special\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[:es:Sandro de Am\u00e9rica (serie de televisi\u00f3n)|Sandro de Am\u00e9rica]]''\n| [[:es:Tita Russ|Reyna Ross]]\n| Episodes: \"El \u00daltimo Hombre en La Tierra\" and \"Todo Va a Estallar\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Talento FOX]]''\n| Judge\n| [[Talent show]]\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Sky Rojo]]''\n|\n| Lead role (Netflix)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''La pelea de mi vida''\n| Bel\u00e9n Est\u00e9vez\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Teen Angels, El Adi\u00f3s''\n| Herself\n| Concert film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''A Los 40'' \n| Melissa\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Me cas\u00e9 con un boludo'' \n| Herself \n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Permitidos|That's Not Cheating]]'' \n| Camila Boecchi\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Accused (2018 film)|The Accused]]'' \n| Dolores Dreier\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Trolls World Tour]]'' \n| Barb\n| Voice role (Latin American dub)\n|}\n\n== Stage ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Location\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz|Rinc\u00f3n de luz]]''\n| Malena \"Coco\" Cabrera\n| rowspan=4 |<center>Gran Rex</center>\n|-\n| 2004-05\n|''[[Floricienta]]''\n| Roberta Espinoza\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Chiquititas]]''\n| Augustina Ross\n|-\n| 2007-10\n| ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles|Casi \u00e1ngeles]]''\n| [[List of Casi \u00c1ngeles characters|Marianella Rinaldi]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Crucible]]''\n| [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]]\n|<center> Teatro Broadway</center>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Casi Normales''\n| Herself\n|Teatro Tabar\u00eds\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda|Esperanza m\u00eda: El musical]]''\n| Julia Albarrac\u00edn / Esperanza\n|<center> [[Teatro Opera|Opera Allianz]]</center>\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Lali Esp\u00f3sito discography|List of songs recorded by Lali Esp\u00f3sito|l2=list of songs}}\n\n*''[[A Bailar (Lali Esposito album)|A Bailar]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Soy (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Soy]]'' (2016)\n*''[[Brava (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Brava]]'' (2018)<ref name=\"Brava\" />\n\n== Concert tours ==\n'''Headlining'''\n* [[A Bailar Tour]] (2014\u201316)\n* [[Soy Tour]] (2016\u20132017)\n* [[Lali en Vivo]] (2017\u20132018)\n* [[Brava Tour]] (2018\u20132019)\n\n'''Opening act'''\n* [[The Prismatic World Tour]] {{small|(for [[Katy Perry]])}} (2015)\n* [[The 7/27 Tour]] {{small|(for [[Fifth Harmony]])}} (2016)\n* [[One World Tour (Ricky Martin)|One World Tour]] {{small|(for [[Ricky Martin]])}} (2016)\n* [[Witness: The Tour]] {{small|(for [[Katy Perry]])}} (2018)\n* [[Never Be the Same Tour]] {{small|(for [[Camila Cabello]])}} (2018)\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Lali Esp\u00f3sito}}\nAs of February 2019, Esp\u00f3sito has won 39 awards from 71 nominations, including five [[Premios Gardel|Gardel Awards]], four [[MTV Europe Music Awards]], one [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Award]], one [[Heat Latin Music Awards|Heat Latin Music Award]], thirteen [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina|Argentine Kids' Choice Awards]], six [[MTV Millennial Awards]], one [[Heat Latin Music Awards|Heat Latin Music Award]], one [[Martin Fierro Awards|Martin Fierro Award]], and one [[Tato Award]]. Moreover, Lali has received nominations for the [[Premio Lo Nuestro]], the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], and the [[Seoul International Drama Awards]], among others.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.3musica.com/lali/}}\n* {{IMDb name|1373106|Mariana Esp\u00f3sito}}\n*{{Instagram|id=lalioficial}}\n\n{{Lali Esp\u00f3sito|state=collapsed}}\n{{Teen Angels|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esposito, Lali}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century Argentine actresses]]\n[[Category:Argentine child actresses]]\n[[Category:Argentine child singers]]\n[[Category:Argentine female models]]\n[[Category:Argentine pop singers]]\n[[Category:Argentine stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Argentine telenovela actresses]]\n[[Category:Argentine television actresses]]\n[[Category:Argentine contraltos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Singers from Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:21st-century Argentine singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American female models]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lali\n| image        = Lali Esp\u00f3sito Premios F\u00e9nix (31915561718) (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Lali in 2018\n| birth_name   = Mariana Esp\u00f3sito\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|10|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* songwriter\n* actress\n* dancer\n* model \n}}\n| years_active = 2003\u2013present\n| family       = \n| module       = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Latin pop]]\n* [[Dance music|dance]]<ref name=\"dance\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/nueva-princesita-dance_0_950905093.html|title=La nueva princesita del dance|date=6 July 2013|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]}}</ref>\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]<ref name=\"paparazzi\" /><ref name=\"elsol\" />\n* [[dubstep]]<ref name=\"paparazzi\">{{cite journal |last1=Costelo |first1=Soledad |date=26 July 2013 |title='Ya en TeenAngels me decian que tenia que hacer mi m\u00fasica' |journal=Paparazzi Magazine |issue=611 |pages= |publisher=Atl\u00e1ntida |quote=Tiene base de dance, de hip hop y mucho sonidito de dubstep |url=http://www.3musica.com/fotos/13_Revista%20Paparazzi.pdf |accessdate=30 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304193921/http://www.3musica.com/fotos/13_Revista%20Paparazzi.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\n| label       = [[Sony Music|Sony]]\n| instruments = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* drums\n* guitar\n* harmonica\n}}\n| website     = {{URL|laliesposito.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Mariana \"Lali\" Esp\u00f3sito''' (born 10 October 1991),  who records as '''Lali''', is an Argentine singer, songwriter, actress, dancer and model.\n\nEsp\u00f3sito began her career as an [[Child actor|actress and singer]] in 2003 when she joined the cast of the [[Children's television series|children's]] [[telenovela]] ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz]]'', created by producer [[Cris Morena]]. She had other subsequent [[supporting character|supporting roles]] in telenovelas ''[[Chiquititas]]'' and ''[[Floricienta]]'' and a main role in ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'', the latter of which increased her fame in [[Latin America]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Europe]].\n\nFrom 2007 to 2012, Esp\u00f3sito, along with four other cast members from ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', was part of the [[teen pop]] band [[Teen Angels]], which originated from the series. The group was commercially successful internationally, and toured throughout Argentina and countries such as Israel, Spain, Italy and Latin America. Esp\u00f3sito also sang in the soundtracks of ''Rinc\u00f3n de Luz'' and ''[[Chiquititas]]''. Following her role in the unsuccessful 2011 telenovela ''Cuando me sonre\u00eds'' and her portrayal of [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]] in the Buenos Aires production of ''[[The Crucible]]'', Esp\u00f3sito made her film debut in ''La pelea de mi vida'' in 2012, starring alongside [[Mariano Mart\u00ednez (actor)|Mariano Mart\u00ednez]] and Federico Amador. In January 2013, she began acting in the television comedy ''[[Solamente Vos]],'' as the daughter of [[Adri\u00e1n Suar]]'s character. In 2015, Esp\u00f3sito portrayed her first lead role on TV as \"Esperanza\" on ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda]]''. [[Esperanza m\u00eda (soundtrack)|Its soundtrack album]], in which she appeared on nine of the eleven tracks, received a platinum certification in Argentina for selling over 40,000 copies.\n\nHer debut solo studio album, ''[[A Bailar (Lali Esposito album)|A Bailar]]'', was released on 21 March 2014, featuring [[pop music|pop]] and [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/Lali-Esposito-Presento-primer-solista_0_986901422.html |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito. Present\u00f3 \"Lali\", su primer disco solista. |date=4 September 2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |language=Spanish}}</ref>  \"[[A Bailar (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|A Bailar]]\" was released as the [[lead single]] of the homonymous album. The album spawned the singles \"[[Asesina (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Asesina]]\", \"[[Mil A\u00f1os Luz (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Mil A\u00f1os Luz]]\", \"[[Del Otro Lado (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Del Otro Lado]]\" and \"[[Histeria (song)|Histeria]]\". The album peaked at No. 5 in Argentina and at No. 3 in Uruguay. In 2016, she released her second studio album ''[[Soy (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Soy]]'' after the previous release of the songs \"[[Unico (song)|Unico]]\" and \"[[Soy (song)|Soy]]\". Both albums were certified gold in Argentina by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] (CAPIF).\n\n[[List of awards and nominations received by Lali Esp\u00f3sito|Esp\u00f3sito's accolades]] include five [[Premios Gardel|Gardel Awards]], four [[MTV Europe Music Awards]], one [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Award]], thirteen [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina|Argentine Kids' Choice Awards]], six [[MTV Millennial Awards]], one [[Heat Latin Music Awards|Heat Latin Music Award]], one [[Martin Fierro Awards|Martin Fierro Award]], one [[Tato Award]], and nominations for the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]], [[Premios Lo Nuestro]], and the [[Seoul International Drama Awards]]. In 2015, ''[[Infobae]]'' named Esp\u00f3sito one of the 10 most influential women in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2015/12/15/1776501-las-10-mujeres-mas-influyentes-la-argentina-el-2015|title=Las 10 mujeres m\u00e1s influyentes de la Argentina en el 2015|publisher=[[Infobae]]|accessdate=18 April 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Artistic career ==\n=== 1998\u20132006: Early work; ''Rinc\u00f3n de Luz'', ''Floricienta'' and ''Chiquititas'' ===\nEsp\u00f3sito made her television debut on the children's program ''Caramelito y vos'' ({{lang-en|Caramelito And You}}) in 1998, when she was 6 years old.<ref name=\"elmundo\">{{cite news |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012 |url=http://elmundo.com.sv/espectaculos/2480-mariana-esposito-ya-no-esta-chiquitita.html |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |title=Mariana Esp\u00f3sito ya no est\u00e1 \"chiquitita\" |date=20 September 2010 |first=Sonia |last=V\u00e1squez |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126214954/http://www.elmundo.com.sv/espectaculos/2480-mariana-esposito-ya-no-esta-chiquitita.html |archivedate=26 November 2010  }}</ref> She made her acting debut in ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz|Rinc\u00f3n de luz]]'' (''Corner of Light''), a children's television series created by [[Cris Morena]], in which she played one of the main supporting characters Malena \"Coco\" Cabrera. A year later, Esp\u00f3sito appeared as Roberta in ''[[Floricienta]]'', another successful series by Cris Morena. In 2006, she portrayed Agustina Ross in a new rendition of Cris Morena's highly successful children's series ''[[Chiquititas]]'' (''Tiny Girls''). She also participated in stage adaptations of these three series.<ref name=\"cm\">{{cite news |url=http://crismorenagroup.com.ar/ingles/ingles-11.html |title=Chiquititas |work=[[Cris Morena Group]] |accessdate=7 September 2012  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430000238/http://crismorenagroup.com.ar/ingles/ingles-11.html |archive-date=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00f3sito debuted as a singer on soundtrack albums for ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz|Rinc\u00f3n de luz]]'', ''[[Floricienta]]'' and ''[[Chiquititas]]''. These albums were a commercial success in [[Argentina]] and numerous other countries, most notably [[Israel]].<ref name=\"cm\"/>\n\n=== 2007\u20132010: Success with ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'' and ''Teen Angels'' ===\nIn 2007, Esp\u00f3sito landed her first leading role on television, as [[List of Casi \u00c1ngeles characters|Marianella \"Mar\" Rinaldi]] in ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'' (''Almost Angels''), also created by Morena and produced by [[Cris Morena Group]]. It became one of the most popular adolescent television programs in [[Argentina]], [[Latin America]] and [[Israel]].<ref name=\"Gente2\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=16362 |title=Queremos ser felices, enamorarnos y cambiar el mundo |date=13 October 2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Juan Cruz |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021749/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=16362 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The series lasted from 2007 to 2010 and held high viewer ratings and earning four [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]] for Best Juvenile Program.<ref name=\"clarin\">{{cite news|url=http://edant.clarin.com/diario/2010/04/09/espectaculos/c-02176672.htm |title=Todos los nominados al Mart\u00edn Fierro |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012 |date=9 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhile acting in ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', Esp\u00f3sito became one of five members of successful [[pop music|pop]] band [[Teen Angels]], signed to [[Sony BMG]], along with [[Gast\u00f3n Dalmau]], [[Juan Pedro Lanzani]], [[Nicol\u00e1s Riera]] and [[Mar\u00eda Eugenia Su\u00e1rez]].<ref name=\"cm\"/> Teen Angels reached success in countries such as Argentina, Israel, [[Chile]], [[Peru]], [[Spain]] and [[Uruguay]].<ref name=\"los40\">{{cite news|work=[[Los 40 Principales]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=9 March 2010 |url=http://www.los40.com/actualidad/noticias/teenangels-visita-espana-y-edita-nuevo-disco/nota/1296250.aspx |title=Teenangels visita Espa\u00f1a y edita nuevo disco}}</ref><ref name=\"elcomercio\">{{cite news|url=http://elcomercio.pe/espectaculos/471230/noticia-teen-angels-conquistaron-jovenes-limenos |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=2 May 2010 |title=Los Teen Angels conquistaron a los j\u00f3venes lime\u00f1os |work=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]}}</ref><ref name=\"latercera\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/entretencion/2010/08/661-281919-9-teenangels-llega-a-chile.shtml |title=TeenAngels llega a Chile |date=5 August 2010 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=[[La Tercera]]}}</ref> Although ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'' ended in 2010, the band members announced they would continue working together, with [[Roc\u00edo Igarz\u00e1bal|Rochi Igarz\u00e1bal]] replacing Mar\u00eda Eugenia Su\u00e1rez.<ref name=\"Gente4\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17249 |title=Nos queremos mucho como para separarnos |date=27 January 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Juan Cruz |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021813/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17249 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Gente3\">{{cite news |work=[[People (magazine)|Gente]] |url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17353 |title=Los cambios siempre te hacen madurar |date=1 March 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |first=Joaqu\u00edn |last=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021818/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=17353 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2007 to 2012, Teen Angels released six studio albums, of which five were certified [[Platinum record|platinum]] and one was certified [[Gold record|gold]] by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]].<ref name=\"ndw\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nuevodiarioweb.com.ar/notas/2008/5/4/espectaculo-253659.asp |title=El segundo CD de \u2018Casi Angeles\u2018 alcanz\u00f3 el platino |date=4 May 2008 |work=Nuevo diario web |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=\"terra\">{{cite news|url=http://www.terra.com.ar/teen/201/201078.html |title=Teen Angels logra un Disco de Platino con su \u00faltima placa |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.terra.com.ar}}</ref><ref name=\"ddo\">{{cite news |url=http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/08/teenangels-recibio-el-disco-de-oro/ |work=[[Teen Angels]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Teen Angels recibi\u00f3 el Disco de Oro |date=25 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101231147/http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/08/teenangels-recibio-el-disco-de-oro/ |archive-date=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They were also spokespersons for numerous brands, such as [[Coca-Cola]].<ref name=\"cocacola\">{{cite news|accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Coca Cola pisa fuerte con \"Hoy quiero\" en la costa |url=http://infokioscos.com.ar/593/coca-cola-pisa-fuerte-con-hoy-quiero-en-la-costa.html |year=2008 |work=infokioscos.com.ar}}</ref> The band won a [[Clar\u00edn Awards|Clar\u00edn Award]], a [[Kids' Choice Awards Argentina|Kids' Choice Award Argentina]],<ref name=\"kcaa\">{{cite news|url=http://www.26noticias.com.ar/teen-angels-y-suena-conmigo-los-mas-nominados-a-los-kids-choice-awards-argentina-137623.html |title=Teen Angels y Sue\u00f1a Conmigo, los m\u00e1s nominados a los Kids' Choice Awards Argentina |work=www.26noticias.com.ar |year=2011}}</ref> two [[Los 40 Principales|Los 40 Principales Awards]],<ref name=\"los401\">{{cite news|url=http://casiangeles.com/mexico/novedades/teenangels-ganadores-de-los-premios-40-principales-%E2%80%9Cmejor-artista-nacional-de-argentina%E2%80%9D-gracias-por-votar-a-teenangels/ |title=Teen Angels ganadores de los Premios 40 Principales a la mejor artista nacional de Argentina |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=[[Casi \u00c1ngeles|Casi \u00e1ngeles]] |year=2009}}</ref><ref name=\"los402\">{{cite news |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |url=http://www.primiciasya.com/primicias/TeenAngels-Ganadores-de-Los-Premios-40-Principales-por-segundo-a241o-consecutivo-20101210-86248.html |date=10 December 2010 |title=TeenAngels: Ganadores de Los Premios 40 Principales por segundo a\u00f1o consecutivo |work=Primicias Ya |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106021125/http://www.primiciasya.com/primicias/TeenAngels-Ganadores-de-Los-Premios-40-Principales-por-segundo-a241o-consecutivo-20101210-86248.html |archive-date=6 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and a Quiero Award, and three nominations for [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers|Carlos Gardel Awards]].<ref name=\"gardel1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/espectaculos/todos-los-nominados-a-los-premios-gardel-2009/20090401172238011766.html |title=Todos los nominados a los Premios Gardel 2009 |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Pronto |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102082506/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/espectaculos/todos-los-nominados-a-los-premios-gardel-2009/20090401172238011766.html |archive-date=2 November 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"gardel2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tododecris.net/2010/09/teen-angels-nominados-los-premios.html |title=Teen Angels nominados a los premios Gardel |work=Todo de Cris |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |date=21 September 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"gardel3\">{{cite news |url=http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/10/tennangels-nominado-a-los-premios-gardel-2011/ |work=[[Teen Angels]] |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Teen Angels nominado a los Premios Gardel 2011 |date=26 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101231221/http://teenangelsonline.com/2011/10/tennangels-nominado-a-los-premios-gardel-2011/ |archive-date=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nTeen Angels disbanded in 2012,<ref name=\"sonicomusica2\">{{cite news|accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.sonicomusica.com |url=http://www.sonicomusica.com/pop/teen-angels/noticias/se-separan-los-teen-angels/ |date=20 January 2012 |title=\u00bfSe separan los Teen Angels?}}</ref> and held its last concert on 11 October 2012 in [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]].<ref name=\"sonicomusica\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sonicomusica.com/pop/teen-angels/noticias/el-ultimo-show-de-teenangels-en-fotos/ |title=El \u00faltimo show de TeenAngels en fotos |date=11 October 2012 |work=www.sonicomusica.com |language=Spanish |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> ''Teen Angels, el adi\u00f3s'', a [[3D film|3D]] [[concert film]] about Teen Angels, was released in 2013 and marked the end of the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yups.tv/noticias/272/TeenAngels+en+3D |title=Se confirm\u00f3 el esperado regreso de Casi \u00c1ngeles |work=YUPS |year=2013 |accessdate=19 September 2013 |language=Spanish |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718055918/http://www.yups.tv/noticias/272/TeenAngels+en+3D |archive-date=18 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.infobae.com/2013/03/13/700757-los-teen-angels-hablaron-su-pelicula |title=Los Teen Angels hablaron de su pel\u00edcula |date=13 March 2013 |work=Infobae |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132013: ''Cuando me sonreis'', ''The Crucible'', ''Solamente vos'' and \"A Bailar\" ===\nAfter the end of ''Casi \u00c1ngeles'', Esp\u00f3sito adopted her nickname ''Lali'', by which she had been known to her friends and family, as her stage name.\n\n[[File:Lali Esp\u00f3sito 2012.jpg|200px|thumb|left||Lali Esp\u00f3sito in 2012]]\nIn 2011, Esp\u00f3sito starred on ''Cuando me sonre\u00eds'' (When you smile at me), a new television series by [[Tom\u00e1s Yankelevich]], opposite [[Facundo Arana]], [[Julieta D\u00edaz]] and [[Benjam\u00edn Rojas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1378923-lali-esposito-la-nueva-heroina|title=Lali Esposito, la nueva hero\u00edna|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2011/12/30/624588-finalizo-la-novela-cuando-me-sonreis-telefe|title=Finaliz\u00f3 la novela Cuando me sonre\u00eds por Telefe - Teleshow|publisher=}}</ref> The following year, Esp\u00f3sito portrayed [[Abigail Williams (Salem witch trials)|Abigail Williams]] in the Buenos Aires production of ''[[The Crucible]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/teatro/clasico-rejuvenecido_0_722327772.html|title=Las brujas de Salem: un cl\u00e1sico rejuvenecido|first=Mar\u00eda Ana|last=Rag|publisher=}}</ref> by [[Arthur Miller]], and made her film debut with ''La pelea de mi vida'' (''The Fight of My Life''), which also starred [[Mariano Mart\u00ednez (actor)|Mariano Mart\u00ednez]] and Federico Amador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/cine/mariano-martinez-esta-cordoba-hablo-con-vos|title=Mariano Mart\u00ednez est\u00e1 en C\u00f3rdoba, y habl\u00f3 con Vos|first=VOS - La Voz del|last=Interior|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.larazon.com.ar/cine/la-pelea-de-mi-vida_4850-p.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=26 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101011448/http://www.larazon.com.ar/cine/la-pelea-de-mi-vida_4850-p.html |archivedate=1 November 2014  }}</ref>\n\nSince January 2013, Esp\u00f3sito had starred the [[Pol-ka]] series ''[[Solamente Vos|Solamente vos]]'' (''Only You''), along with [[Adri\u00e1n Suar]] and [[Natalia Oreiro]], as Daniela, one of its leading characters.<ref name=\"televisionar\">{{cite news|url=http://television.com.ar/diario-online/minuto-a-minuto/noticias/190092/arrancan-las-grabaciones-de-solamente-vos/ |work=television.com.ar |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Arrancan las grabaciones de Solamente vos |year=2012}}</ref>\nIn 2013, Esp\u00f3sito announced she would release her first album as a solo artist,<ref name=\"elsol\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito lanza un proyecto musical como solista: \"Va a ser una locura\"|url=http://elsolonline.com/noticias/view/176731/lali-esposito-lanza-un-proyecto-musical-como-solista-va-a-ser-una-locura-|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130730061223/http://elsolonline.com/noticias/view/176731/lali-esposito-lanza-un-proyecto-musical-como-solista-va-a-ser-una-locura-|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 July 2013|date=7 July 2013|work=Diario El Sol}}</ref> titled ''A Bailar''.<ref name=\"dance\" /><ref name=\"videoclip\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish |title=La chica del videoclip|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/chica-videoclip_0_964703590.html|date=29 July 2013|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]}}</ref> When asked about the album's genre, she described it as mainly [[dance music|dance]] with [[hip hop]] influences.<ref name=\"elsol\" /><ref name=\"videoclip\" /><ref name=\"prontoclip\">{{cite news|accessdate=30 July 2013|language=Spanish|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito grab\u00f3 su primer videoclip, 'A Bailar': 'Estoy con todas las pilas puestas'|url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-grabo-primer-videoclip-bailar-llena-orgullo-tratar-ser-pionera-genero/20130729150036113585.html|date=29 July 2013|work=Pronto.com.ar|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804021546/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-grabo-primer-videoclip-bailar-llena-orgullo-tratar-ser-pionera-genero/20130729150036113585.html|archivedate=4 August 2013}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"A Bailar\", was released for [[Music download|digital download]] on her website on 5 August,<ref name=\"adulta\">{{cite journal|last1=S\u00e1nchez Mari\u00f1o|first1=Juan Cruz|date=6 August 2013|title=Hoy me siento m\u00e1s adulta y mandada|journal=Gente|url=http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=18050|issue=2507|pages=93\u201398|publisher=Atl\u00e1ntida|accessdate=9 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021822/http://www.gente.com.ar/nota.php?ID=18050|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> causing the website to crash because of a spike in traffic.<ref>{{cite news|language=Spanish |accessdate=9 August 2013|url=http://www.diariopopular.com.ar/notas/165349-lali-esposito-colapso-la-web-se-lanzo-como-solista|work=Diario Popular|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito colaps\u00f3 la web: se lanz\u00f3 como solista|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> On 2 September, Esp\u00f3sito presented the music video for \"A Bailar\" at the prominent [[La Trastienda Club]].<ref>{{cite journal|year=2013|title=A bailar con Lali y ONMAG|journal=OMAG|url=http://on-mag.net/site/?p=274|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923071858/http://on-mag.net/site/?p=274|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 September 2013|accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-presenta-video-clip-bailar-y-invita-acompanes/20130820114924115326.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito presenta el video clip de \"A bailar\" y te invita a que la acompa\u00f1es|date=27 August 2013|accessdate=27 August 2013|language=Spanish|work=Pronto|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823023003/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-presenta-video-clip-bailar-y-invita-acompanes/20130820114924115326.html|archivedate=23 August 2013}}</ref> \"A Bailar\" received 100,000 [[YouTube]] views on its release day, and the single entered the top 20 on [[iTunes]] Latin and iTunes Israel.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mundotkm.com/hot-news-114284-lali-esposito-rompe-record |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito rompe r\u00e9cord! |work=Mundo TKM |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |date=12 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911154019/http://www.mundotkm.com/hot-news-114284-lali-esposito-rompe-record |archive-date=11 September 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It also was popular in music charts and radio channels in [[Latin America]], [[Italy]] and [[Israel]].\n\n=== 2014\u20132015: ''A Bailar'', ''A los 40'' and ''Esperanza m\u00eda'' ===\nPrevious to the release of her debut album, Esp\u00f3sito released ''A Bailar EP'', which included the tracks \"A Bailar\", \"[[Asesina (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Asesina]]\" and \"[[Del Otro Lado (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Del Otro Lado]]\". The music video for \"Asesina\", the second single, was uploaded to the singer's official YouTube account on 10 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.infobae.com/2014/03/10/1549190-el-sensual-video-lali-esposito/ | title=El sensual video de Lali Esp\u00f3sito | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work= Teleshow |date=10 March 2014 |publisher= [[Infobae]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/poprock/asesina-el-infartante-nuevo-videoclip-de-lali-esposito-que-viene-cordoba | title=\"Asesina\": El infartante nuevo videoclip de Lali Esp\u00f3sito, que viene a C\u00f3rdoba | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work= Vos |date=11 March 2014 |publisher= La Voz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/nota/582423/ocio-espectaculos/lali-esposito-derrite-pantalla-asesina-nuevo-videoclip.html | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito, una \"Asesina\" que derrite la pantalla | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=10 March 2014 |publisher= La Gaceta}}</ref> The ten-track album ''[[A Bailar (Lali Esposito album)|A Bailar]]'' (English: ''Let's Dance'') was released on 21 March 2014.\n\nIn support of the album, Esp\u00f3sito embarked on the [[A Bailar Tour]] of Argentina, with several later stops in Uruguay, Chile, Spain, Italy and Israel.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.diarioveloz.com/notas/122349-lali-esposito-debuto-como-cantante-e-hizo-delirar-sus-fans | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito debut\u00f3 como cantante e hizo delirar a sus fans | accessdate=10 November 2016 | work=Diario Veloz | date=20 April 2014 | publisher=Cia. General de Producciones | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715114827/http://www.diarioveloz.com/notas/122349-lali-esposito-debuto-como-cantante-e-hizo-delirar-sus-fans | archive-date=15 July 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The tour earned  million in the first five shows at [[Teatro Opera|Teatro Opera Allianz]] and was later named the highest-grossing tour of 2015 in Argentina.<ref name=gross>{{cite web |url= http://www.perfil.com/mobile/?nota=/contenidos/2016/01/02/noticia_0079.html |title= El a\u00f1o en que Lali fue la reina |accessdate= 12 January 2016 |author= ''Perfil'' |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160202043843/http://www.perfil.com/mobile/?nota=%2Fcontenidos%2F2016%2F01%2F02%2Fnoticia_0079.html |archive-date= 2 February 2016 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=gross2>{{cite web |url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/argentinian-pop-and-tv-star-mariana-lali-esposito-visited-the-friends-of-zion-museum-and-received-a-special-friendship-award-300258585.html |title= Argentinian Pop and T.V. Star Mariana \"Lali\" Esp\u00f3sito Visited the Friends of Zion Museum and Received a Special Friendship Award |accessdate= 6 May 2016|work= [[PR Newswire]]}}</ref> Following the tour's success, more dates were added, and the tour concluded on 25 April 2016 at [[Menora Mivtachim Arena]], [[Tel Aviv]], after a total of 74 dates.\n\nIn May 2014, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the Peruvian film ''A los 40'', directed by Bruno Ascenzo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40|title=Actriz argentina Lali Esp\u00f3sito ser\u00e1 parte de la pel\u00edcula \u2018A los 40\u2019|date=27 September 2013|publisher=|access-date=5 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024110801/http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40|archive-date=24 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpp.com.pe/2013-09-27-lali-esposito-pronto-en-lima-para-promocionar-pelicula-a-los-40-noticia_634676.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito pronto en Lima para promocionar pel\u00edcula A los 40|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014 she starred in the Peruvian film \"A los 40\" (At 40), directed by Bruno Ascenzo.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40 | title=Actriz argentina Lali Esp\u00f3sito ser\u00e1 parte de la pel\u00edcula \u2018A los 40\u2019 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=23 September 2013 | work=La Rep\u00fablica | publisher=Grupo La Rep\u00fablica | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024110801/http://www.larepublica.pe/27-09-2013/actriz-argentina-lali-esposito-sera-parte-de-la-pelicula-a-los-40 | archive-date=24 October 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://rpp.pe/famosos/celebridades/lali-esposito-pronto-en-lima-para-promocionar-pelicula-a-los-40-noticia-634676 | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito pronto en Lima para promocionar pel\u00edcula A los 40 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=23 September 2013 | work=RPP Noticias |publisher= Grupo RPP}}</ref> In the same year, she became the first ever Argentine artist to win a [[Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Award]] in the [[United States]] for Best Latin Artist.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/mira/ella-es-la-unica-argentina-nominada-los-kids-choice-awards-2014 | title=Ella es la \u00fanica argentina nominada a los Kids\u2019 Choice Awards 2014 | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=2 February 2014 | work=Vos |publisher= La Voz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eleconomista.es/evasion/noticias/5851812/06/14/Cinco-divas-latinas-que-estan-por-llegar.html#.Kku8ZX3CQgintIs | title=Cinco divas latinas que est\u00e1n por llegar | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=13 June 2014 | work=El Economista |author=Iwan, M. |publisher= Ecoprensa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.prensariomusica.com/8618-3-Musica-trabajo-de-vanguardia-con-Lali-Esposito.note.aspx | title=3 M\u00fasica: trabajo de vanguardia con Lali Esp\u00f3sito | accessdate=10 November 2016 | date=28 April 2014 | work=Prensario M\u00fasica & Video |author=Iwan, M. |publisher= Editorial Prensario}}</ref>\n\nIn later 2014, the singer signed an exclusive publishing contract with [[Sony Music|Sony Music Entertainment Argentina]] and released \"[[Mil A\u00f1os Luz (Lali Esp\u00f3sito song)|Mil A\u00f1os Luz]]\" as the third single from ''A Bailar''. To celebrate her incorporation to Sony Music, Esp\u00f3sito released a deluxe edition of ''A Bailar'', which contained unpublished material including a new song, a remix, several video clips and a documentary of the tour. The album peaked at No. 3 in Uruguay and at No. 5 in Argentina, where it was certified gold a few days after its release.\n\nIn 2015, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the [[Pol-ka]] telenovela ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda]]'' (''My lovely hope'') alongside [[Mariano Martinez (actor)|Mariano Martinez]] as Julia \"Esperanza\" Albarrazin, a young woman who settles in a convent by posing as a novice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2014/09/08/1593283-como-sera-la-nueva-tira-que-protagonizaran-mariano-martinez-y-lali-esposito|title=C\u00f3mo ser\u00e1 la nueva tira que protagonizar\u00e1n Mariano Mart\u00ednez y Lali Esp\u00f3sito - Infoshow, Lali Esp\u00f3sito, David Bisbal, El Trece, Solamente vos, Telefe - Teleshow|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://urushow.com/se-avanza-en-la-ficcion-2015-de-lali-esposito/|title=Se avanza en la ficci\u00f3n 2015 de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe A Bailar Tour, continued to 2016 across national cities like [[Buenos Aires]], [[Rosario]], [[Mar del Plata]] and [[C\u00f3rdoba, Argentina|C\u00f3rdoba]] and included international stops in [[Uruguay]], [[Italy]], [[Spain]] and [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/divertite/musica/lali-esposito-trae-bailar-tour.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito trae su \"A bailar tour\" a Montevideo|first=|last=elpais.com.uy|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, the singer performed as the opening act for [[Ricky Martin]] show, held in [[Buenos Aires]] and in 2015 for [[Katy Perry]]'s [[The Prismatic World Tour]].\n\n=== 2016\u20132017: ''Soy'', ''Permitidos'' and collaborations ===\nEsp\u00f3sito released her second studio album ''[[Soy (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Soy]]'' on 20 May 2016, with ''[[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]'' newspaper writing that \"she takes one more step with this album, she experiments, shows herself as she is, and that is always valuable\".<ref name=soycr>{{cite news | url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/divertite/musica/sensacion-que-empieza-mostrar.html | title=Una sensaci\u00f3n que empieza a mostrar | accessdate=6 June 2016 | last= Fourment | first= Bel\u00e9n |date=30 May 2016 |newspaper= [[El Pa\u00eds (Uruguay)|El Pa\u00eds]]}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Intrusos en el espect\u00e1culo|Intrusos]]'', the singer referred to the album's title (''Soy'', English: ''I Am'') saying that \"it is called Soy because I am sharing the truth about what I think and feel. It is super personal\".<ref name=\"interview2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.infobae.com/2016/05/19/1812834-lali-esposito-conto-que-se-inspiro-mariano-martinez-algunos-temas-su-disco|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito cont\u00f3 que se inspir\u00f3 en Mariano Mart\u00ednez para algunos temas de su disco|publisher=[[Infobae]]|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016|language=Spanish|author=Ver\u00f3nica Guerman}}</ref> It sold more than 20,000 copies in Argentina in just three hours, being certified gold by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] (CAPIF).<ref name=\"interview3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1900809-las-lagrimas-de-emocion-de-lali-esposito-recibio-un-disco-de-oro-a-horas-de-lanzar-su-nuevo-album|title=Las l\u00e1grimas de emoci\u00f3n de Lali Esp\u00f3sito: recibi\u00f3 un disco de oro a horas de lanzar su nuevo \u00e1lbum|newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n]]|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=20 May 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref> The album debuted at No. 1 in Argentina, Uruguay and Israel, and at No. 5 and No. 6 in Italy and Spain, respectively. Its lead single, \"[[Soy (song)|Soy]]\", was released on 5 May and peaked at No. 5 on the ''[[Monitor Latino]]'' Argentina Top 20 chart and at No. 15 on the Ecuador Pop Songs chart. The second single, \"[[Boomerang (Lali song)|Boomerang]]\", was released on 5 September 2016. As of June 2017, its music video has been viewed more than 17 million times. ''Soy'' was listed as one of the best albums of 2016 by [[Billboard Brasil]] along with [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'', [[Lady Gaga]]'s ''[[Joanne (album)|Joanne]]'', [[J Balvin]]'s ''[[Energia (J Balvin album)|Energ\u00eda]]'' and others.<ref name=bilbra>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com.br/noticias/os-melhores-discos-de-2016-ate-agora/ | title=Os melhores discos de 2016 \u2013 At\u00e9 agora | accessdate=21 October 2016 | work= [[Billboard Brasil]] |date=26 July 2016 |publisher= [[IG Group]]}}</ref> In the same year, Esp\u00f3sito was featured on [[Abraham Mateo]]'s remix of the song \"Mueve\" from the re-issue of his album ''Are You Ready?'', on [[Brian Cross]] song \"Firestarter\" from his second studio album ''Darkness to Life'' and on [[Baby K (artist)|Baby K]]'s Spanish version of the international hit \"[[Roma-Bangkok]]\".\n\nIn August, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the [[romantic comedy]] film ''[[That's Not Cheating|Permitidos]]'' as Camila Boecchi alongside [[:es:Mart\u00edn Piroyansky|Mart\u00edn Piroyansky]]. The film, which was directed by [[:es:Ariel Winograd|Ariel Winograd]], grossed [[United States dollar|$]]1.9 million and has been viewed more than 370,000 times. The [[review aggregator]] website Todas Las Cr\u00edticas assigned the film a weighted average score of 67 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"tlc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.todaslascriticas.com.ar/pelicula/permitidos/criticas|title=Permitidos, cr\u00edticas|website=Todas Las Cr\u00edticas|accessdate=2 August 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe singer embarked on the [[Soy Tour]] of Latin America, Europe and Asia on 8 September. Reviews of the tour performances generally praised Esp\u00f3sito's vocals and the show's staging, which is said that \"fulfills the expectations of a nowadays international pop show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/musica/cinco-detalles-del-explosivo-show-de-lali-esposito|title=Cinco detalles del explosivo show de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|website=vos.lavoz.com.ar|accessdate=7 November 2016|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00f3sito's 2016 most notable accolades include Favorite Artist and Favorite Song for \"Soy\" at the [[:es:Anexo:Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards Argentina 2016|2016 Argentine Kids' Choice Awards]], [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Latin America South Act|Best Latin America South Act]] at the [[2016 MTV Europe Music Awards]], Argentine Artist of the Year at the 2016 MTV Millennial Awards, and nominations for Best Actress at both the 2016 [[Seoul International Drama Awards]] and the 2016 [[Mart\u00edn Fierro Awards]], where she won Best Theme Song for \"Tengo Esperanza\". The singer became the first ever Argentine artist to enter the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[List of Billboard Social 50 number-one artists|Social 50]] and [[List of number-one artists on the Billboard Artist 100|Artist 100]] charts, peaking at No. 2 and No. 69, respectively.\n\nIn July and November, respectively, Esp\u00f3sito released \"[[Una Na]]\" and \"Tu Novia\" as the first two singles from her upcoming third studio album.<ref name=\"2018BB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/7934094/argentina-lali-esposito-interview|title=Lali Esposito Talks Getting Noticed in 'The Age of Song': Interview|date=18 August 2017|accessdate=18 August 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|first=Santiago|last=Torres}}</ref> The former one rapidly reached the top of the [[Monitor Latino|Argentine National Songs]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Argentina/Nacionalidad/20170911|publisher=[[Monitor Latino]]|accessdate=18 September 2017|title=Top 20 Nacional Argentina \u2013 Del 11 al 17 de Septiembre, 2017|language=Spanish|date=11 September 2017}}</ref> In November, the siner kicked off her second concert tour in support of ''Soy'', titled [[Lali en Vivo]], with two sold-out shows at the [[Estadio Luna Park|Luna Park Arena]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/fama/lali-esposito-agrega-nueva-funcion-luna-park_0_Hkjf-c9UZ.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito agrega nueva funci\u00f3n en el Luna Park|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn.com]]|date=29 July 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nIn that period of time Lali was the most popular in the global ranking of different topics in multilingual Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wikirank.net/en/Lali%20Esp%C3%B3sito | access-date=2019-08-13 | website=WikiRank | title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito | archive-date=13 August 2019 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20190813103520/https://wikirank.net/en/Lali%20Esp%C3%B3sito | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===2018\u20132019: ''Brava'', ''The Accused'' and ''Talento FOX''===\nFrom January to July, the singer continued with her [[Lali en Vivo]] tour, which visited [[Peru]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], [[Israel]] and the [[United States]]. In February, Esp\u00f3sito was featured on [[Mau y Ricky]] and [[Karol G]]'s [[Mi Mala#Remix version|remix of \"Mi Mala\"]], with [[Becky G]] and [[Leslie Grace]], and, in May, she teamed up with [[CD9 (band)|CD9]] and [[Ana Mena]] for the remix of \"Prohibido\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8099267/becky-g-karol-g-leslie-grace-lali-mau-y-ricky-mi-mala-remix|title=Becky G, Karol G, Leslie Grace & Lali Are Squad Goals in Mau y Ricky's 'Mi Mala (Remix)' Video Premiere|author=Billboard Staff|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=12 February 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> Preceded by the release of \"[[100 Grados]]\", in April, and \"Besarte Mucho\", in July, the singer released her third studio album, ''[[Brava (Lali Esp\u00f3sito album)|Brava]]'', in August 2018. One week after, the album received a gold certification by the [[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]] for having sold ten thousand copies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cmtv.com.ar/noticias/noticia_completa.php?bnid=2318&nid=20041&artista=Lali_Esposito&titulo=Ser_Genuina_-_Lali_Esposito |title=Ser Genuina - Lali Esp\u00f3sito |website=CMTV.com.AR |language=Spanish |accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref> Esp\u00f3sito embarked on the [[Brava Tour]] immediately after the album release, on 23 August, with two sold-out shows at the [[Estadio Luna Park|Luna Park Arena]].<ref name=\"Brava\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmtv.com.ar/noticias/noticia_completa.php?bnid=2318&nid=21200&artista=Lali_Esposito&titulo=#BravaTour_-_La_gira_de_Lali|title=#BravaTour - La gira de Lali|website=[[:es:Canal CM|CMTV]]|accessdate=19 April 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref> The album was succeeded by the release of the singles \"[[Sin Querer Queriendo]]\" with Mau y Ricky, and \"[[Caliente (Lali song)|Caliente]]\", with Brazilian [[drag queen]] [[Pabllo Vittar]]. The singles peaked at number 14 and 51 on the ''[[Billboard Argentina|Billboard]]'' [[Argentina Hot 100]], respectively.\n\nOutside of recording music, Esp\u00f3sito made her debut as a judge on [[Fox Latin America]]'s original television [[talent show]] ''[[Talento FOX]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/fama/lali-esposito-nueva-sorpresiva-faceta-laboral_0_SJHE6BamG.html|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito tiene una nueva y sorpresiva faceta laboral|work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]]|date=5 January 2017|accessdate=5 January 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://television.com.ar/lali-esposito-diego-torres-y-wisin-juntos-por-talento-fox/78592|title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito, Diego Torres y Wisin juntos por Talento FOX|accessdate=8 May 2018|date=4 May 2018|website=television.com.ar|language=Spanish}}</ref> In September, Esp\u00f3sito starred in the film ''[[The Accused (2018 film)|The Accused]]'', as Dolores Dreier, a girl accused of killing her best friend.<ref name=\"2018BB\" /> The film was directed by Gonzalo Tobal and is made its premiere in the main competition of the [[75th Venice International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/salio-el-primer-poste/20180418141324279705.html|title=Sali\u00f3 el primer p\u00f3ster de la nueva pel\u00edcula de Lali Esp\u00f3sito|website=pronto.com.ar|last=Cuschnir|first=Tatiana|language=Spanish|date=18 April 2018|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nLali started off 2019 performing in [[Times Square]], [[New York City]], for [[Univision]]'s [[Feliz! (Univision program)|Countdown Feliz 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.axs.com/lali-gives-historic-performance-in-times-square-for-new-year-s-eve-cou-135809|title=Lali gives historic performance in Times Square for New Year's Eve countdown|date=3 January 2019|accessdate=4 January 2019|website=[[AXS (company)|axs.com]]|first=Lucas|last=Villa}}</ref> Early that year, the music video for \"[[Lindo Pero Bruto]]\", her collaboration with [[Thal\u00eda]], was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8495715/thalia-lali-lindo-pero-bruto-video|title=Thal\u00eda and Lali Drop Candy-Colored 'Lindo Pero Bruto' Video: Watch|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=30 January 2019|accessdate=30 January 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> The singer received notable nominations for the [[Premio Lo Nuestro]] and the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]].<ref name=\"Nods\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8492678/premio-lo-nuestro-2019-nominations-full-list|title=Premio Lo Nuestro 2019 Nominations: Natti Natasha, J Balvin, Bad Bunny Lead Nods|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=8 January 2019|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8497865/ozuna-leads-2019-billboard-latin-music-awards-finalists-complete-list|title=Ozuna Leads 2019 Billboard Latin Music Awards Finalists: Complete List of Nominees|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=12 February 2019|date=12 February 2019|first=Leila|last=Cobo}}</ref> During the first months of the year, Lali continued touring with ''Brava'', which was certified four times platinum in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/gossip/con-musica-y-actuacion-lali-esposito-busca-romper-prejuicios-3644858.html|title=Con m\u00fasica y actuaci\u00f3n, Lali Esp\u00f3sito busca romper prejuicios|work=[[:es:El Sol de M\u00e9xico|El Sol de M\u00e9xico]]|accessdate=21 May 2019|date=20 May 2019|first=Adolfo|last=L\u00f3pez|language=Spanish}}</ref> For the [[21st Annual Gardel Awards]], Lali won three awards, the most of the night, in the categories for Best Female Pop Album and Best Cover Design for ''Brava'', and Song of the Year for \"Sin Querer Queriendo\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8511545/lali-sebastian-yatra-bad-bunny-latin-notas|title=Lali Wins Big at Premios Gardel|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=15 May 2019|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the last months of 2019, Lali took her Brava Tour to Europe, the United States and the [[Rock in Rio]] music festival in [[Brazil]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8528386/latin-notas-lali-tour-dates-farruko-en-letra-de-otro|title=This Week in Latin Notas: Lali's Tour Dates, HBO Latino Presents 'Farruko: En Letra de Otro' & More|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=27 August 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Suzette|last=Fernandez}}</ref> where she also received a gold certification for \"Caliente.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://portalpopline.com.br/na-casa-do-popline-lali-recebe-certificado-de-ouro-por-caliente-parceria-com-pabllo-vittar/|title=Na Casa do POPline, Lali recebe certificado de Ouro por \u201cCaliente\u201d, parceria com Pabllo Vittar|first=Kavad|last=Madeiros|website=POPline|accessdate=13 November 2019|date=29 September 2019|language=Portuguese}}</ref> It was in these months that Lali officially kicked off her fouth music era: in October, she released her fourth studio album's lead single, \"[[Laligera]]\", which peaked at number 24 on the ''Billboard'' Argentina Hot 100;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8532708/favorite-lali-music-video-poll|title=What's Your Favorite Lali Music Video? Vote!|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=10 October 2019|accessdate=13 November 2019|first=Jessica|last=Roiz}}</ref> in November, she released \"Como As\u00ed\", which features boy band [[CNCO]], with whom she co-hosted the [[2019 Premios Juventud]] ceremony back in July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8543096/viva-friday-lali-cnco-j-alvarez|title=Viva Friday Playlist: Lali Joins Forces With CNCO, J Alvarez Releases 'La Fama Que Camina Vol. 2' & More|first=Jessica|last=Roiz|date=8 November 2019|accessdate=8 November 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/8512499/premios-juventud-2019-nominees-list|title=Maluma, Bad Bunny and Anuel AA Lead Premios Juventud Nominations: Full List|first=Suzette|last=Fernandez|date=21 May 2019|accessdate=13 November 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n== Other work ==\n=== Modeling ===\nEsp\u00f3sito has been a spokesperson for numerous brands, either independently or with her [[Teen Angels]] bandmates.<ref name=\"cocacola\"/> Her first commercial was for the children's fashion label MCbody Jeans. In 2007, she signed an exclusive contract with the Argentine [[lingerie]] brand Promesse,<ref name=\"univision\">{{cite news |url=http://foro.univision.com/t5/Erreway/Mariana-Esposito-tambien-cara-de-Promesse/td-p/152514631 |work=foro.univision.com |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |title=Mariana Esposito tambien cara de Promesse |date=23 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130205034818/http://foro.univision.com/t5/Erreway/Mariana-Esposito-tambien-cara-de-Promesse/td-p/152514631 |archivedate=5 February 2013  }}</ref> and she has done most of her photo sessions with [[Luisana Lopilato]].<ref name=\"solocristv2\">{{cite news |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2009/08/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |title=Fotos de Mariana Esp\u00f3sito en Promesse Primavera/Verrano 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012154116/http://www.solocristv.net/2009/08/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |archivedate=12 October 2016  }}</ref><ref name=\"solocristv1\">{{cite news |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2009/03/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |title=Fotos de Mariana Esp\u00f3sito en Promesse Oto\u00f1o/Invierno 2009 |year=2009 |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012191306/http://www.solocristv.net/2009/03/fotos-de-mariana-esposito-en-promesse.html |archivedate=12 October 2016  }}</ref> In 2009, Esp\u00f3sito and [[Juan Pedro Lanzani|Peter Lanzani]] did a special promotion for KEFF body spray for the Israeli market.<ref name=\"lali\">{{cite news |url=http://www.marianae.com.ar/marianaesposito/index.php |title=Mariana Esp\u00f3sito \u2013 La p\u00e1gina |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=www.marianae.com.ar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091026174951/http://www.marianae.com.ar/marianaesposito/index.php |archivedate=26 October 2009  }}</ref> Since 2011, she has been the spokesperson for the lingerie brand Lara Teens. In 2014 she starred in a commercial for hair conditioner Biokur in Uruguay and a commercial for feminine wipes company Carefree in Argentina.\n[[File:Lali Esp\u00f3sito (logo).png|thumb|right|150px|Esp\u00f3sito's logo as a solo artist.]]\nEsp\u00f3sito has been the cover model for magazines such as ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''Galore'', ''Caras'', ''OnMag'', ''Las Rosas'', ''Twees'', ''[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]'', ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'', ''Luz'', ''Viva'', ''Watt'', ''Nueva'', ''Upss'' and ''Fack'', among others.\n\n=== Entrepreneurship ===\nOn 21 September 2013, Esp\u00f3sito launched her own line of eponymous [[perfume]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clarin.com/espectaculos/podes-oler_0_969503180.html |work=[[Clar\u00edn (Argentine newspaper)|Clar\u00edn]] |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Tambi\u00e9n me pod\u00e9s oler |date=6 August 2013 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-lanzara-su-perfume/20130711090929112057.html |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Lali Esp\u00f3sito lanzar\u00e1 su perfume |date=18 September 2013 |work=Pronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715013542/http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/famosos/lali-esposito-lanzara-su-perfume/20130711090929112057.html |archivedate=15 July 2013  }}</ref> In 2018, she launched an item of clothing for [[47 Street]].\n\n=== Philanthropy ===\nIn May 2010, Esp\u00f3sito and her [[Teen Angels]] bandmates participated in an action organized by the Biodiversity Foundation on the occasion of the [[World Biodiversity Day]] and raised awareness of the importance of preserving biodiversity.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fundacion-biodiversidad.es/inicio/noticias/noticias/113354-concierto-bravo-por-la-tierra |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |title=Concierto \"Bravo por la Tierra\" |date=19 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102222754/http://www.fundacion-biodiversidad.es/inicio/noticias/noticias/113354-concierto-bravo-por-la-tierra |archivedate=2 November 2013  }}</ref> In 2013, Esp\u00f3sito supported Best Buddies International, a [[non-governmental organization]] that promotes social inclusion and employment of people with intellectual disabilities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://infolaliesposito.blogspot.com.ar/2013/08/pineiro-prod-y-lali-esposito-juntos.html |title=Pi\u00f1eiro Prod y Lali Esp\u00f3sito juntos acompa\u00f1ando a Best Buddies |date=16 August 2013 |language=Spanish |accessdate=19 September 2013 |work=infolaliesposito.blogspot.com.ar}}</ref> In 2014 she participated in the concert at [[Teatro Opera]] by the Guest Foundation that marked the 25th anniversary of the fight against [[HIV]]. In 2015 she starred in the solidarity campaign \"Flood, what are we doing?\" for the foundation to help flood victims in the city of C\u00f3rdoba.\n\nEsp\u00f3sito has been named \"Godmother\" of Dono x Vos foundation, a nongovernmental organization dedicated to raising awareness about [[organ donation]]. In 2017, the singer joined forces with Red Solidaria and [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate Football Club]] to launch a solidarity campaign named \"Amor Es Presente\". The campaign received donated toys that were later gifted to more than twelve-thousand children as part of [[Christmas]] festivities.\n\n===Activism===\nEsp\u00f3sito has proclaimed herself in favor of the [[voluntary termination of pregnancy]] in Argentina, where [[Abortion in Argentina|abortion]] is still illegal. The bill proposed that an abortion may be performed during the first 14 weeks of pregnancy, with no requirements other than the woman's desire. Esp\u00f3sito is part of a [[Feminism in Argentina|Feminist]] group of Argentine actresses and singers, such as [[Jimena Bar\u00f3n]], [[Griselda Siciliani]], [[Carla Peterson (actress)|Carla Peterson]], [[Florencia Pe\u00f1a]] and [[Florencia de la V]], among others. Although the bill was approved by the [[Argentine Chamber of Deputies|Chamber of Deputies]], it was rejected by the [[Argentine Senate|Senate]]. Esp\u00f3sito has expressed her position in major events such as the 48th annual [[Martin Fierro Awards]], in which she lifted up a green scarf, sign of the pro-legal abortion movement in Argentina, at the end of her performance. Moreover, in her [[Brava Tour]], she dedicates her song \"Tu Revoluci\u00f3n\" to the movement, while the stage lights turn green and green hearts are displayed in the screens.\n\n== Personal life ==\nLali is the daughter of Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Riera, who road-manages her tour, and Carlos Esp\u00f3sito, a [[Association football|football]] coach. She has two siblings, Patricio Esp\u00f3sito and Ana Laura Esp\u00f3sito. She was born and grew up in Parque Patricios. After high school, they moved to Banfield.<ref name=\"lali\"/><ref name=\"solocristv3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.solocristv.net/2008/08/biografia-y-entrevista-mariana-esposito.html |accessdate=24 December 2012 |language=Spanish |work=Solo Cris TV |title=Biograf\u00eda y entrevista a Mariana Esp\u00f3sito |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910203657/http://www.solocristv.net/2008/08/biografia-y-entrevista-mariana-esposito.html |archive-date=10 September 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> She currently resides in [[Palermo, Buenos Aires]].<ref name=\"solocristv3\"/>\nShe has Italian ancestors from her father's lineage.\n\nFrom 2006 to 2010, Esp\u00f3sito dated her ''[[Chiquititas]]'' and ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]'' co-star [[Peter Lanzani]].<ref>http://www.pronto.com.ar/articulo/informacion/peter-lanzani-y-lali-espsito-nos-amamos-como-cualquier-hijo-de-vecino/20081209171838077164.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, the 23-year-old Esp\u00f3sito was ranked third sexiest Argentine woman in a survey reported by [[Radio Continental]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.continental.com.ar/noticias/espectaculos/jesica-cirio-encabeza-una-lista-de-las-mujeres-mas-sexys-de-argentina/20140318/nota/2134949.aspx |title=J\u00e9sica Cirio encabeza una lista de las mujeres m\u00e1s sexys de Argentina (J\u00e9sica Cirio tops a list of the sexiest women in Argentina) |publisher=[[Radio Continental]] |date=2014-03-18 |access-date=2020-03-25 |language=Spanish}}</ref> That same year, she was ranked the 27th-most influential Spanish-speaking celebrity on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yosoyred.com/2014/03/las-100-cuentas-de-twitter-mas-influyentes-en-espanol-usando-analisis-de-redes/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317232153/http://yosoyred.com/2014/03/las-100-cuentas-de-twitter-mas-influyentes-en-espanol-usando-analisis-de-redes/|title=las 100 cuentas de twitter mas influyentes en espa\u00f1ol usando an\u00e1lisis de redes.|archivedate=17 March 2014 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{Main|Lali Esp\u00f3sito videography}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Rinc\u00f3n de Luz]]''\n| Malena \"Coco\" Cabrera\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2004-2005\n| ''[[Floricienta]]''\n| Roberta Espinosa\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Chiquititas#Chiquititas Sin Fin|Chiquititas Sin Fin]]''\n| Agustina Ross\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2007-2010\n| ''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]''\n| Marianella Rinaldi\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Cuando Me Sonre\u00eds''\n| Milagros Rivas\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Dulce amor (telenovela)|Dulce Amor]]''\n| Ana\n| Episode 36\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Solamente Vos]]''\n| Daniela Cousteau\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2015-2016\n| ''[[Esperanza m\u00eda|Esperanza M\u00eda]]''\n| Julia Albarrac\u00edn / Esperanza\n| Lead role\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Showmatch]]''\n| Makeup seller\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Diary (TV series)|MTV Diary]]''\n| Herself\n| Special\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[:es:Sandro de Am\u00e9rica (serie de televisi\u00f3n)|Sandro de Am\u00e9rica]]''\n| [[:es:Tita Russ|Reyna Ross]]\n| Episodes: \"El \u00daltimo Hombre en La Tierra\" and \"Todo Va a Estallar\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Talento FOX]]''\n| Judge\n| [[Talent show]]\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Sky Rojo]]''\n|\n| Lead role (Netflix)\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''La pelea de mi vida''\n| Bel\u00e9n Est\u00e9vez\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Teen Angels, El Adi\u00f3s''\n| Herself\n| Concert film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''A Los 40'' \n| Melissa\n| Main role